@EndNode

@Node "Required Files" "iceterm.guide/Required Files"
@Next "The ARP Library"
@Prev "Quick Start"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Required files
==============

   Since IceTERM is freely distributed I do not have any direct control
over the files you have received(1).  A basic installation requires two
programs: IceTERM and IceOLR  (see @{"Batch SIGs" Link "Batch SIGs"}).  Strictly speaking
IceTERM is the only one that is required, but IceOLR is used to read
messages off-line and to manage the downloaded message base. IceTERM
may also be distributed in a package called VBBSDisk, this package
includes a number of other support programs (written in CanDo by Ian
Gunn) and is meant to be unarchived onto a disk to build a complete
terminal environment for new users (it was originally assembled for The
Amiga Users of Calgary Society(2)).

   As well as the programs (IceTERM and IceOLR) you will need their
icon files.  These programs are intended to be run from the WorkBench
and take a number of configuration parameters from their icons, if you
run them from the CLI you still need the icons, but you can hide the
icons in @{b}S:@{ub} or @{b}C:@{ub} if you want.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Of course if you get a copy of IceTERM directly from me this
should not be a problem, see See @{"Direct Updates" Link "Direct Updates"}, for how to do this.

   (2)  AMUC is one of the largest and most active Amiga Users groups
in North America.


@EndNode

@Node "The ARP Library" "iceterm.guide/The ARP Library"
@Next "Setting up"
@Prev "Required Files"
@Toc "Quick Start"

The ARP library
===============

   IceTERM uses the ARP(1) Library to provide the file requester if you
are running AmigaDOS 1.3 or older.  The ARP Library is a file called
@{b}Arp.Library@{ub} that should be in your @{b}LIBS:@{ub} directory. If it is not
present and you are not using at least AmigaDOS 2.0 IceTERM will
display a warning requester and exit.  To install it, copy the
@{b}Arp.Library@{ub} file from the distribution archive into your @{b}LIBS:@{ub}
directory.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  ARP is the AmigaDOS Replacement Project, a set of CLI
replacement commands developed by various Amiga Programmers and made
available as freely distributable software.  It was released twice,
once for AmigaDOS 1.2 and then for AmigaDOS 1.3.


@EndNode

@Node "Setting up" "iceterm.guide/Setting up"
@Next "Basic Tool types"
@Prev "The ARP Library"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Setting up IceTERM
==================

   First you must unpack the distribution archive.  IceTERM is usually
distributed in an @{b}LZH@{ub} format archive.  Unpacking this type of archive
is quite simple, just use @{b}CD@{ub} to go to the directory where the archive
is located(1) and type a command like:

     lharc x IceTERMv119.LZH

   Then to set up IceTERM you must drag it (by its icon) from the
directory where the distribution archive was unpacked to the place you
wish to keep it.  At this point, if you are running a pre-2.0 version
of AmigaDOS, you should also copy the @{b}Arp.Library@{ub} to your @{b}LIBS:@{ub}
directory if you do not have ARP installed (see @{"The ARP Library" Link "The ARP Library"}).

   Next you need to edit the WorkBench tool types array for IceTERM.
What's a tool type array you ask?  This is a much under-utilized
feature of the Amiga's WorkBench environment. To access it you single
click on the IceTERM icon and then select the @{b}Information...@{ub} menu item
from WorkBench's @{b}Icons@{ub} menu (or @{b}Info@{ub} from WorkBench's menu under
AmigaDOS 1.3 and earlier).  WorkBench will then open a window
summarizing information about the icon(2), and within that window is
the string gadget(3) you can use to edit the tool type array.

   If you are running AmigaDOS 2.0 or higher you can install IceTERM by
just dragging it's icon to where you want to keep it.  Then when you
first double click it, IceTERM will prompt you for the additional
configuration information it needs (such as user name and password).
T{No Value For "ERM"} distribution archives often contain additional
icons for dialing specific BBS systems, these are project icons which
have their default tool set to IceTERM.  If you start IceTERM by double
clicking one of these project icons any additional configuration
information will be saved within in the project icon.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This example assumes that the archive is called: @{b}IceTERMv119.LZH@{ub}
your copy might be called something else entirely.

   (2)  An icon represents a program, data file, disk or directory, so
this information window really displays information about the program,
data file, disk or directory.

   (3)  A place you can type in some text, edit it, and then tell the
Amiga to use it by hitting the return key.


@EndNode

@Node "Basic Tool types" "iceterm.guide/Basic Tool types"
@Next "Basic Serial Port"
@Prev "Setting up"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Basic tool types
================

   The purpose of the tool type array is to pass user configuration
information to programs that are run from the WorkBench.  This Amiga
feature has not been extensively used by other programs, so it may be
unfamiliar at first.

   Once the information window is displaying the IceTERM icon you can
scroll through the list with the little arrows to the left of the
string gadget.  These are the tool types you should pay attention to
(in descending order of importance):

@{b}USER=@{ub}
     your name (up to 63 characters(1)), this will be used to create
     your account when you log onto the BBS,

@{b}PASSWORD=@{ub}
     your password(2) (up to 63 characters), since you do not have to
     type this in, choose a nice long one,

@{b}BAUD=@{ub}
     the baud rate of your modem, for older modems this might be set to
     @{b}1200@{ub} or @{b}2400@{ub}, if you have an MNP or v42 capable modem this should
     be set to at least @{b}9600@{ub} and if you have one of the more expensive
     V.32, V.32bis, HST, v.fast or v34(3) modems you will probably want
     to use @{b}19200@{ub} or @{b}38400@{ub}, some serial boards and modems will even
     support higher baud rates(4).  @{i}Note that you should not use @{b}14400@{ub}
     or @{b}28800@{ub} as these are the modem's internal speeds, they are not
     speeds supported by the modem's serial port (and will not work,
     even if your serial board happens to support them),@{ui}

@{b}HANDSHAKE=@{ub}
     the handshaking you use between computer and modem, this should be
     set to one of @{b}none@{ub} or @{b}7wire@{ub}, if it is not present then the system
     defaults to @{b}none@{ub}.  If you use a baud rate higher than @{b}2400@{ub} you
     should use the @{b}7wire@{ub} setting and you should pay attention to how
     your modem is set up,

@{b}EDITOR=@{ub}
     the editor you wish to use, this is the editor you will use to
     compose messages etc.,

@{b}MESSROOT=@{ub}
     the directory for downloaded messages, these messages can be read
     and replied to by the off-line reader @{b}IceOLR@{ub},

@{b}EMAILROOT=@{ub}
     the directory for email and user lists, do not put this in @{b}RAM:@{ub} as
     IceTERM will have to redownload some data each time you use it,

@{b}DOWNDIR=@{ub}
     the directory where your downloads will go, this may be overridden
     from within IceTERM if you want,

@{b}TEMPDIR=@{ub}
     the directory where temporary files will be made, this defaults to
     @{b}T:@{ub} which should be safe for most people,

@{b}KEEPFILE=@{ub}
     the name of the file to save useful messages in, put this on a
     floppy or hard drive so that the kept information is not lost when
     you reboot,

@{b}SCRIPT=@{ub}
     the name of the script file you want to run, this is optional in
     certain circumstances.

   There are a number of additional tool types that may show up in the
IceTERM icon, these are used to store initial size and position
information of the various windows that IceTERM opens.  The complete
reference to all the tool types of IceTERM appears in a later chapter
(see @{"Tool types" Link "Tool types"}).

   It should be noted that the tool type names (the part to the left of
the equals sign) should normally be capitalized(5), and capitalization
to the right of the equal sign is not significant.  Also, the order in
which tool types are listed is not significant, except when there are
duplicate entries, in which case the tool type that is closer to the
end of the list will be used.

   The first tool types to set up are the @{b}USER@{ub} and @{b}PASSWORD@{ub} entries,
these are used to specify your user name and password. The IceTERM
program will automatically send these to the BBS(6) in order to log you
in.  If you do not already have an account there the BBS will create
one for you.  Both of these entries are limited to 63 characters(7) and
capitilization is not important--that is, @{b}Fred@{ub} is the same as @{b}fred@{ub}.
For example you might have:

     USER=John Doe
     PASSWORD=OnE oF MaNy SuCh!

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  You should avoid the use of special characters, punctuation
marks and spaces within your user name, as these characters may be
forbidden by, or cause problems with, various email systems (such as
FidoNet and the Internet).  Its best to stick with a short version of
your real name (say 20 characters or less) with no spaces within it
(substituting the underscore or period for spaces will usually work).

   (2)  If you do not include the password tool type IceTERM will
prompt you for your password each time you log into the BBS, this is
sometimes useful to keep your account to yourself.

   (3)  At the time of writing these were not shipping, but they were
expected to transfer upto about 30000 baud.

   (4)  @{b}57600@{ub} and @{b}115200@{ub} baud are the most common very high speeds

   (5)  This is optional now, but it is the standard recomended in
Commodore's style guide.

   (6)  If you connect to more than one IceBBS based BBS and wish to
have a different name or password depending on the BBS you can specify
these in the script file (see @{"Script commands" Link "Script commands"}) that dials you into the
systems.  Or you can use different project icons for each BBS you call.

   (7)  If you plan to use FidoNet email you should limit your name to
less than 30 characters.


@EndNode

@Node "Basic Serial Port" "iceterm.guide/Basic Serial Port"
@Next "Your Editor"
@Prev "Basic Tool types"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Basic serial port
=================

   The @{b}BAUD@{ub} tool type is used to set the baud rate between IceTERM and
your modem.  If this item is not specified IceTERM will use the baud
rate that you have set in the Amiga Preferences tool.  Most current
modems are 1200 or 2400 baud, the newer MNP and v42 modems can use 9600
baud, and the more advanced (and expensive) modems can use 19200 and
38400 baud.  @{i}If you specify a baud rate higher than 2400 you normally
must also select @{b}7wire@{ub} mode for the handshaking, otherwise you will
encounter a reduction in transmission speed or errors@{ui}.  For example you
might specify:

     BAUD=2400

   The @{b}HANDSHAKE@{ub} tool type is used to select the type of handshaking
that is to be used between IceTERM and your modem.  If no handshaking
tool type is set in the IceTERM icon then IceTERM will use the default
you have set up in the Amiga's Serial Preferences(1) editor.

   There are two methods of handshaking that can be used with IceTERM,
either @{b}none@{ub} or @{b}7wire@{ub} (2).  The first (@{b}none@{ub}) is quite simple, if no
handshaking is used then there is no way for the computer to tell the
modem to slow down when its buffers get full (or visa versa).  This is
generally quite safe for 1200 and 2400 baud modems; however, it is @{i}not@{ui}
safe for MNP, v42, V.32, HST or higher speed modems.  To disable
handshaking use:

     HANDSHAKE=none

There are some very old modems (usually 1200 baud modems) that do not
support the @{b}7wire@{ub} mode of handshaking, for these you must use the @{b}none@{ub}
mode.

   The @{b}7wire@{ub} mode is usually to be preferred over @{b}none@{ub}; however, there
are some complications, you must have a serial cable that supports the
additional wires (this is usually the case with prefabricated serial
cables these days) and your modem will almost certainly need to be told
to turn on the handshaking (look for commands relating to CTS/RTS or
seven wire handshaking and see @{"Modem settings" Link "Modem settings"}).  To enable handshaking
set:

     HANDSHAKE=7wire

If you have a modem that connects to your Amiga at 9600 baud or higher
it is @{i}essential@{ui} that the hardware handshaking is used.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Preferences will allow you to select among three types of
handshaking: none, XON/XOFF and CTS/RTS. The CTS/RTS type is the same
as @{b}7wire@{ub}. The XON/XOFF type cannot be used by IceTERM.  If XON/XOFF is
specified IceTERM will ignore it and fall back to @{b}none@{ub}.

   (2)  Either @{b}7wire@{ub} or just @{b}7@{ub} can be used in the tool type


@EndNode

@Node "Your Editor" "iceterm.guide/Your Editor"
@Next "Message Bases"
@Prev "Basic Serial Port"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Selecting your editor
=====================

   The @{b}EDITOR@{ub} tool type is used to specify the name of the editor you
want to use to edit the messages you are posting or replying to on a
IceBBS system.  This will default to the infamous @{b}Ed@{ub}, simply because it
is standard on every Amiga system.  There are two possible problems you
will encounter here, the first is that the editor you are using should
be in your @{b}C:@{ub} directory.  The second is that some editors (CygnusEd and
Az are good examples) @{i}detach@{ui} from the CLI they are run from.  By this I
mean they always appear to be started with a command line like @{b}run az@{ub}
even if you just typed @{b}az@{ub}.  These editors can still be used so long as
you remember to save(1) your messages and close the editor @{i}before@{ui} you
answer the @{b}Do you want to post?@{ub} requester.  For example you might use:

     EDITOR=dme

   If you are running IceTERM under AmigaDOS 2.0 or higher then the
custom screen that IceTERM opens will be a public screen.  This screen
has the name @{b}ICEBBS-TERM@{ub}.  If you use an editor that supports public
screens you should be able to get the editor to appear on IceTERM's
public screen.  Different editors will probably use different ways of
finding out what screen to use.  In the case of @{b}Ed@{ub} you can use:

     EDITOR=ed window "RAW:0/0/640/200/Edit/SCREENICEBBS-TERM"

Note that you cannot put a space between the word @{b}SCREEN@{ub} and the
@{b}ICEBBS-TERM@{ub} name.  Also note that capitalization is significant here!

   Other editors exist that support public screens, as I learn of them
I will add the appropriate command to this section, if you use one that
is not listed here please send me the tool type that you use.

   The XDME editor from Fish Disk 776 uses public screens, the tool type
would be:

     EDITOR=xdme -ps ICEBBS-TERM

this editor has the odd feature that if you already have it running
elsewhere on your system it will not fire up a second copy of itself
and so, in this case, its window will always open on the screen the
first copy was running on.  Newer versions of @{b}xdme@{ub} add the @{b}-n@{ub} switch to
prevent this.

   TurboText, from Oxxi, supports public screens.  If you use TurboText
as your editor, the tool type would be:

     EDITOR=TTX SCREEN ICEBBS-TERM

   GoldED, a shareware product, supports also public screens, a number
of people have reported that it works quite well with IceTERM.

   If your editor does not support public screens and you are running
under AmigaDOS 2.0 you can force your editor to open on IceTERM's
screen by re-enabling the hack that older versions of IceTERM used
previously (and the current IceTERM's still use when running under
AmigaDOS 1.3).  You do this by including the @{b}WBHACK@{ub} (see @{"The editor" Link "The editor"})
tool type in the icon.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  When IceTERM starts the editor it tells it to edit a file
called something like: @{b}tempfile@{ub}, most editors have a feature which will
automatically save under this original name.  This is the save method
you want to use, since that is the file that IceTERM will load to send
to the BBS.


@EndNode

@Node "Message Bases" "iceterm.guide/Message Bases"
@Next "Your mail box"
@Prev "Your Editor"
@Toc "Quick Start"

The message bases
=================

   The @{b}MESSROOT@{ub} tool type is used to specify the name of a directory
you want to use to store the messages you download from an IceBBS
system with the BatchSIGs function.  This directory will be used to
store a lot of files, it should go on a disk where there is plenty of
space.  If you are using a floppy based system you might want to name
the disk @{b}Messages@{ub} and then specify:

     MESSROOT=Messages:

then IceTERM will prompt you to insert the @{b}Messages@{ub} disk whenever it is
needed.

   You should not store any other files within the directory specified
by @{b}MESSROOT@{ub} as IceTERM and IceOLR read, write and delete lots of files
in this directory.


@EndNode

@Node "Your mail box" "iceterm.guide/Your mail box"
@Next "Optional tool types"
@Prev "Message Bases"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Your mail box
=============

   The @{b}EMAILROOT@{ub} tool type is used to specify a directory where
received email (electronic mail) and the user list for the BBS system
is to be stored.  For example:

     EMAILROOT=dh2:vbbs/email

   Note that you should @{i}not@{ui} tell IceTERM that the @{b}MESSROOT@{ub} and
@{b}EMAILROOT@{ub} are the same directory or even that one is in a
subdirectory of the other as this can cause quite a bit of confusion.


@EndNode

@Node "Optional tool types" "iceterm.guide/Optional tool types"
@Next "Start the terminal"
@Prev "Your mail box"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Optional tool types
===================

   The remaining four tool types are safely optional, but should
probably still be set.

   The @{b}DOWNDIR@{ub} tool type specifies the directory where your file
downloads will go by default.  This will default to @{b}RAM:@{ub}.  If you have
a small system you may want to change this to a disk based directory,
and if you only have floppy disks you will probably want to set this to
@{b}DownLoads:@{ub} and then name a few disks @{b}DownLoads@{ub} (1)--this way you will
always have some free space to download to.

   The @{b}TEMPDIR@{ub} tool type specifies the directory where temporary files
will be made.  These are created when you edit messages in the feedback
and email tools of IceTERM, as well when you enter extended file
descriptions for file uploads.  This tool type will default to the
AmigaDOS standard temporary directory @{b}T:@{ub}.  The only problem you might
find with this is that the @{b}T:@{ub} directory may be assigned to a spot on
your boot disk, which is probably write protected.

   The @{b}KEEPFILE@{ub} tool type is the name of the file to save useful
messages in.  IceTERM will automatically @{i}append@{ui} to this file each item
that you decide to keep.  This will default to a file in @{b}ram:@{ub} called
@{b}keepfile@{ub}.  If you want a convenient way of saving useful or interesting
things you should change this to point to a permanent storage place.
Most of the windows in IceTERM have a @{b}KEEP@{ub} button that writes their
contents to this file.

   The @{b}SCRIPT@{ub} tool type specifies the name of the script file you want
to run when you double click the IceTERM icon.  There is no default to
this tool type, IceTERM will not run(2) a script file unless this is
present. A sample script file will probably be provided by your BBS
sysop or local user's group, the provided sample script file in the
archives I ship out(3) is set to dial my BBS, so take care, it is
probably long distance! Note that if you do not specify a directory
path(4) as part of the script file name the script file will be assumed
to be in the same directory as the IceTERM icon.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  When naming a disk you do not include the @{b}:@{ub} character in the
disk name, AmigaDOS will automatically include it for you.

   (2)  Of course this is not really true either.  If you start IceTERM
from a @{i}tool@{ui} icon without a @{b}SCRIPT@{ub} tool type then IceTERM will not start
any script files up. But, if IceTERM is started from a @{i}project@{ui} icon it
will attempt to use the project file as its script file.

   (3)  Your local BBS sysop may have modified it to dial his BBS
already.

   (4)  This is programmer's speak for directory or disk name.


@EndNode

@Node "Start the terminal" "iceterm.guide/Start the terminal"
@Prev "Optional tool types"
@Toc "Quick Start"

Double click!
=============

   Well if you've read the previous section, considered some of the
things in it and checked the tool type entries for your copy of the
IceTERM program you are now ready to double click the IceTERM icon.

   After doing this one of two things will happen(1), either the script
will start running and you will eventually be connected to and then
logged into a IceBBS based BBS, or IceTERM will open a window and just
sit there. In the latter case you can type a modem dial command and
call a IceBBS based BBS, when the two systems connect you will be
logged in automatically and you will get the normal IceTERM control
panel.

Additional customization
========================

   For more information on additional customization options available
within IceTERM, see @{"Tool types" Link "Tool types"}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Of course if some unexpected error is encountered you may get a
diagnostic requester from IceTERM instead.


@EndNode

@Node "Modem settings" "iceterm.guide/Modem settings"
@Next "Trouble Shooting"
@Prev "Quick Start"
@Toc "Main"

Modem Settings
**************

   This chapter contains some suggested settings for different brands
of modems.  If you are using another brand of modem (particularly a
high speed one) please let me know what settings you have found useful.

   I have set up the suggested configurations so that you can just send
the sequence of commands to your modem once, saving the settings in the
modem for future use.  Modems are designed to store your preferred
settings in some form of non-volatile RAM, so that even if you turn the
modem off these settings will still be there.  This is a @{i}good@{ui} thing to
do, since it means you no longer need to put any modem specific
commands in your dialing scripts (except to perhaps reset the modem
before dialing).


 @{" USR Dual Standard " Link "USR Dual Standard"} 
 @{" Supra FAX Modem " Link "Supra FAX Modem"} 
 @{" Zyxel " Link "Zyxel"} 
 @{" GVC 2400 MNP " Link "GVC 2400 MNP"} 
 @{" USR Sportster v34 " Link "USR Sportster v34"} 
 @{" Modem problems " Link "Modem problems"} 


@EndNode

@Node "USR Dual Standard" "iceterm.guide/USR Dual Standard"
@Next "Supra FAX Modem"
@Prev "Modem settings"
@Toc "Modem settings"

USR Dual Standard modem
=======================

   This is a tricky modem to set up as the factory defaults are not
very suitable to high speed serial port connections.  Here's what to
set:
     ATB0
     AT&H1
     AT&R2
     AT&K3
     AT&B1
     AT&A3
     ATX6
     AT&W

Then you should be able to setup IceTERM with the following tool types:
     BAUD=19200
     HANDSHAKE=7

If you are running an accelerated Amiga or using a serial port on an
expansion board you might want to try @{b}BAUD=38400@{ub} instead.


@EndNode

@Node "Supra FAX Modem" "iceterm.guide/Supra FAX Modem"
@Next "Zyxel"
@Prev "USR Dual Standard"
@Toc "Modem settings"

Supra FAX Modem V.32bis
=======================

   This modem will normally be shipped almost correctly set, the manual
claims it is set to @{b}AT&F2@{ub} unless you bought the Macintosh package;
however, you should check to make certain...
     AT&F2
     ATW2
     ATS95=3
     AT&W

The @{b}ATW2@{ub} and @{b}ATS95=3@{ub} settings are non-standard but yield a more
informative connection string.


@EndNode

@Node "Zyxel" "iceterm.guide/Zyxel"
@Next "GVC 2400 MNP"
@Prev "Supra FAX Modem"
@Toc "Modem settings"

Zyxel modems
============

   Hopefully UUG or John Lees can fill in the blanks here.

     AT&B1       fix the baud rate
     AT&K4       Negotiate for V.42 or MNP4
     AT&H3       Turn hardware flow control (CTS/RTS) on
     AT&W


@EndNode

@Node "GVC 2400 MNP" "iceterm.guide/GVC 2400 MNP"
@Next "USR Sportster v34"
@Prev "Zyxel"
@Toc "Modem settings"

GVC 2400 MNP modem
==================

   The GVC 2400 MNP was one of the earliest 2400 baud modems with MNP
at a reasonable price.
     AT%C1
     AT\J0    This is a rather unique setting
     AT\N3
     AT\V1
     AT\Q3
     AT\G0    This is a rather unique setting
     AT&W

Then you should be able to setup IceTERM with the following tool types:
     BAUD=9600
     HANDSHAKE=7


@EndNode

@Node "USR Sportster v34" "iceterm.guide/USR Sportster v34"
@Next "Modem problems"
@Prev "GVC 2400 MNP"
@Toc "Modem settings"

USR Sportster v34
=================

   This is one of the least expensive external v34 modems.  It is a
pretty good performer, although its big brother the v34 Courier seems
to more consistently connect at the maximum possible v34 speeds.  This
modem actually comes pre-configured for hardware flow control, so you
just plug it in and set your IceTERM to:

     BAUD=38400
     HANDSHAKE=7

or perhaps to @{b}BAUD=57600@{ub} if your serial port will go that fast.  If you
experience problems getting IceTERM to conplete the connection, or you
get a lot of errors you might just do a factory reset of the modem, in
case it had not been properly reset at the factory.  Use the following
commands to do this:

     AT&F1
     ATY0
     AT&W

   One possible problem with this modem is that IceTERM seems to be
able to send commands, from the dialing script, too fast for the modem
to handle.  So you might want to increase the @{b}DELAY@{ub} settings in any
dialing scripts (see @{"Script commands" Link "Script commands"}) you use.


@EndNode

@Node "Modem problems" "iceterm.guide/Modem problems"
@Prev "USR Sportster v34"
@Toc "Modem settings"

Modem problems
==============

   The most common problem people have with IceTERM is to do with the
settings of their serial port and the modem's serial port related
settings.  Of these the key issue is the use of hardware(1)
handshaking, which is essential when you are using baud rates higher
than @{b}2400@{ub}.  The most common problems are:

   @{b}*@{ub} Not enabling the hardware handshaking in IceTERM.  This is done by
     including the @{b}HANDSHAKE=7@{ub} tool type in the IceTERM icon,

   @{b}*@{ub} Not telling the modem to use hardware handshaking.  This one can
     be quite tricky, especially on the earlier v32 and v32bis modems
     (such as the Dual Standard).  These modems were not shipped with
     handshaking enabled, and in order to get the right handshaking
     mode turned on you had to send two modem commands @{b}AT&H1@{ub} and @{b}AT&R2@{ub}.
     The later v.fast and v34 modems usually have a factory default
     setting @{b}AT&F1@{ub} that sets up the correct handshaking(2),

   @{b}*@{ub} Telling the modem to use software handshaking.  This will not work
     with IceTERM(3) since it needs a full 8-bit data path and the
     software handshaking removes two of the characters for its own
     use.  Software handshaking is also called XON/XOFF handshaking,
     and sometimes CTRL-Q/CTRL-S.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Also called 7 wire.

   (2)  Although these modems usually add another factory setting
designed for use with the Macintosh that selects the wrong type of
handshaking.

   (3)  In fact it will not work well with most normal terminal
programs when you are downloading binary files.


@EndNode

@Node "Trouble Shooting" "iceterm.guide/Trouble Shooting"
@Next "Using the terminal"
@Prev "Modem settings"
@Toc "Main"

Trouble Shooting
****************

   This chapter contains a set of common problems (and some uncommon
ones) along with some suggestions as to what to do to try to solve them.
If you have not yet read the @{i}Quick Start@{ui} chapter (see @{"Quick Start" Link "Quick Start"}), and
you are having problems, please read it now.


 @{" Will not start " Link "Will not start"}         IceTERM fails to start after double clicking
 @{" Cannot quit " Link "Cannot quit"}            I cannot exit from IceTERM
 @{" Connects then quits " Link "Connects then quits"}    IceTERM connects to the BBS then quits
 @{" The BBS hangs up " Link "The BBS hangs up"}       The BBS hangs up on me
 @{" MNP error " Link "MNP error"}              I get an MNP error requester
 @{" Garbage appears " Link "Garbage appears"}        Garbage appears in the window
 @{" Line noise " Link "Line noise"}             Problems with phone line noise
 @{" Message problems " Link "Message problems"}       Various problems posting messages
 @{" User name problems " Link "User name problems"}     Various problems with user names
 @{" Talk window closes " Link "Talk window closes"}     The talk window closes on me
 @{" Writing to boot disk " Link "Writing to boot disk"}   IceTERM is writing to my boot disk
 @{" Hanging up the modem " Link "Hanging up the modem"}   IceTERM will not hang up the modem
 @{" Slow transfers " Link "Slow transfers"}         File transfers are very slow
 @{" Internal modems " Link "Internal modems"}        Problems with internal modems
 @{" Enforcer hits " Link "Enforcer hits"}          Enforcer complains about IceTERM
 @{" Scripts will not run " Link "Scripts will not run"}   My dialing script will not run
 @{" Posting crash " Link "Posting crash"}          IceTERM crashes after I post a message
 @{" No response " Link "No response"}            Once logged in, IceTERM will not respond
 @{" Modem will not dial " Link "Modem will not dial"}    Very old modem will not dial
 @{" Doors do not appear " Link "Doors do not appear"}    The door chooser does not display all the doors
 @{" Doors do not work " Link "Doors do not work"}      Doors do not start correctly
 @{" Problems snapshotting " Link "Problems snapshotting"}  Some windows do not seem to snapshot
 @{" Conference garbage " Link "Conference garbage"}     So the conference turns to greek?
 @{" Data but no server " Link "Data but no server"}     Warning message on the control panel


@EndNode

@Node "Will not start" "iceterm.guide/Will not start"
@Next "Cannot quit"
@Prev "Trouble Shooting"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

IceTERM␀will not start
======================

   IceTERM refuses to start and immediately returns to the CLI prompt.

   If you are running under AmigaDOS 1.2 or 1.3 you need to check your
@{b}LIBS:@{ub} to see if you have @{b}Arp.Library@{ub} installed.  Check to see that you
are not already using the serial port.  It could also be that you are
low on memory. In all these cases IceTERM should bring up a diagnostic
requester.


@EndNode

@Node "Cannot quit" "iceterm.guide/Cannot quit"
@Next "Connects then quits"
@Prev "Will not start"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

I can't quit out of IceTERM
===========================

   The quit command is accessed from a menu on the IceTERM screen.
Often(1) the window to which this menu item is connected will be hidden
by other windows.  Look around for the small control panel (with the
various IceTERM function buttons), activate it (by clicking in it
somewhere) and then hit the menu button and select @{b}Quit@{ub} from the menu.
This window also has a close window button, you can click on it rather
than using the menu item if you like.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Especially when running from the WorkBench.


@EndNode

@Node "Connects then quits" "iceterm.guide/Connects then quits"
@Next "The BBS hangs up"
@Prev "Cannot quit"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

IceTERM␀connects then quits
===========================

   The initial terminal window (titled: "ASCII Window", where the modem
commands appear) goes away then reappears instead of the control
window.  The control window (with the various function gadgets of
IceTERM) may actually flash briefly onto the screen before the ASCII
terminal window reappears.

   Either your modem cable probably is not passing the carrier detect
(CD) line or the modem is not configured to send a carrier detect
signal to the computer.  Most modern serial cables are assembled with
all the necessary pins wired straight through, older cables(1),
especially those which appear to have missing pins, may not pass all
the necessary signals.  To test a cable is quite simple, but a little
tricky for the novice, it is easiest to borrow a cable that is known to
work and try it.

   If you suspect the modem is the problem, the setting to check is
usually the @{b}AT&C@{ub} command.  The @{b}&C0@{ub} generally tells the modem to always
keep the carrier detect line on (regardless of whether there is a
connection or not).  The @{b}&C1@{ub} command tells the modem to send the
carrier detect only when there is a connection currently.  Other modems
may have a suppress carrier detect mode too.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Often these might be custom or even homemade.


@EndNode

@Node "The BBS hangs up" "iceterm.guide/The BBS hangs up"
@Next "MNP error"
@Prev "Connects then quits"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

The BBS hangs up on me
======================

   There is a possibility this can happen at any time due to the number
of ways a phone call can be interrupted(1), but typically it is a
problem when a user is trying to log in.  This problem is really two
separate ones:

   @{b}*@{ub} First, if the BBS hangs up on you before the modems have fully
     connected it is nothing to worry about.  A IceBBS system will
     reset the modems from time to time, and if you happen to dial in
     at just the right time this will happen to you.  This will happen
     more often on a very busy BBS as the modem is reset after each
     user logs out.  If this happens just wait a few seconds and redial.

   @{b}*@{ub} Second, if the BBS hangs up on you after the modems have connected
     but before the control panel says you are logged in, it is
     probably a line noise problem(2).  Line noise (see @{"Line noise" Link "Line noise"}) can
     affect the connection a number of ways, first it can lead to the
     two modems connecting at different rates. And second, it can cause
     trouble as the two ends of the connection try to start the
     protocol, this is indicated by a long period of modem light
     flashing and your name not appearing in the title bar.  In either
     case you should just hang up and try again.

   If your BBS session is interrupted at some point after you have
logged in there is little you can do about it.  However, both the file
and SIGs downloading functions feature session resume capabilities, so
by calling the BBS back and requesting those interrupted items again
you will be able to pick up where you left off.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Call waiting and other people picking up the phone to make a
call are examples

   (2)  For about a year one of my phone lines had about a 1 in 6
chance of being terrible, then the problem suddenly went away, phone
company contacts told me that the local exchange had been upgraded
around the time the problems disappeared.


@EndNode

@Node "MNP error" "iceterm.guide/MNP error"
@Next "Garbage appears"
@Prev "The BBS hangs up"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Error detected in MNP mode!
===========================

   This error message can occur if your modem and the BBS are running in
MNP or V.42 mode and the IceTERM and BBS have successfully negotiated
to leave the error correction duties to the modems.  Normally when this
is done all the data is guaranteed to get from one computer to another
without any errors occuring.  However, when the phone lines are
exceptionally noisy (see @{"Line noise" Link "Line noise"}) or when some external event(1)
interferes with the phone line the modems may lose the connection
entirely.  In this case it appears that they can send corrupt data back
to the computer.  Because of this both IceBBS and IceTERM do some extra
checking of data packets(2) sent over these @{i}error-free@{ui} circuits and
when such an error is detected they stop communications(3) and warn the
user.

   Handshaking (see @{"Modem settings" Link "Modem settings"}) is another cause for this requester
appearing.  If there is a handshaking problem on the serial line
between your modem and the computer, or between the BBS and its modem
it is possible for some data to get lost.  When this happens the
checksums will not match and the computers will drop the connection and
this message will appear.  If you are just starting to use the MNP or
V.42 mode and you get these requesters you should check the serial
cable, the handshaking setting (in the IceTERM icon) and the modem
register settings that control handshaking.  If you get this when doing
file uploads then it is almost certain the problem is handshaking
between your modem and computer.

   Finally, check the version of your @{b}serial.device@{ub} the older 1.3 and
1.2 devices did have some problems that may cause data loss (perhaps
through poorer handshaking).  The most up-to-date device for AmigaDOS
1.3 (or 1.2) is the one that came with the 1.3.2 update, it contains a
version number of 34.12 and a date stamp of 27 Mar 1989.  With AmigaDOS
2.0 or higher you can use the @{b}version@{ub} command:

     version serial.device full

With AmigaDOS 1.3 or earlier you can check your device by issuing the
CLI command:

     type devs:serial.device opt h

and then looking for a date and version number near the beginning of
the output(4).  When diagnosing this you might want to drop back to
2400 baud and see if troubles go away.

In MNP mode IceTERM stops working
=================================

   If you are using an MNP capable modem (in particular the GVC 2400
MNP) and cannot use IceTERM once the connection process is complete and
the control window says you are @{b}Logged in@{ub}, then take a look at your
modem settings - you should set it to @{b}AT\G0@{ub} (5).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Such as the call waiting signal, or another person taking the
phone off the hook and starting to dial (which is called the "Craig
Lever's Sister problem").

   (2)  This was first suggested by a fellow from the Software
Distillery I met at DevCon '91.

   (3)  This is about all that can be done since there is no packet
retry logic in the MNP and V.42 connection mode at this point in time.

   (4)  Of course AmigaDOS 2.0 has a better serial device.

   (5)  This was the Al K.  problem, we still do not know how his modem
ever got set incorrectly.


@EndNode

@Node "Garbage appears" "iceterm.guide/Garbage appears"
@Next "Line noise"
@Prev "MNP error"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Garbage in the window
=====================

   Upon typing commands into the ASCII mode window all you get is
garbage.

   When this happens it is probably because of a baud rate mismatch
between the computer and the modem. Note that IceTERM gets its baud
rate from several places.  First it picks up whatever the default
preferences baud rate is.  Next it looks in the tool types array of the
IceTERM program's icon for a @{b}BAUD@{ub} tool type.  Then if IceTERM was
started from a project icon it looks for a @{b}BAUD@{ub} tool type in the
project icon and uses that baud rate.  Finally, it checks to see if it
was started from the CLI, and if it was it looks for a @{b}-b@{ub} command line
switch and uses that baud rate.

   Complex or what?  Actually, this sequence is always applied in the
same order for all configuration parameters:

   @{b}*@{ub} First accept any Amiga defaults(1),

   @{b}*@{ub} Second look for a setting in the IceTERM program's icon (if one is
     available),

   @{b}*@{ub} Third, if IceTERM was started from a project icon, look in the
     project icon for any settings,

   @{b}*@{ub} Finally, if IceTERM was started from the CLI, scan the command
     line and use any settings found there.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  As set by the various preferences programs.


@EndNode

@Node "Line noise" "iceterm.guide/Line noise"
@Next "Message problems"
@Prev "Garbage appears"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

I get massive quantities of line noise
======================================

   This may be a problem with your phone lines or the loading you are
placing on them.  If you are experiencing troubles with a high speed
modem you should try disconnecting all additional phone line devices(1)
that you have to see if that makes any difference.  Once, while testing
a pair of V.32 modems (at the time $1600 a piece) I could not get more
than about 4800 baud out them, I finally tracked the problem down to a
$19 phone that was sharing one of the lines.

   Phone lines are quite amazing things, they are light weight,
unshielded, use very light connectors and work well most of the time.
Once, when the AMUC Express was moved, all the newly installed phone
lines (7 of them!) worked well with the exception of one.  This was the
infamous 5224 line, and it naturally had to be the FidoNet line at the
time.  After a week or so this line started causing all sorts of
troubles because it would generate a large amount of line noise (which
you could hear if you placed a phone call).  It took two service calls
from the phone company to figure it out, turns out that an isolation
jumper that connects the input side to the output side on the
distribution block inside the house was not making a good connection.
This little one cent, push on, spring clip brought a big BBS to its
knees!

   It might also appear that you are having lots of line noise slow
down your connection when the problem is really the result of having
the wrong handshaking (or incorrect modem settings, see @{"Modem settings" Link "Modem settings"})
between your modem and serial port.  There are two modes available:
either @{b}-hn@{ub} (no handshaking(2)) @{b}-h7@{ub} (RTS/CTS handshake, 7 wire mode(3)).
It should not matter which you choose, except that if you are running a
newer modem where the serial rate can be higher than the modem's phone
line rate then you @{i}must@{ui} use the 7 wire mode.  It is strongly recomended
that you use @{b}7wire@{ub} mode whenever your baud rate exceeds 2400.

   The @{b}LINK@{ub} tool type can be very useful in diagnosing and fixing
serial communications problems, see @{"Serial port" Link "Serial port"}.

   Some hard drive controller cards can cause interference with the
Amiga's internal serial port.  Normally what happens is that the hard
disk transfers take over the Amiga's bus for a long enough time that a
serial port interrupt gets serviced too late. This causes loss of a
character or characters.  This symptoms of this problem are that
downloads to the RAM disk or to floppies seem to work fine, but
downloads to a hard drive partition take much longer.  If the @{b}LINK@{ub} tool
type is set you will see lots of NAK (N-type) packets being generated.
The GVP "Combo boards", which combine memory expansion, an '030 chip
and a SCSI controller on one card are notorious for this.  There is a
program called @{b}GVPPatch@{ub} that will help fix the problem.  I have had
reports of a similar problem happening in a system that has an ICD
Trifecta controller and an RCS'040 board.

   NOTE: since the IceTERM to IceBBS link uses a full 8-bit binary
connection you cannot select the serial port's XON XOFF handshaking.
If you do select this via the Amiga's Preferences, IceTERM will default
to no handshaking.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Such as other modems, phones, FAX and answering machines.

   (2)  From the WorkBench set the @{b}HANDSHAKE=none@{ub} tool type.

   (3)  From the WorkBench set @{b}HANDSHAKE=7wire@{ub} in the IceTERM icon.


@EndNode

@Node "Message problems" "iceterm.guide/Message problems"
@Next "User name problems"
@Prev "Line noise"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Problems posting messages
=========================

No editor appears
-----------------

   Sometimes a user will be able to read messages with the feedback
tool (this can also happen with email and IceOLR), but when she hits
the @{b}P@{ub} (for post) or @{b}R@{ub} (for reply) keys nothing appears to happen.  This
can be caused by a number of things:

   @{b}*@{ub} by not editing the @{b}EDITOR@{ub} line in the IceTERM icon's tool type
     array,

   @{b}*@{ub} by not running IceTERM with enough stack space.  Try the CLI
     command:
          STACK 10000

     just before running IceTERM, or if running IceTERM from an icon
     adjust the stack setting from the WorkBench's @{b}Icons, Information@{ub}
     menu item,

   @{b}*@{ub} by trying to use an editor that is not in the @{b}C:@{ub} directory, check
     to see if the editor is actually in @{b}C:@{ub} (1),

   @{b}*@{ub} it is possible that you are out of RAM and the editor cannot be
     started,

   @{b}*@{ub} some editors are particular about the screen font, so if you are
     running AmigaDOS 2.0 and have changed the screen font,

   @{b}*@{ub} some editors need a larger stack setting and perhaps depend on the
     current directory, if this is the case you can run the editor from
     a script file such as this:

          .key file
          STACK 20000
          CD RAM:
          myeditor <file>

   @{b}*@{ub} sometimes the editor actually has opened but it is just hidden
     away on another screen.  If this is the case you want to read up
     on the @{b}WBHACK@{ub} tool type and about public screens (see @{"Your Editor" Link "Your Editor"}),

   @{b}*@{ub} some editors just don't seem to want to be spawned by the
     Execute() function in AmigaDOS, so if all else fails try another
     editor (perhaps even @{b}Ed@{ub}) that is known to work with IceTERM.

My postings never appear on the BBS
-----------------------------------

   This could be because you are using an editor that detaches from the
CLI.  The editors: @{b}AZ@{ub} and @{b}CygnusEd@{ub} are known to do this.  Try a
different editor.  Actually, IceTERM can now handle these editors too,
just wait until you are finished editing your message and have saved
the file @{i}before@{ui} clicking on the IceTERM requester that asks you if you
want to post the message.

   IceTERM tells the editor to edit a file called something like
@{b}tempfile@{ub} when the editor is started.  The results of your editing must
be put back into that file.  This is easily done as most editors have
two ways of saving your work, the @{i}save as@{ui} (where you must tell the
editor the file name to use) and the @{i}save@{ui} function.  You will normally
want to select the @{i}save@{ui} function and then exit the editor.  Note also
that some editors have a @{i}save and exit@{ui} function which should also work
with IceTERM.

Duplicate postings keep appearing
---------------------------------

   These are usually the result of a user using an editor that detaches
from the CLI and not saving his message before clicking on the posting
message requester.  Essentially, this is a result of the previous
problem.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Or include the full directory path to your editor, see also
@{"Tooltype rules" Link "Tooltype rules"}.


@EndNode

@Node "User name problems" "iceterm.guide/User name problems"
@Next "Talk window closes"
@Prev "Message problems"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

How do I log in under my own name?
==================================

   Simple!  Just edit the tool types in the IceTERM icon.  There is an
entry called @{b}USER@{ub} for your name and @{b}PASSWORD@{ub} for your password (see
@{"Name and password" Link "Name and password"}).  Note: you do not have to save the password in the
icon, if you do not include it then IceTERM will ask you to enter it
whenever you start IceTERM.

How do I log in with different names?
=====================================

   Typically this problem arises when a user wants to connect with
several different BBS systems each running IceBBS software.  He may
wish to use the same name on each BBS, but with  different passwords,
he may even wish to have a different name and password on each system,
or he may have several accounts on the same system.

   There are three ways of doing this, they differ mainly in how you
connect to those BBS systems:

   @{b}*@{ub} the easiest (and most wasteful) is to just duplicate IceTERM
     (along with its icon) so you have one copy per BBS(1) and then put
     the appropriate name and password in each icon.  To do this just
     click on the IceTERM icon and select the "copy" function from the
     WorkBench menu,

   @{b}*@{ub} the next is to put separate @{i}project@{ui} icons in the same directory as
     the IceTERM @{i}tool@{ui} icon and in these icons put the individual names
     and passwords (see @{"Name and password" Link "Name and password"}).  Then to log onto a
     particular BBS just double click on the correct icon.  This is a
     nice method because IceTERM will store any snapshot information you
     make in the @{i}project@{ui} icon from which it was started so you can make
     a fully custom environment for each BBS,

   @{b}*@{ub} the last is to include the @{b}name@{ub} and @{b}password@{ub} commands (see
     @{"Script commands" Link "Script commands"}) in your dialing script file.  You put these
     commands immediately before the command that dials the BBS.  This
     way one script can dial several BBS systems, on each of which you
     can have accounts with different names and passwords.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Of course each copy of IceTERM must have a different name or be
placed in a different drawer.


@EndNode

@Node "Talk window closes" "iceterm.guide/Talk window closes"
@Next "Writing to boot disk"
@Prev "User name problems"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

The talk window opens and closes
================================

   You need to have these files in your system:

     LIBS:translator.library
     DEVS:narrator.device

   Often people strip these from their system to save space on the boot
disk.  Also, it appears that these no longer come with AmigaDOS 2.1 or
3.0(1). It is safe to run IceTERM without these present, but you will
not be able to page the sysop(2).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  If this is the case you can copy them off your older version of
AmigaDOS, try to use the ones from version 1.3.3

   (2)  Also, the sysop will not be able to page you either, this is a
neat feature, its fun to be downloading stuff from a BBS, demonstrating
a neat program to your friends and suddenly the computer starts talking
to you.


@EndNode

@Node "Writing to boot disk" "iceterm.guide/Writing to boot disk"
@Next "Hanging up the modem"
@Prev "Talk window closes"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

IceTERM␀wants to write to my boot disk
======================================

   IceTERM needs to create some temporary files from time to time. It
puts these files in the directory @{b}T:@{ub}.  By default this directory will
be the @{b}:T@{ub} directory on your boot disk.  You need to add to your startup
sequence a command like:

     ASSIGN T: RAM:

   This tells your Amiga to put temporary files into the RAM disk.
Alternatively, you can edit the tool types in the IceTERM icon and add
an entry called @{b}TEMPDIR@{ub}, pointing to the directory you wish to use.


@EndNode

@Node "Hanging up the modem" "iceterm.guide/Hanging up the modem"
@Next "Slow transfers"
@Prev "Writing to boot disk"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

IceTERM␀will not hang up the modem
==================================

   What usually happens here is that when you exit IceTERM with the
@{b}Quit@{ub} menu item, the modem still stays on-line, when you really
wanted it to hang up the connection.

   The problem here is that your modem has been set to ignore the @{b}DTR@{ub}
line, when IceTERM exits it closes the serial port which should drop
the @{b}DTR@{ub} line.  This should cause the modem to drop the line. However,
modems can be set to ignore this line, and/or your serial cable may not
pass this line.  If your modem is ignoring the line you may wish to
send it an @{b}AT&D3@{ub} command before starting up IceTERM. You can make this
setting permanent by issuing an @{b}AT&W@{ub} command. Note: some people do not
like to use the @{b}AT&D3@{ub} setting as they like to hop from one terminal
package to another without the modem hanging up the connection.

   There is another possible cause of this problem: faulty serial port
software.  There is a known problem with the Commodore A2232 multi-port
serial card that prevents it from doing a hardware hangup of the modem.
Contact your dealer to see about getting the more recent version of
the serial device driver that fixes this problem.


@EndNode

@Node "Slow transfers" "iceterm.guide/Slow transfers"
@Next "Internal modems"
@Prev "Hanging up the modem"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

I get very slow file transfers
==============================

   See the notes in @{"Line noise" Link "Line noise"} and @{"Serial port" Link "Serial port"}, this can be a symptom
of poor phone line conditions or handshaking mismatches.  To help
diagnose this you might want to enable the link diagnostics, see @{"LINK" Link "LINK"}
for information.

   Additionally, check to see that you are not doing something terribly
CPU intensive (such as running @{b}Lharc@{ub}, @{b}LZ@{ub} or a ray tracer(1)) as these
will steal lots of CPU.  Also, if this happens a lot and you are
running IceTERM on a 8 or 16 colour screen reduce it to 2 or 4 colours
and see if the problem stops.

   This symptom may also be present when the BBS is particularly busy.
For example, if many users are on-line at one time and downloading
files, the BBS system may not respond as quickly to each user.  As
well, if the BBS is processing an incoming package of FidoNet or USENET
mail, this may cause decreased performance.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  AutoCLI is known to do this as well as some CPU monitors.


@EndNode

@Node "Internal modems" "iceterm.guide/Internal modems"
@Next "Enforcer hits"
@Prev "Slow transfers"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Internal modem problems
=======================

   There are a number of possible problems that can arise when using an
internal modem (that is a modem that is on a board that is installed in
an A2000, A3000 or A4000 card slot).

Applied Engineering internal modem will not respond
---------------------------------------------------

   On early versions of this internal modem you need to send an @{b}ATC1@{ub}
command to the modem to get it to respond.

Strange things are happening
----------------------------

   Earlier versions of the Applied Engineering modem would not handle
multiple character reads correctly, IceBBS and IceTERM(1) do a lot of
this for reasons of efficiency, new versions of the modem's ROM
software fix the problem.

   This problem is characterized by problems that occur immediately
upon connecting to the BBS, the control window will appear and perhaps
one or two things will appear to work but then IceTERM will stop
functioning.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  I used to have a version of IceTERM that was patched to do
single character I/O but this version is no longer available.


@EndNode

@Node "Enforcer hits" "iceterm.guide/Enforcer hits"
@Next "Scripts will not run"
@Prev "Internal modems"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Enforcer complains about IceTERM
================================

   The Enforcer is a developer's MMU(1) utility which monitors memory
accesses by the CPU and reports possible illegal accesses.  There is
one function that will cause Enforcer to complain when running IceTERM
under AmigaDOS 1.3, this is the Talk function.  The 1.3.3 update to
AmigaDOS fixes this.  If you experience any enforcer hits while running
IceTERM please let me know (especially if you have a method of
repeating them).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  You must have the full version of the 68030 or 68040 to have an
MMU.  Many accelerator cards use the @{i}EC@{ui} or @{i}LC@{ui} CPUs which do not have a
fully functional MMU.


@EndNode

@Node "Scripts will not run" "iceterm.guide/Scripts will not run"
@Next "Posting crash"
@Prev "Enforcer hits"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

The script file will not run
============================

   Certain older modems (particular 1200 baud modems) either do not
respond fast enough or do not like to see a carriage return followed by
a line feed.  When you try to use a modem like this IceTERM may send it
a dial command and the modem might not seem to respond at all.  To fix
this change all @{b}crlf@{ub} and @{b}lf@{ub} commands in the script file to @{b}cr@{ub} or @{b}char
13@{ub} commands and add some @{b}delay@{ub} commands between the @{b}send@{ub} and @{b}cr@{ub}
commands (see @{"Serial port" Link "Serial port"}).

   I once used an old 1200 baud modem for testing and it would not
respond if CTS/RTS (7 wire) handshaking was used.


@EndNode

@Node "Posting crash" "iceterm.guide/Posting crash"
@Next "No response"
@Prev "Scripts will not run"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

IceTERM␀crashes after I post a message
======================================

   If you find that the message reader locks up or crashes after
posting or replying to a message - and you are running IceTERM from the
WorkBench - remove the line in your startup-sequence which says
@{b}resident Shell-Seg@{ub} or else run IceTERM from the CLI.  I believe this
bug has been fixed.


@EndNode

@Node "No response" "iceterm.guide/No response"
@Next "Modem will not dial"
@Prev "Posting crash"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

IceTERM␀does not respond once logged in
=======================================

   If you are using an MNP capable modem and cannot use IceTERM once
the connection process is complete and the control window says you are
@{b}Logged In@{ub}, then take a look at your modem settings you should set @{b}AT\G0@{ub}
(1).  (This was the Al K. problem).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This may only apply to the GVC MNP 2400 modem.


@EndNode

@Node "Modem will not dial" "iceterm.guide/Modem will not dial"
@Next "Doors do not appear"
@Prev "No response"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

My Packard Bell modem does not dial
===================================

   On some modems it seems that the @{b}crlf@{ub} command in the script file
(which sends a carriage return line feed pair) confuses the modem.  The
solution to this is to replace all @{b}crlf@{ub} commands with either @{b}cr@{ub} or @{b}char
13@{ub} commands (which will just send a carriage return).


@EndNode

@Node "Doors do not appear" "iceterm.guide/Doors do not appear"
@Next "Doors do not work"
@Prev "Modem will not dial"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

My doors do not appear
======================

   If you do not see all the doors you have placed in your @{b}DOORDIR@{ub}
directory listed in the door chooser there are several possibilities:

   @{b}*@{ub} You have not copied @{i}both@{ui} the door client @{i}and@{ui} its icon to the
     directory.  IceTERM looks at the icon to determine if a program
     that has been placed in the door directory can be used as a door,

   @{b}*@{ub} You may have placed a server in the directory as well.  Servers
     are used only by the BBS, they are often distributed as part of
     the door package so sysops receive compatible versions of both the
     client and the server,

   @{b}*@{ub} The missing door may not be a IceTERM door.  Other BBS systems have
     doors too, none of these can currently be used with IceBBS or
     IceTERM.


@EndNode

@Node "Doors do not work" "iceterm.guide/Doors do not work"
@Next "Problems snapshotting"
@Prev "Doors do not appear"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

My doors do not work
====================

   If nothing happens when you select a door from the door chooser there
are four possible explainations:

   @{b}*@{ub} You might not have some necessary piece of support software
     installed that the door requires to run.  For example an ARexx
     door requires that you have ARexx installed,

   @{b}*@{ub} The BBS may not be running the server for the door that you are
     trying to use, or you may not have enough privilege to run the
     door,

   @{b}*@{ub} You might have an old version of the door, this may be causing
     problems when trying to start the door on your machine or the
     server on the BBS, ask your sysop for an up-to-date version of the
     client,

   @{b}*@{ub} You might be trying to run a server rather than a client, remember
     that servers are for the BBS only.


@EndNode

@Node "Problems snapshotting" "iceterm.guide/Problems snapshotting"
@Next "Conference garbage"
@Prev "Doors do not work"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Some windows do not snapshot
============================

   If you are having problems trying to get a window to snapshot to a
new postition in IceTERM here are the things to look for:

   @{b}*@{ub} Make certain that the WorkBench window that contains the icon you
     started IceTERM from is closed.  Under AmigaDOS 1.3 this is not
     important but under AmigaDOS 2.0 and higher the new file
     notification feature can cause some problems.  Whenever IceTERM is
     updating the tool types in the icon it does so one item at a time,
     and can miss write attempts if the icon is currently being displayed by
     WorkBench,

   @{b}*@{ub} There are a couple windows in IceTERM which do not pick up their
     new snapshot locations until IceTERM is restarted,

   @{b}*@{ub} If you have duplicate tool types in the icon (perhaps from an
     earlier version of IceTERM), then when IceTERM snapshots it will
     only change the first matching tool type it finds.  However, the
     routines which load the tool types from the icons when IceTERM is
     started will only use the last tool type they read from the icon.
     The result is that the updated tool type is ignored until the
     duplicate is deleted.


@EndNode

@Node "Conference garbage" "iceterm.guide/Conference garbage"
@Next "Data but no server"
@Prev "Problems snapshotting"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Garbage characters in the conference
====================================

   Sometimes the contents of the conference may appear to @{i}turn to
greek@{ui}.  This occurs when someone enters a @{b}CTRL-N@{ub} character into a
message to switch character sets.  To restore the conference to the
regular character set just enter a @{b}CTRL-O@{ub} character in a message.


@EndNode

@Node "Data but no server" "iceterm.guide/Data but no server"
@Prev "Conference garbage"
@Toc "Trouble Shooting"

Data but no server message
==========================

   This message appears in the title bar of the control panel window
when you close a window that is receiving data before it is all sent.
For example, if you close a text window (such as @{"Message of the day" Link "Message of the day"})
while it is still filling with text, you will get this message.

   This is because IceBBS is still sending data to a window (the server)
which no longer exists.

   This is an informative or diagnostic message and is not a cause for
any alarm.


@EndNode

@Node "Using the terminal" "iceterm.guide/Using the terminal"
@Next "From the CLI"
@Prev "Trouble Shooting"
@Toc "Main"

Using IceTERM
*************

   Once you have dialed into and connected to a system running IceBBS
software, IceTERM will change its window from the plain ASCII console
window to one with a number of buttons in it.  This is the IceTERM
control panel and you use this to select which functions you want to
use and to exit from IceTERM.  The @{b}Quit@{ub} function (which is used to exit
from the BBS) is activated by either clicking on the close window
gadget or by selecting the @{b}Quit@{ub} item in the menu that is attached to
the control window.  It is also possible to exit from IceTERM by just
interrupting the phone connection, by either unplugging the phone cable
or turning off the modem.  This is not the recommended way of exiting
IceTERM since you will not be warned if there is still a background
transfer taking place.

   This chapter describes the functions provided by the control window.


 @{" Connect time " Link "Connect time"}           Session timer and remaining time
 @{" The main buttons " Link "The main buttons"}       The twelve buttons
 @{" Message of the day " Link "Message of the day"}     The BBS greeting and email messages
 @{" Keep buttons " Link "Keep buttons"}           Saving messages and interesting text
 @{" Chat and talk " Link "Chat and talk"}          The chat and talk buttons
 @{" SIGs " Link "SIGs"}                   The on-line SIGs system
 @{" Batch SIGs " Link "Batch SIGs"}             The batch downloader for SIG messages
 @{" Conference " Link "Conference"}             Talking to other users
 @{" Get files " Link "Get files"}              Downloading files from the BBS
 @{" Send file " Link "Send file"}              Sending a file to the BBS
 @{" Feedback " Link "Feedback"}               The original simple message base
 @{" Monitor " Link "Monitor"}                Watching and paging others on the BBS
 @{" EMail " Link "EMail"}                  How to use electronic mail
 @{" News " Link "News"}                   The news menu
 @{" Shell " Link "Shell"}                  Remote access to AmigaDOS
 @{" Serial port features " Link "Serial port features"}   Additional special modes
 @{" Doors " Link "Doors"}                  Extending the IceTERM and BBS


@EndNode

@Node "Connect time" "iceterm.guide/Connect time"
@Next "The main buttons"
@Prev "Using the terminal"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Session timers
==============

   The two digital clocks show your total connection time and the
maximum time left in this session (before the BBS logs you out).  The
connection timer (on the left) counts up from zero, while the time
remaining clock counts (on the right) down to zero.  IceTERM will beep
you once a minute during the last five minutes of your session.
IceTERM will also put up a requester and beep twice if your session has
been idle for more that six minutes.  To get the clocks to update at a
different rate use the @{b}UPDATERATE@{ub} tool type (see @{"Timer control" Link "Timer control"}). The
default update rate is about once every 10 seconds.


@EndNode

@Node "The main buttons" "iceterm.guide/The main buttons"
@Next "Message of the day"
@Prev "Connect time"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

The main buttons
================

   The twelve main BBS functions available through IceTERM are accessed
through the buttons in this window.  There is also a menu bar connected
to the main control window which is used to exit the IceTERM program,
provides menu equivalents for some of the buttons and also provides the
snapshot function (see @{"The snapshot menu" Link "The snapshot menu"}).  Most of the other control
windows (see @{"Window positioning" Link "Window positioning"}) in IceTERM also have the snapshot menu
item. This item is used to save the position and size (where
applicable) of the window along with the state of any toggle buttons,
multi-state buttons and some of the string requesters in the window
that it is attached to. This information is saved in the icon from
which IceTERM was started(1) and will be reloaded the next time you
start IceTERM from that icon.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The icon that was double clicked, either a tool or project icon.


@EndNode

@Node "Message of the day" "iceterm.guide/Message of the day"
@Next "Keep buttons"
@Prev "The main buttons"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Text windows
============

   When IceTERM connects to the BBS an additional window will usually
appear, this is a scrolling text window which will display the sysop's
message of the day.  An additional, similar window will appear to
inform you of waiting email if there is some on the BBS for you.

   Whenever a window of this type shows up on your screen (the BBS uses
them for a number of things) it is always controlled in the same way.
There are two sliders with which you can scroll up and down, left and
right through the message.  The window is also re-sizable.  When you
are done with the contents of the window just hit the close button.
You do not have to stop what you are doing to read the message, it is
safe to just click it into the background to be read later.
Additionally, you will find that clicking on a line of test within the
window will cause that line to highlight, this feature is not yet used
for anything.


@EndNode

@Node "Keep buttons" "iceterm.guide/Keep buttons"
@Next "Chat and talk"
@Prev "Message of the day"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Keep buttons
============

   A number of IceTERM's windows have a button marked @{b}Keep@{ub}.  This
button is used to save the current contents of that window into your
keep file (see @{"Optional tool types" Link "Optional tool types"}).  When you click on the @{b}Keep@{ub} button
the system file requester will appear, this has been preset to the name
of the keep file that you specified with the @{b}KEEPFILE@{ub} tool type (see
@{"The keepfile" Link "The keepfile"}).  If you just want to save the window's contents into
this file (appended to the end), click on the file requester's @{b}OK@{ub}
button.  If you would like to save the data somewhere else use the file
requester to select the file it is to be appended to, or enter the name
of a new file and one will be created for you.


@EndNode

@Node "Chat and talk" "iceterm.guide/Chat and talk"
@Next "SIGs"
@Prev "Keep buttons"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Chat and talk
=============

   The chat and talk functions are similar tools which are used to
communicate directly between the user and sysop.

   Both functions are symmetric, when the window opens on your IceTERM
screen a similar window opens on the sysop's computer screen.  With the
chat window, whatever you type into it will appear in the sysop's chat
window and visa versa.  Since both you and the sysop might start typing
at the same time it is good practice to open a second chat window(1)
and then each person claims a window for his own. The really nice thing
about chat windows is that they may be left open while you attempt to
do something, allowing the sysop to provide true on-line help without
interfering with the flow of events.  Note if you are downloading files
at the same time as chatting you will find that it takes longer to send
what you are typing.

   The talk function differs from the chat function in that whatever is
typed into the window at one end of the connection is @{i}spoken@{ui} by the
Amiga's speech synthesizer at both ends of the connection.  Note that
this function works both ways: you can page the sysop and the sysop can
page you, so do not be surprised(2) if sometime late one night (say on a
full moon) your Amiga suddenly starts talking to you...

   For the talk function to work you must have the narrator device and
translator libraries installed on your system (see @{"Talk window closes" Link "Talk window closes"}),
if either is not installed then the window will quickly close.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Since IceTERM and IceBBS allow you to do several things at once
this is easy and natural to do.

   (2)  I did this to one of my users (Sheldon Maloff) who I had
noticed had been idle for a while, it turns out he was working on a
backup program at the time and had forgotten IceTERM was running in the
background. The truly surprising part of it was that his backup program
was designed to use the speech system to prompt him to change disks,
and then suddenly it just started talking to him...


@EndNode

@Node "SIGs" "iceterm.guide/SIGs"
@Next "Batch SIGs"
@Prev "Chat and talk"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

SIGs
====

   There are two buttons (@{b}Sigs@{ub} and @{b}BatchSIG@{ub}) that access the SIGs(1)
subsystem within IceBBS.  With the SIG tools one can read messages,
post new messages (perhaps aking for help) and reply to messages
(perhaps providing advice) in any of the SIG areas that are being
carried on the IceBBS systems you call.  Note that these SIGs can
either be local only to a particular BBS or may be broadcast around the
world either through FidoNet or USENET.  The IceBBS support software
enables a sysop to configure FidoNet and USENET areas as being read
only(2) or fully read write.


 @{" Subscription " Link "Subscription"}         Selecting the SIGs you want to read
 @{" All-Sub " Link "All-Sub"}              To read all the SIGs or just your subscription
 @{" Reading new " Link "Reading new"}          Reading new postings
 @{" Reading threaded " Link "Reading threaded"}     Threaded reading to explore a topic
 @{" Searching " Link "Searching"}            Searching for particular messages
 @{" High counter " Link "High counter"}         Remembering what you read last
 @{" Posting " Link "Posting"}              Entering a new message into a SIG
 @{" Replying " Link "Replying"}             Entering your comments on an existing message
 @{" Quoting " Link "Quoting"}              Aids to cite the original message
 @{" Changing SIGs " Link "Changing SIGs"}        How to move between the SIGs
 @{" Kill filters " Link "Kill filters"}         Filtering out messages by author and subject
 @{" Private " Link "Private"}              Replying to a message in private
 @{" Moderator functions " Link "Moderator functions"}  Extra controls to maintain a SIG

   The @{b}Sigs@{ub} button activates the on-line reader, so named as it allows
one to read the SIGs directly while connected to the BBS. Since reading
a high volume news group this way can take up a considerable amount of
time an alternative exists that allows one to quickly download SIGs and
read them off-line (see @{"Batch SIGs" Link "Batch SIGs"}).  The on-line reader initially
opens two windows on the IceTERM screen.  One of these is a text
display window where the text of the current message is displayed for
you to read and the other is a control panel that provides the
additional buttons you need to use the SIGs system.

   As the windows for the on-line SIG reader are being opened by
IceTERM a list of all the SIGs that are available on the BBS is being
transferred to the directory specified by the @{b}MESSROOT@{ub} tool type (see
@{"Message Bases" Link "Message Bases"}).  Once the file has been transferred the gadgets will
unghost and the SIG reader will be ready for use.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The term @{i}SIG@{ui} is an abbreviation for special interest group,
which in the computer world is not a political lobby group, but rather
a group of people who share a common interest and wish to discuss it.

   (2)  If the sysop does this postings may still be made to the SIG
but they will remain local to the BBS.


@EndNode

@Node "Subscription" "iceterm.guide/Subscription"
@Next "All-Sub"
@Prev "SIGs"
@Toc "SIGs"

Subscribing to SIGs
-------------------

   About the first thing you should do is to select the SIGs you wish
to subscribe to (that is the ones you will be reading on a regular
basis).  To do this click on the subscribe gadget and a pair of list
windows will appear.

   In one window is a list of all the SIGs that are available on this
BBS, in the other is the list of SIGs that you are currently subscribed
to.  By clicking on the SIG names you can add new SIGs to your
subscription list and remove unwanted ones from it.  When you have
finished changing your subscription click on the close window gadget of
one of the SIG list windows and a confirmation requester will appear to
check that you want to save the changes.


@EndNode

@Node "All-Sub" "iceterm.guide/All-Sub"
@Next "Reading new"
@Prev "Subscription"
@Toc "SIGs"

All or subscribed
-----------------

   Once you have subscribed to the SIGs you wish to read you can read
just those SIGs by making sure the subscription mode button says @{b}Sub@{ub}
instead of @{b}All@{ub}.  When this button is set to @{b}All@{ub} the SIG reader will
cycle through all the SIGs that are on the BBS.  The state of this
button can be saved for future sessions by snapshoting (see
@{"Window positioning" Link "Window positioning"}) the window.


@EndNode

@Node "Reading new" "iceterm.guide/Reading new"
@Next "Reading threaded"
@Prev "All-Sub"
@Toc "SIGs"

Reading new messages
--------------------

   Reading messages is generally accomplished by using the two buttons
marked: @{b}<<@{ub} and @{b}>>@{ub}, which take you to the previous and next message
(respectively) in the chronological order of posting. Note that these,
and the other buttons, can be bound to keyboard equivalents of your
choice(1).  Normally one clicks on the @{b}>>@{ub} button to read all the new
postings in a SIG, when the last message has been read the next click
on the @{b}>>@{ub} button will take you to the next SIG.  Which SIG this is
depends on whether you are in the read all SIGs (the @{b}All@{ub} button) or read
only subscribed SIGs (the @{b}Sub@{ub} button) mode.  Most users will configure
the on-line reader to the @{i}read subscribed SIGs@{ui} mode.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Currently available only in the OLR.


@EndNode

@Node "Reading threaded" "iceterm.guide/Reading threaded"
@Next "Searching"
@Prev "Reading new"
@Toc "SIGs"

Reading threaded
----------------

   There is also a fully threaded message read facility available.
This is accessed by the buttons marked: @{b}Prev@{ub}, @{b}Next@{ub}, @{b}Child@{ub}, and @{b}Parent@{ub}.
This may be used at any time, even while reading messages with the @{b}<<@{ub}
and @{b}>>@{ub} buttons.  In fact, the threaded read is perhaps most useful when
you need to step backwards and read through the messages which led to a
particular reply.

   The BBS maintains several links between messages.  When a new message
is posted to the BBS it is entered into a particular SIG as an
isolated(1) message.  This message remains isolated in the SIG until
someone decides to reply to it.  At this point the new reply is entered
into the SIG as a new message and is linked (threaded) to the message
that it was a reply to, by the parent and child links.  Now the
original posting's @{b}Child@{ub} button will no longer be ghosted; and when
pressed, will take the reader to the first reply to it.  Conversely,
the reply's @{b}Parent@{ub} button will not be ghosted; and when pressed, will
take you to the original posting that prompted the reply.

   If any additional replies are made to the original posting their
@{b}Parent@{ub} buttons will all point back to the one original message.
However, the @{b}Child@{ub} button on the original message still only points at
the first reply.  To see the other replies to the original message you
use the @{b}Child@{ub} button to go to the first reply and then use the @{b}Next@{ub} and
@{b}Prev@{ub} buttons to look at the rest of the replies.  All the replies to
the original message are linked together in a ring, so by pressing the
@{b}Next@{ub} message button one sees the replies in the order of posting (from
oldest to newest); while by using the @{b}Prev@{ub} button one sees the replies
in the reverse order of posting (from newest to oldest).

   All the original postings in a SIG are also linked together in a
ring by the @{b}Next@{ub} and @{b}Prev@{ub} buttons.  Effectively the messages created by
posting (rather than replying) form the backbone of the SIG and the
messages created by replying to other messages form the ribs and
meat(2) attached to this backbone.

   Now what happens when someone replies to a message that is itself a
reply?  In this case the new reply is entered as a @{i}child@{ui} of the
original reply.  So when you are reading the original reply you will
find that @{i}both@{ui} its @{b}Parent@{ub} (which takes you to the original posting) and
its @{b}Child@{ub} buttons are unghosted.  Now, if you click on the @{b}Child@{ub} button
you will be taken to the first reply (possibly the first of a chain of
replies) to this message (which itself is a reply).  At this lower
level the @{b}Parent@{ub} buttons take you back to the original reply.

   The buttons in the control panel ghost and unghost as you select
different messages to read.  The states of these buttons act as extra
visual clues about the message.  For example:

   @{b}*@{ub} If the @{b}Parent@{ub} button is ghosted it means that this message is not
     a reply to any other message, since it has no parent.  This means
     that it is either an original posting or it is a reply to a
     message that has since been removed from the BBS(3),

   @{b}*@{ub} If the @{b}Parent@{ub} button is not ghosted it means that this message is
     a reply to some other message on the BBS.  If there are any other
     messages that are replies to this same message then you can read
     them too by using the @{b}Next@{ub} and @{b}Prev@{ub} buttons,

   @{b}*@{ub} If the @{b}Child@{ub} button is ghosted then there are no replies to this
     message,

   @{b}*@{ub} If the @{b}Child@{ub} button is not ghosted then there are replies to this
     message and you can read the first of them by clicking on the
     @{b}Child@{ub} button and any additional replies can then be read by
     using the @{b}Next@{ub} and @{b}Prev@{ub} buttons.

   Feel free to browse the history behind interesting messages by
backing up to them by either using the @{b}Parent@{ub} or @{b}Prev@{ub} buttons as
appropriate.  When you have obtained the information you needed you can
resume reading new messages by pressing the @{b}>>@{ub} button.  This system was
designed to allow a free mixture of threaded and sequential reading to
increase the usefulness of a BBS as a message exchange system.
Additional features like the ability to mark key messages as permanent,
delete junk messages and to search for keywords also serve to further
this goal.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Despite the term @{i}isolated@{ui} the message can still be read by
using the normal non-threaded read, or by doing a threaded read along
the root (posting) level of messages in the SIG by using the @{b}Next@{ub} and
@{b}Prev@{ub} keys.

   (2)  Of course if you are vegetarian you might use the classical
tree analogy where the messages created by posting form the trunk of
the tree and the replies form the branches and leaves.

   (3)  Every so often the BBS trims the message bases by removing old
messages and ones that have been deleted by the moderators, when a root
posting is removed any replies to it become orphaned and are thus
elevated to posting status (that is they are linked into the backbone
chain of the SIG and their parent buttons will be ghosted).


@EndNode

@Node "Searching" "iceterm.guide/Searching"
@Next "High counter"
@Prev "Reading threaded"
@Toc "SIGs"

Searching for a message
-----------------------

   On top of the message browsing buttons described previously some
additional message locating tools are accessed through the @{b}Goto Msg@{ub}
button.  Clicking on this opens another mini-control panel containing
buttons that can be used to go to the first message posted after a
particular date and time or to search for messages containing the given
text in the subject, author or even message body.  The go to message
window can be left open all the time, or opened and closed as needed.
It always locates messages within the currently selected SIG, so to
search several SIGs for the same thing you will need to open the Goto
SIG window as well and use both windows.

   To go to a message posted after a particular date or time you use the
buttons in the top half of the go to message window.  The buttons with
the @{b}+@{ub} in their label increase the target date (move it towards the
future) and the buttons with the @{b}-@{ub} in their label decrease the target
date (move it towards the past).  You adjust the date you are looking
for by clicking on these buttons until the date that is displayed looks
right and then you hit the @{b}Go@{ub} button and the message reader will take
you to the first message posted on or after the date and time you have
specified.  This has been set up in this fashion since one often seems
to think in terms like "I saw something like that a few days ago.."

   The go to message window also contains a pair of buttons marked @{b}First@{ub}
and @{b}Last@{ub}.  These are used to move you to the very oldest message in the
current SIG, or the very newest respectively.  No date or search string
need be entered, just hit the appropriate button.

   The go to message window also provides the ability to locate messages
by a case insensitive search of their contents.  These contents include
the full message itself and the subject and author lines.  To use this
feature you hit the @{b}Search@{ub} button and a text string entry gadget will
appear.  Type the string of characters or even a phrase you want to
search for and hit return.  Now the search text has been set you can
search for a message containing that text, either previous to the
currently displayed message by clicking on the @{b}<@{ub} button or posted after
the current message by clicking on the @{b}>@{ub} button.  Clicking on these
buttons a second time will move you to the second message in which the
search string occurs, and so on.

   This search facility can also be used to search a SIG for messages
addressed to you, just enter your name in the search string and find
yourself.


@EndNode

@Node "High counter" "iceterm.guide/High counter"
@Next "Posting"
@Prev "Searching"
@Toc "SIGs"

The high message counter
------------------------

   There is a button that selects between @{b}New@{ub} and @{b}Manual@{ub}.  In practice
this is seldom used, in fact its only real use is when you quickly want
to set your high read mark pointer (the counter that tells the BBS what
the most recent message you have read in a SIG is) manually to skip
over a bunch of messages.  To do this you set the button to @{b}Manual@{ub} mode
and then use the @{b}Prev@{ub} or @{b}Next@{ub} buttons to go to the end of the SIG (or
better yet use the @{b}Goto Msg@{ub} button to select today's date and goto it).
If the gadget is set to the @{b}New@{ub} position then only the @{b}>>@{ub} button will
affect the high read mark location.  This is so that if you happen to
follow an interesting thread of replies @{i}forward@{ui} in time, while reading
new messages, you don't skip over any new messages that do not happen to
be in that thread.  Sound confusing?  Don't fret, just leave the button
set to the @{b}New@{ub} position all the time and all will be well.


@EndNode

@Node "Posting" "iceterm.guide/Posting"
@Next "Replying"
@Prev "High counter"
@Toc "SIGs"

Posting a message
-----------------

   To post a new message of your own into a SIG all you need do is to
click on the @{b}Post@{ub} button.  When this is done IceTERM will start up the
editor you have specified with the @{b}EDITOR@{ub} tool type (see @{"Your Editor" Link "Your Editor"}).
You enter the text of your message into the editor and when you are
done you save the file (IceTERM has already given it a name) and exit
from the editor.  A requester will now appear on IceTERM's screen
asking you if you really want to post this message, and if you still
do, click on the @{b}Yes@{ub} button.  IceTERM will then proceed to ask you for
the subject of your posting and the name of the person it is addressed
to.  Once these questions have been answered the message will be sent
to the BBS and entered into the current SIG as the most recent message.


@EndNode

@Node "Replying" "iceterm.guide/Replying"
@Next "Quoting"
@Prev "Posting"
@Toc "SIGs"

Replying to a message
---------------------

   To reply to the current message click on the @{b}Reply@{ub} button. When this
is done IceTERM will start up the editor you have specified with the
@{b}EDITOR@{ub} tool type (see @{"Your Editor" Link "Your Editor"}) and preload the editor's buffer with
the message you are replying to.  The message may be formatted to
indicate that it is quoted (see @{"Quoting" Link "Quoting"}).

   You can enter the text of your message into the editor and even
include bits of the original message to help clairify your thoughts.
When you are done you save the file (IceTERM has already given it a
name) and exit from the editor.  A requester will now appear on
IceTERM's screen asking you if you really want to post this reply, and
if you still do, click on the @{b}Yes@{ub} button.  IceTERM will then proceed to
ask you to supply a new subject for your reply if you want the subject
to be the same as the original message just hit return, otherwise enter
the new subject. Unlike the posting of a new message IceTERM will not
ask you for the name of the person it is addressed to, as a reply is
assumed to be addressed to the author of the message being replied to.
Once these questions have been answered the message will be sent to the
BBS and entered into the current SIG as the most recent message and
will be chained onto the list of replies to the original message.


@EndNode

@Node "Quoting" "iceterm.guide/Quoting"
@Next "Changing SIGs"
@Prev "Replying"
@Toc "SIGs"

Message quoting
---------------

   When replying (see @{"Replying" Link "Replying"}) to a message you can choose to have the
message pre-quoted before it is loaded into the editor.  To do this you
use the @{b}>@{ub} and the @{b}-@{ub} buttons.  These two buttons allow you to edit the
string that is inserted at the beginning of each line to quote the
message and to customize the line at the beginning of the message that
states who the original author was and on what date he made the
posting.  There is an additional multi-state button that selects
between @{b}None@{ub}, @{b}Quote@{ub}, @{b}Header@{ub} and @{b}Both@{ub}.  These modes specify:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}None@{ub} no quoting or header is to be done,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Quote@{ub} only the quoting of each line is to be done,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Header@{ub} only the author/date header is to be included,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Both@{ub} both the header and quoting of each line is to be done.

   Some other programs exist to do this sort of reply quoting, one of
these is called IceIQle which stands for: Integrated Communications
Environment Initial Quoter and Lexicographical Editorializer.  This was
written by Kevin Huculak(1) and it is freely distributable.  From
Kevin's documentation:

     IceIQle can generate completely customizable taglines and
     signatures with any Off-Line based message reader that uses an
     external text editor, AND in conjunction with the IceTERM BBS
     software, Copyright 1993 Stephen Vermeulen or AmiQWK, also
     provides header strings and initialed quoting with paragraph
     wordwrap. Initialed quoting is of the form:

          KH> Original Message

     It also works with IceTERM when quoting EMail and SIGS messages
     On-Line.

     The customized header strings, tag lines and signatures can be read
     randomly or sequentially from a text file of your favorites.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Email: Kevin_Huculak@amuc.mtroyal.ab.ca


@EndNode

@Node "Changing SIGs" "iceterm.guide/Changing SIGs"
@Next "Kill filters"
@Prev "Quoting"
@Toc "SIGs"

Changing SIGs
-------------

   From time to time you will want to change the SIG you are reading.
The on-line reader does this for you automatically when you reach the
end of new messages and hit the @{b}>>@{ub} button a second time.  In this case
it switches to the next SIG in your list of SIGs (see @{"All-Sub" Link "All-Sub"}) and
positions you at the last message you read in that SIG (for
continuity).  Hence, by just clicking on the @{b}>>@{ub} button you will
eventually read all the new messages in all the SIGs you are interested
in.

   There are three other buttons in the on-line reader's control panel
that allow you to move around the SIGs.  These are @{b}Prev SIG@{ub}, @{b}Next SIG@{ub}
and @{b}Goto SIG@{ub}.  These all work with the currently selected list of SIGs
(see @{"All-Sub" Link "All-Sub"}).  The @{b}Next SIG@{ub} takes you down the list one SIG, the @{b}Prev
SIG@{ub} button takes you up the list one SIG, and the @{b}Goto SIG@{ub} button opens
a window containing the names of all the SIGs in the list and allows
you to go to a SIG by just clicking on its name.


@EndNode

@Node "Kill filters" "iceterm.guide/Kill filters"
@Next "Private"
@Prev "Changing SIGs"
@Toc "SIGs"

The kill filters
----------------

   The on-line reader also sports a kill filter system.  This allows
you to save time by preventing the BBS from sending you messages that
have subjects or authors which are listed in your kill filters. There
are 6 buttons to control the message system's two kill filters. They
are arranged in two columns: on the left are the buttons for the author
killer and on the right are the buttons for the subject killer.  The
@{b}Kill@{ub} button (in either column) is used to add the current message's
author or subject to the kill filter that column controls. The @{b}Edit@{ub}
button is used to review your kill filters and to remove any unwanted
kill entries so you can see those subjects or authors again.  The @{b}Auth@{ub}
and @{b}Subj@{ub} buttons are toggle gadgets that are used to enable and disable
the kill filters (which you can do at any time).  The names and
subjects in your kill filters are stored in your @{b}MESSROOT@{ub} tool type and
when you open the on-line reader, or when you add another subject or
author to the kill filter or when you edit a kill filter the kill
filters will be sent to the BBS.  The BBS then will screen out messages
that match the activated kill filters and on those messages it only has
to transmit the header across the phone lines (so the threading
information is still valid), but you save time because the body of the
killed message is not transferred.


@EndNode

@Node "Private" "iceterm.guide/Private"
@Next "Moderator functions"
@Prev "Kill filters"
@Toc "SIGs"

Private replies
---------------

   The @{b}Private@{ub} button is not currently implemented but is intended to
be used to mark a reply or posting as private to the addressee, for
those networks like FidoNet which support @{i}private@{ui} messages within a
public conference area.  I emphasise the word private because in these
public networks the @{i}only@{ui} way to ensure that your message is only read
by the intended addressee is to send it in encrypted form (see
@{"Encryption" Link "Encryption"} regarding the use of PGP for encryption).


@EndNode

@Node "Moderator functions" "iceterm.guide/Moderator functions"
@Prev "Private"
@Toc "SIGs"

Moderator functions
-------------------

   There are a set of extra buttons intended to be used by trusted users
who have been granted moderator(1) access to some of the SIGs.  If you
have been granted moderator access to a SIG(2) you will find that the
@{b}Move@{ub}, @{b}Delete@{ub} and @{b}Perm@{ub} buttons work, otherwise you will find that
clicking on them just causes an error message requester to appear on
your screen.

   The @{b}Move@{ub} button is used to move the current message from this SIG
into another SIG.  When you click on the button a list of all the SIGs
on the BBS will appear, you can then select the name of the SIG you
want this message moved to.  The BBS will then copy the message over to
the new SIG and will mark it as deleted from the current SIG.  If you
wanted to copy the message into the new SIG but leave it in the current
SIG as well, all you have to do is undelete it now by clicking on the
@{b}Delete@{ub} button to restore it.

   The @{b}Delete@{ub} button is used to delete a message from a SIG.  This can
be used to remove messages that the moderator considers inappropriate
for publication in the SIG.  To delete a message just click on the
@{b}Delete@{ub} button.  The message is not physically deleted from the SIG
until the next time that the BBS SIG trimming utility runs(3) and so,
until the trimmer runs the message may be restored by a moderator
clicking on the @{b}Delete@{ub} button a second time. When a message is marked
as deleted it will not be visible to or downloadable by any user.

   The @{b}Perm@{ub} button is used to mark a message as being permanent.  This
helps to improve the usefulness of the SIG system as a reference tool
by marking useful messages as permanent.  Then when the message trimmer
runs it will leave them in place, but age out the less-useful messages
that were not marked as permanent.  Note that to make a message
deletable again you just click on the @{b}Perm@{ub} button a second time.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  As the name implies a moderator is someone who watches over the
postings and replies in a newsgroup to make certain that the users are
staying on topic and not causing undue pain and suffering to each other.

   (2)  Moderator access can be granted by the sysop on a SIG by SIG
basis.

   (3)  This is sysop configurable, but typically will be run once a
day.


@EndNode

@Node "Batch SIGs" "iceterm.guide/Batch SIGs"
@Next "Conference"
@Prev "SIGs"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Batch downloading of SIGs
=========================

   The @{b}Batch SIG@{ub} button is used to start a batch download of all the
new messages in all the SIGs you are subscribed to. The tool works
largely on its own automatically downloading any new SIG messages onto
the your disk and uploading any new messages |hat you may have created
by posting or replying with the IceOLR utility. As the tool does its
work it will print status messages in the window showing the SIG
currently being downloaded, the remaining bytes in that SIG and the
total number of bytes transfered so far.  When it is done it will close
down automatically. Note: it only processes the SIGs to which you
subscribe.


 @{" The OLR " Link "The OLR"} 
 @{" Interrupting batch SIGs " Link "Interrupting batch SIGs"} 
 @{" Autostarting batch SIGs " Link "Autostarting batch SIGs"} 

   When you first subscribe to a SIG the BBS will only send you the
last two days of messages in that SIG.  To retrieve earlier messages
see @{"Interrupting batch SIGs" Link "Interrupting batch SIGs"}.

   There is one important thing that must be done while configuring
IceTERM for the batch SIGs function to work properly, this is to set up
the @{b}MESSROOT@{ub} tool type (see @{"Message Bases" Link "Message Bases"}).  If this tool type is not
set up, the system will default to sending the messages into the @{b}RAM:@{ub}
disk and the important files that log when you last connected and
downloaded messages will be lost when you next reboot, this will lead
to re-downloading a lot of messages.


@EndNode

@Node "The OLR" "iceterm.guide/The OLR"
@Next "Interrupting batch SIGs"
@Prev "Batch SIGs"
@Toc "Batch SIGs"

The OLR
-------

   To read, post and reply to the messages downloaded from the SIGs
system you use an off-line message reader.  This allows you to connect,
download messages and then log off quickly minimizing connection time.
There are two programs currently available for reading SIGs messages
while off-line: @{b}IceOLR@{ub} (1) and @{b}IceReader@{ub} (2).  The old SIGs system,
which is no longer in use, had three message readers: @{b}READ@{ub}, @{b}VBBSReader@{ub}
(3) and @{b}GPReader@{ub} (4) as well as a separate trimmer program called @{b}AGE@{ub},
these are no longer useful and should be ignored.

   IceOLR is documented and distributed separately from IceTERM as it
tends to get updated at odd times.  The IceOLR does contain all the
functions of the on-line reader, plus it contains a number of
additional capabilities that may never be put into the on-line reader
because of code size and execution speed constraints(5).  IceOLR does
allow you to edit your subscription list, so once you have installed
the IceOLR you almost never need to go back to using the on-line reader.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  @{b}IceOLR@{ub} stands for Off Line Reader and its a freely
distributable part of the IceTERM package.

   (2)  Written by Yannick Koehler, an IceBBS sysop from Quebec.

   (3)  Part of Ian Gunn's CanDo IceBBS support package.

   (4)  From Greg Pringle, an avid local user.

   (5)  Included in the latter category is the display which shows an
overview of the current SIG sorted by subject, author, addressee or
posting date which has proved to be a popular addition to the IceOLR.


@EndNode

@Node "Interrupting batch SIGs" "iceterm.guide/Interrupting batch SIGs"
@Next "Autostarting batch SIGs"
@Prev "The OLR"
@Toc "Batch SIGs"

Interrupting batch SIG downloads
--------------------------------

   Batch SIG downloads are interruptable, this can happen in three ways.
First, the phone connection could be broken for some reason (this
includes the BBS disconnecting you for running out of time); second,
you might click on the batch SIG window's close button; and third, you
might hit the @{b}Interrupt@{ub} button.  In all three cases the message
download is fully resumable and the only retransmission that is
required is the one message that was being transmitted at the time the
transmission was stopped and some handshaking overhead to find out
which SIGs need updating.  To resume a batch SIG download that was
interrupted all you do is to reconnect to the BBS and click on the
@{b}Batch SIG@{ub} button.

   When a batch SIG transfer is stopped by pressing the @{b}Interrupt@{ub}
button the additional ghosted buttons will unghost and give you some
extra control over the download process. This functionality was added
primarily to address the problem with downloading the whole BBS message
base when you are subscribing to a new SIG and also to allow you to
grab older messages which are still on the BBS but for some reason are
not on your machine and you want to read them.  This is implemented
through the extra buttons, of which there are five.  The only one that
is unghosted initially is the @{b}Interrupt@{ub} button, you push this when you
want to interrupt a batch download to use some of the other options.
When the @{b}Interrupt@{ub} is hit the download will stop and the other four
buttons will unghost, you can hit the @{b}Change Date@{ub} and @{b}Change SIGs@{ub}
buttons to describe what you want done.  The date button will bring up a
date selector which you can use to determine how far back in time you
want to go(1).

   The @{b}Change SIGs@{ub} button will summon a pair of windows with which you
can make @{i}temporary@{ui} changes to your current subscription list (allowing
you to just request one SIG or even request SIGs you don't normally
subscribe to).  Once the dates and SIGs to be downloaded are selected
you hit the @{b}Start@{ub} button and the process starts again.  If you decide
that hitting the @{b}Interrupt@{ub} button was just a bad idea, hit either the
@{b}Cancel@{ub} or the close window buttons.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  For a high volume SIG which you are just subscribing to you
might only want to go back one or two days. Two days is the default for
new subscriptions.


@EndNode

@Node "Autostarting batch SIGs" "iceterm.guide/Autostarting batch SIGs"
@Prev "Interrupting batch SIGs"
@Toc "Batch SIGs"

Auto starting batch SIGs
------------------------

   Batch SIGs can be automatically started by IceTERM by including the
@{b}AUTOSTART=batch@{ub} tool type (see @{"Autostart" Link "Autostart"}) in the IceTERM icon.  Once
you have done this IceTERM will start a batch SIG download as soon as
you log into the system and the downloader window will close once it is
done, so you can make the message transfer completely automatic.

   Batch SIGs should abort automatically when disk space is exhausted
(you will probably have to click on the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button of at least one
disk full requester), and when you go to resume in a later session the
only extra resending will be the message that was being written when
the disk ran out of space (the old SIGs used to have to retransmit the
entire SIG that was being downloaded when the problem occured).


@EndNode

@Node "Conference" "iceterm.guide/Conference"
@Next "Get files"
@Prev "Batch SIGs"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Confer
======

   The confer function implements a live, real-time, chat or
conferencing function between all the users who may be on-line at the
same time.  When the confer button is hit two extra windows will appear
on the screen.

   The user window is the one into which you type whatever you have to
say to the other users who are on-line.  This window has a limited
editing capability (by moving with the cursor keys and over typing)
until the return key is hit.  When this is done the full line is sent
to the conference server on the BBS to be sent to all the other users
who are on-line in the conference system.

   The user text entry window also contains two string gadgets in the
lower border.  These are used to enter two strings called the
@{i}hailstring@{ui} and @{i}tailstring@{ui}.  When you hit return your IceTERM
program will insert the hailstring at the start of the message and
append the tailstring to the end of the message.  These two strings are
useful when setting up fancy ANSI text effects (colours and italics) to
make your messages distinctive, and for defining a prompt sequence(1)
that identifies your messages. The tailstring may seem a bit useless,
but it can be used to put a cleanup escape sequence into the message so
that your special text effects do not interfere with other users'
effects.

   New messages will appear in the conference window.  Since the
conference system uses quite large packets it is able to transmit the
text more efficiently than the chat function, so it can be faster to
use the conference between the sysop and a user if there is a file
transfer taking place at the same time.

   When the conference is first opened the BBS will send the user some
recent postings to the conference subsystem so that the user can catch
up with the recent chatter(2), the number of old messages that will be
sent is determined by the conference history setting on the BBS machine
which the sysop can configure.

   Since the conference window multitasks with the rest of the IceTERM
tools it is quite safe to open the conference window up and then go
away and read messages or download files while waiting for someone to
enter the conference.  One of the more common annoyances is a user who
enters the conference and then immediately leaves it, without waiting
for others to join him.  To prompt other users to enter the conference
there is a paging button in the @{b}Monitor@{ub} tool (see @{"Monitor" Link "Monitor"}).

   To capture the contents of a conference hit the capture button @{b}Log@{ub}
which will then change to @{b}Logging@{ub} to indicate the conference is being
logged to a file.  Which file you ask? By default it will go to
@{b}RAM:CONF.LOG@{ub}, but if you include the @{b}CONFLOG@{ub} tool type you can specify
a different file name.

   There are several special icon tool types (see @{"Conference tool" Link "Conference tool"}) for
the conference system.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Something a few characters long, like your initials, so others
can see who is speaking.

   (2)  And also see who else has been logging in and out during the
day.


@EndNode

@Node "Get files" "iceterm.guide/Get files"
@Next "Send file"
@Prev "Conference"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Get files
=========

   The get files function is perhaps the most used function on any
IceBBS based system.  This is the @{i}directory utility@{ui} with which you can
browse around the file system of the BBS and select files for
downloading.  When the get files button is clicked; three windows will
appear and the modem will start receiving the root directory names from
the BBS.  Once this is finished the directory window will be refreshed
and the names of the root directories on the BBS will appear.


 @{" Changing directories " Link "Changing directories"}    Moving about the file tree
 @{" Sorting files " Link "Sorting files"}           Viewing by name and date
 @{" Confirmation " Link "Confirmation"}            Controlling those requesters
 @{" Short description " Link "Short description"}       The date display format and short description
 @{" Directory downloading " Link "Directory downloading"}   Downloading a whole directory tree
 @{" Downloading " Link "Downloading"}             Controling the file downloads
 @{" Download directory " Link "Download directory"}      So where do all those files go?
 @{" Download resume " Link "Download resume"}         Finishing an incomplete download
 @{" Downloading email " Link "Downloading email"}       Getting files that people send you
 @{" Finding files " Link "Finding files"}           Searching for files on the BBS
 @{" Keep Desc " Link "Keep Desc"}               Keeping file descriptions


@EndNode

@Node "Changing directories" "iceterm.guide/Changing directories"
@Next "Sorting files"
@Prev "Get files"
@Toc "Get files"

Changing directories
--------------------

   When you select the @{b}Get Files@{ub} button, one of the windows that opens
displays the names of directories that are on the BBS.  When the window
first appears, it does not have any text in the top bar of the window.
To move to a particular directory, click on its name in the directory
window.  A @{b}Please Wait...@{ub} message will appear on the get files panel
while the BBS sends you the information.

   The title bar of the directory window will change to reflect the
current directory that you are looking at.  If there are any files in
this directory that can be downloaded by the user they will appear in
the files window.  If there are further directories within the current
one, they will be displayed in the directory window.

   To move back up the directory tree you hit the @{b}Parent@{ub} button.


@EndNode

@Node "Sorting files" "iceterm.guide/Sorting files"
@Next "Confirmation"
@Prev "Changing directories"
@Toc "Get files"

Sorting files
-------------

   The file display window can display its contents sorted either by
name (alphabetically) or by file date.  The button that toggles between
@{b}Name@{ub} and @{b}Date@{ub} is using to determine the method with which the names are
sorted(1).  Sorting by date is a convenient way to see what files have
been recently added to the BBS, for this reason the newest files appear
at the top of the list.

   You can save the way you like to have the files sorted by using the
@{b}Snapshot@{ub} (see @{"The snapshot menu" Link "The snapshot menu"}) function.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The sort method only affects the files list.  Directories are
always sorted alphabetically.


@EndNode

@Node "Confirmation" "iceterm.guide/Confirmation"
@Next "Short description"
@Prev "Sorting files"
@Toc "Get files"

Controlling the requesters
--------------------------

   There are several mode control buttons in the get files control
window.  The first two are the @{b}Describe@{ub} and @{b}Confirm@{ub} buttons.  By
default these buttons are selected (they appear @{i}pushed in@{ui}) if you
deselect either one and snapshot the window (see @{"The main buttons" Link "The main buttons"}) they
will appear in the desired state when you next use IceTERM.  The
@{b}Describe@{ub} button controls whether the IceTERM program will request a
full file description when you click on a file name.  If the button is
selected, IceTERM will request the description when you click on a file
name.

   The @{b}Confirm@{ub} button is used to enable and disable the download
confirmation requester.  If you would like to quickly click on a number
of files to be downloaded and do not want to be bothered by
requesters(1) just disable the requester by deselecting the confirm
button.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Maybe you have a V.34 modem and you can readily download
anything and everything.


@EndNode

@Node "Short description" "iceterm.guide/Short description"
@Next "Directory downloading"
@Prev "Confirmation"
@Toc "Get files"

Date format
-----------

   The @{b}YMD@{ub} button is used to select between two different formats of
date display, a concise one and an expanded one, respectively.

Short description
-----------------

   The @{b}?@{ub} button will (when selected) allow the BBS to send IceTERM the
short file descriptions to be displayed in the files window.  When
these are received they will show up to the right of the file names.
Short descriptions are assigned to files either by the user when the
file is uploaded or by the sysop when the file is validated before
being made publicly available.

   You can save the way these buttons are set by using the @{b}Snapshot@{ub}
(see @{"The snapshot menu" Link "The snapshot menu"}) function.


@EndNode

@Node "Directory downloading" "iceterm.guide/Directory downloading"
@Next "Download directory"
@Prev "Short description"
@Toc "Get files"

Downloading a directory tree
----------------------------

   The @{b}File Mode@{ub} button selects between downloading individual files
and complete directory trees (when it is set to @{b}Dir. Mode@{ub}).  Since the
BBS supports downloading directories, CDROMs such as the uncompressed
Fish Disk CD are readily used with IceBBS.  When the button is set to
@{b}Dir. Mode@{ub} any attempt to select a directory will be recognized as a
command to download that directory.  Hence, you cannot change
directories (except by using the @{b}Parent@{ub} button) while in the directory
download mode.  The directory download mode will also download any
subdirectories within the selected directory and their contents
(including other subdirectories).  The directory download mode is
resumable, so long as you leave the interrupted directory and its
contents undisturbed in your download directory (see
@{"Download directory" Link "Download directory"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Download directory" "iceterm.guide/Download directory"
@Next "Downloading"
@Prev "Directory downloading"
@Toc "Get files"

The download directory
----------------------

   The @{b}Set DOWNDIR@{ub} button is used to override the @{b}DOWNDIR@{ub} tool type
(see @{"Basic Tool types" Link "Basic Tool types"}).  If you need to start downloading to a new
directory(1) or one other than that specified by the @{b}DOWNDIR@{ub} tool type
in the IceTERM icon you can click on this and then enter the name of
the directory in the string requester that pops up.

   The directory to which files go is by default @{b}RAM:@{ub}. If you download
a second file of the same name, at the same time as the first file is
being downloaded, the second file will be sent to your @{b}T:@{ub} directory
(which may be overridden by the @{b}TEMPDIR@{ub} tool type, see
@{"Basic Tool types" Link "Basic Tool types"}).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Perhaps if you run out of disk space.


@EndNode

@Node "Downloading" "iceterm.guide/Downloading"
@Next "Download resume"
@Prev "Download directory"
@Toc "Get files"

Controlling the download
------------------------

   To start a file download just click on the name of the file to be
downloaded.  Then depending on the settings of the @{b}Describe@{ub} and @{b}Confirm@{ub}
buttons (see @{"Confirmation" Link "Confirmation"}) a confirmation window may appear, if it does
click on its @{b}Yes@{ub} gadget; also, a description window containing a long
description of the file may also appear (not all files have one), this
gives you extra information about the file which may help you make up
your mind about downloading it. Once you have confirmed that you want
to download the file a small window will appear containing the name of
the file that is being downloaded and the number of bytes left to be
downloaded and a @{b}Pause@{ub} button.  The file will be written to your
download directory (see @{"Download directory" Link "Download directory"}).

   Once a download has started you can pick additional files for
download, leave the get files windows on the screen or close the get
files windows all together.  If additional files are selected for
download they will start transferring almost immediately.  Each file
will be given a turn on the line, about 5000 bytes(1) will be
transferred and then the next file will get a turn.  The downloading
system was designed to do this so that the user can start a large
download and then if he found a another file that was needed quickly he
can just click on it and get it at the same time as the long download.
The @{b}Pause@{ub} button in each of the download windows is used to place that
particular file download on hold, usually so that another download can
be more quickly completed, or so that other BBS operations (like batch
SIG downloads) go faster.  This pausing is not immediate, the
transmission will stop once that download window's server has emptied
its disk buffers.  The size of these buffers varies between IceBBS
systems, those with CDROM drives tend to be larger.

   File downloading is the lowest priority BBS operation that a user can
perform.  This is so that a large file download can be started and then
you can go and do other more interactive tasks on the BBS with little
impact.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The actual amount depends on how the sysop has configured his
IceBBS system, if he has many CDROM drives online he will probably have
increased this amount.


@EndNode

@Node "Download resume" "iceterm.guide/Download resume"
@Next "Downloading email"
@Prev "Downloading"
@Toc "Get files"

Finishing an interrupted download
---------------------------------

   The file download system also supports a resume feature. To get this
to work, just leave the partial files in the download directory (see
@{"Download directory" Link "Download directory"}) and then re-select them for download.  IceTERM will
notice that a file of the same name already exists in the download
directory and will then ask you if you want to resume the download.  If
you do resume then the IceTERM program will request a partial
retransmission from the BBS, the system backs up in the partial file by
about 1000 bytes to prevent any possible corruption due to errors that
may have occurred during the writing of the last few blocks of the
file.  Of course, you should clean out your download directory from
time to time, otherwise you might see this message often.

   Directory downloads may also be resumed, allowing one to easily copy
large directory trees over several connection sessions.


@EndNode

@Node "Downloading email" "iceterm.guide/Downloading email"
@Next "Finding files"
@Prev "Download resume"
@Toc "Get files"

Downloading emailed files
-------------------------

   The email tool can be used to send files to another user of the BBS
(see @{"Emailing a file" Link "Emailing a file"}).  Each user is given a private email directory on
the BBS where her files are stored until she has a chance to download
them.  This special directory is given the name @{b}Email Files...@{ub} and it
appears in the first list of directories that appears when the get
files tool is opened.

   When a file is sent to you by email a message will appear during the
login process alerting you to the file's presence.  You can then use
the get files tool to download the file whenever it is convenient.  All
the standard get files functions work with the emailed files, including
the resume function.  The get files tool will display the name of each
file that has been sent to you along with the name of the person who
sent it in the short description area.

   Once you have successfully downloaded an emailed file you should
delete it from the BBS.  To do this you click on the @{b}Delete File@{ub} button
(so that it is pushed in) and then when you click on the name of a file
IceTERM will ask you if you wish to delete the file from the BBS.  If
you say @{b}Yes@{ub} to this requester the file will be deleted from the BBS and
the get files list will be updated.  You should try not to keep too
many files on the BBS at once in your email directory, since it is
within the sysop's powers to delete files from the accounts of users
who are abusing their privileges at any time...


@EndNode

@Node "Finding files" "iceterm.guide/Finding files"
@Next "Keep Desc"
@Prev "Downloading email"
@Toc "Get files"

Searching for files
-------------------

   IceBBS systems offer two ways to search for files: by contents and
by name.  Both of these are accessed from the @{b}Get Files@{ub} tool using the
@{b}Find@{ub} and @{b}Wild Find@{ub} buttons, shown in the next figure:

The Find button
...............

   When the @{b}Find@{ub} button is pressed it will summon a string requester
where the user types in the string he wants to search for.  These
strings can contain words to be searched for separated by logical
operators.  In the figure I have requested a search for all files
contains @{i}both@{ui} the word "stephen" and the word "vermeulen".  The
searches performed by the @{b}Find@{ub} button include the full contents of all
the files(1).  Normally such a search would take a very long time to
do, but this system uses a pre-computed database that the sysop updates
occasionally, so it actually happens very quickly.

   The result of the above search will appear in a scrolling text window
as shown in the next figure:

If you click on a file name in this window the long description will be
shown (if you have it enabled) and you will be asked if you want to
download the file.

Search engine logical operators
...............................

   The search string will be parsed by the finder and each word within
the string will be searched for in the database.  This produces a table
of files for each word.  The finder can apply several operators to
combine these tables and hence allow you to search for files which must
or may or cannot contain several words.  The operators are:

@{b}A & B@{ub}
     The @{b}&@{ub} (and, intersection) operator takes the lists of words
     contained in the two files and produces a new list containing only
     the words in both files.

@{b}A | B@{ub}
     The @{b}|@{ub} (or, union) operator takes the lists of words contained in
     the two files and produces a new list containing all the words in
     both files.

@{b}A - B@{ub}
     The @{b}-@{ub} (minus, difference) operator takes the lists of words
     contained in file @{b}A@{ub} and removes from that list any words which are
     also contained in file @{b}B@{ub}.

   As well parentheses are available to allow you to group several
operations:

     A & (B - C | (D & F))

will evaluate @{b}D & F@{ub} first to produce @{b}X@{ub}

     A & (B - C | X)

it will then evaluate @{b}B - C@{ub} to produce @{b}Y@{ub}

     A & (Y | X)

it will then evaluate @{b}Y | X@{ub} to produce @{b}Z@{ub}

     A & Z

and will finally evaluate @{b}A & Z@{ub}.

   If there are no parentheses then evaluation proceeds from left to
right as was the case when it evaluated @{b}B - C | X@{ub} above.

The Wild Find button
....................

   One type of search which users have found difficult to do with the
full search function described previously is a simple wild card search
on file names.  This is provided by the @{b}Wild Find@{ub} button(2).

   When you click on the @{b}Wild Find@{ub} button a string requester will
appear as below:

   Into this requester you can enter a valid AmigaDOS wildcard search
pattern and then the tool will search the file databases for any files
whos' names match the pattern.  For example if you enter:

     ice#?.(lha|lzh)

you will see @{b}iceolr@{ub} and @{b}iceterm@{ub} but not @{b}muiicecream@{ub}.  If you enter:

     #?ice#?

   you will see @{b}muiicecream@{ub} as well.  You can use the full set of
pattern matches too, including the @{b}~()|@{ub} type operators.

   This search tool, like the full @{b}Find@{ub} button displays its results in
a scrollable text window.  If you click on a file name in this window
the long description will be shown (if you have it enabled) and you
will be asked if you want to download the file.  The results of the
search are shown in the next figure:

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  In the case of archives (like zip, zoo and lha files) the
search includes all the files within the archives.

   (2)  Inspiration and much goading to implement this is due to Bryan
Ewert who implemented the first version in ARexx to demonstrate how
useful it would be.


@EndNode

@Node "Keep Desc" "iceterm.guide/Keep Desc"
@Prev "Finding files"
@Toc "Get files"

Keeping file descriptions
-------------------------

   If you are an IceBBS sysop then when you download files with the
@{b}Keep Desc@{ub} button pressed in the complete file (including IceBBS header
information) will be sent to you.  If you are not an IceBBS sysop and
you try to do this you will find that the first part of the file will
appear corrupt so you don't want to use this mode.


@EndNode

@Node "Send file" "iceterm.guide/Send file"
@Next "Feedback"
@Prev "Get files"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Send file
=========

   The @{b}Send File@{ub} button is used to send a file from your machine to the
BBS.  Upon clicking the @{b}Send File@{ub} button the standard Amiga file
requester(1) will appear.

   You move about the directory tree using the File Requester's @{b}Parent@{ub}
gadget to go back up the tree and by clicking on directory names to
descend into the directory tree.  You can move to the the top of the
directory tree to see all the disks and assigned names in your system
by clicking on the @{b}Volumes@{ub} button. With the ARP requester you get a
list of all the @{b}Drives@{ub} in your system by either clicking on the drives
gadget or by hitting the menu button on the mouse. The 2.0 requester is
also resizable (the ARP requester is not) by the grab handle in the
bottom right corner.  To send a file you can either single click on the
file and then click on the @{b}Ok@{ub} gadget or you can double click on the
file name.  To exit from the tool you can either hit the cancel button
or the close window gadget.

   Once a file has been selected the BBS will prompt you for both long
and short descriptions to be attached to the file.  When these have
been entered the transmission will start and an additional little
window will show the name of the file being sent and the number of
bytes left to send.  When the file transfer has completed(2) the file
requester will reappear allowing you to select another file. If you
want to send several files at once you can do so by starting the first
and then clicking on the send files button to start a second session.

   It should be noted that on all modems with the exception of the US
Robotics HST modem(3) there is almost no penalty when uploading and
downloading at the same time.  By this I mean that with a 2400 baud
modem (a typical full duplex modem(4)) you will be able to upload at
about 230CPS(5) while still downloading at another file at the same
time at 230CPS.  If your modem is not full duplex the modem has to send
a small amount of data one way, then turn around and send some data in
the other direction.  Because of this constant reversal of the high
speed direction the effective throughput is reduced.

   Tests show that with the HST modem (which should theoretically get
about 700 CPS during bidirectional transfers) one only can get about
350 CPS, so in this case it is best to do all your uploading @{i}and then@{ui}
do all your downloading once the uploads are complete, doing so will
keep the transfer rates in the 1500-1600CPS range.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Under AmigaDOS 1.3 the ARP File Requester will be used instead.

   (2)  Do not click on the close window button of the upload progress
window to close down the system. Instead, wait for the file requester to
reappear and click on its close window or cancel buttons.  The close
window button on the file progress window is intended to be used to
abort an upload.

   (3)  The HST modem is an example of a modem that does not have a
symmetric distribution of send and receive speeds the only other I know
of that may do this is the TeleBit Trailblaizer in PEP mode.

   (4)  Full duplex modems are by far the most common modems these
days, the old 1200, 2400 and the newer V.32, V.32bis and V.34 modems
are examples of these.

   (5)  Characters per second.


@EndNode

@Node "Feedback" "iceterm.guide/Feedback"
@Next "Monitor"
@Prev "Send file"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Feedback
========

   The @{b}Feedback@{ub} menu item activates a simplified message base reader
designed to provide a quick way for the user and sysop to exchange
notes.  This tool was the original message base for IceBBS, and its
design stems from a time when all that was needed was some way for
users to leave feedback and bug reports.  Not much work has been done
on this tool since then and it is showing its age.  When the @{b}Feedback@{ub}
menu item is selected a single console-like window will be opened, the
message text will be displayed therein.

   As soon as feedback has been started the BBS server will bundle up
all the new feedback messages and start sending them to you in one
continuous, uninterrupted stream.  This means that if you take your
time reading the first message the BBS will continue its transmission
and send the second, third and so on.  These messages will be queued in
RAM on your machine and when you step to a new message the display will
be updated a lot faster than most modems are capable of.

   There is a problem with this design.  Because of the message
streaming there is no way(1) for the user to move about the message
base at will, it is purely a @{i}read it once and go onto the next@{ui} type of
reader.  It is unlikely this tool will be improved further as the
inten| is that the SIGs system will replace it entirely (this is also
why the feedback tool no longer has a button in the control window).

   Another example of how old this tool is can be seen in the fact that
it uses keyboard keys for its controls.  The following keys are used:

@{b}SPACE@{ub}
     the space bar is used to page through a long message one screen at
     a time,

@{b}RETURN@{ub}
     the return key is used to step from one message to the next, once
     the end of the current message has been reached.  The reason that
     the return and space keys were not combined into one key is that
     it is very easy to space past the end of the current message and
     there is no way to back up to it again.  This is a problem if you
     wanted to reply to that message,

@{b}P@{ub}
     this is the @{i}post a message@{ui} function.  Upon on hitting the @{b}P@{ub} key
     the message editor that you have selected through the @{b}EDITOR@{ub} tool
     type in the IceTERM icon will appear.  You then type your message
     into this and when it is complete you save it and exit from the
     editor.  IceTERM will recognize when you close the editor and will
     then post the message to IceBBS. Note that if you have problems
     posting a message you should refer to @{"Message problems" Link "Message problems"}.

@{b}R@{ub}
     this is the @{i}reply to current message@{ui} key.  Hitting the @{b}R@{ub} key will
     summon the editor and will load the message you are replying to
     into it.  You can then edit the original message (perhaps quoting
     relevant sections) and when you are done you save and exit just
     like with the posting function.  If you are having problems refer
     to @{"Message problems" Link "Message problems"},

@{b}K@{ub}
     this is the @{i}message keeping@{ui} function.  One of the IceTERM icon
     tool types is the @{b}KEEPFILE@{ub} item.  You use it to specify the name
     of a file where you wish to save (or keep) useful messages.  Every
     time you hit the @{b}K@{ub} key a copy of the current message will be
     appended to this file.

   The feedback system does currently support some of the ANSI control
codes (such as bold face and colouring text) but do not count on this
facility always being available, it makes life difficult for nice
scrolling readers.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This is not strictly true as one could log into the BBS in
ASCII mode and read the feedback messages there, where some additional
movement capabilities exist.  Also the sysop can reset your high
message pointer.


@EndNode

@Node "Monitor" "iceterm.guide/Monitor"
@Next "EMail"
@Prev "Feedback"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Monitor
=======

   The monitor tool is a facility for you to watch what is happening on
the other lines of the BBS.  When this tool is opened three windows: a
small control panel and two scrolling text lists, will be appear.

   The activity list window displays the current activity on the system.
It shows @{i}who did what when@{ui}.  When the tool is first started a sysop
defined number of prior events will be sent, after these old events have
been sent the tool will receive updates as people move about the system
on the other lines.

   The line statistics window shows the time the BBS was last started
and the total number of hours it has been running since then.  Following
that are a series of lines, one for each line on the BBS, that show
(from left to right):

   @{b}*@{ub} The name of the line, this is usually something descriptive about
     the line, such as the phone number or the type of modem that is on
     it,

   @{b}*@{ub} The percent utilization of the line.  This is the total time the
     line has been in use out of the total time the BBS has been
     running,

   @{b}*@{ub} The login and logout times of the last users of the line.  If the
     logout time is zero then that user is still on the line,

   @{b}*@{ub} The name of the current (or last) user of the line.

   The monitor control window with the three buttons is to allow you to
page the other users who have their monitor windows open and to control
the paging bell and screen flash on your system.

   To page the other users who are on the system you hit the @{b}Page@{ub}
button. Doing so will send a beep signal to all users who have their
monitor windows open.  This is usually done to attract someone's
attention(1) to get them to go into the conference.  The beep signal is
translated into either an audible beep or a screen flash at the other
user's end.

   Since some people find the screen flashing and beeping to be annoying
the flash and bell gadgets are provided to enable and disable these two
methods of beeping.  If the gadget is pushed in (selected) the beeper
will be allowed to use that mode and if the gadget is out then the
beeper cannot use that mode.  Your preferred setting for these two
functions can be saved in the IceTERM icon by using the monitor control
window's @{b}Snapshot@{ub} menu item (see @{"The snapshot menu" Link "The snapshot menu"}).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  It would be nice to be able to page individual users for
private conferences, it is on the to-do list.


@EndNode

@Node "EMail" "iceterm.guide/EMail"
@Next "News"
@Prev "Monitor"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Email
=====

   The email tool is used to send private electronic mail between users
and to send files between users.  Neither of these forms of
communication is completely private(1), although other users can not
see your mail, the sysop can if he wants.  When the tool is first
opened a small control window will open containing seven buttons.

   When the tool is opened for the first time all these gadgets may
appear ghosted. Once the gadgets unghost you can use email. On older
versions of IceTERM you may observe the modem lights flashing for quite
a while as IceBBS is sending you the list of all the users on the
BBS(2).  When this list has been received the gadgets will unghost and
all will be ready for your use.  With versions of IceTERM greater than
101 this delay does not occur.


 @{" The user list " Link "The user list"}           Who is on the BBS
 @{" Sending messages " Link "Sending messages"}        Local email on the BBS
 @{" Emailing a file " Link "Emailing a file"}         Sending files between users
 @{" FidoNet mail " Link "FidoNet mail"}            Sending mail to a user on FidoNet
 @{" FidoNet addressing " Link "FidoNet addressing"}      How zones, nets, nodes and points work
 @{" FidoNet newsgroups " Link "FidoNet newsgroups"}      Special support for monitoring newsgroups
 @{" Internet mail " Link "Internet mail"}           Sending mail to a user on the Internet
 @{" Internet addressing " Link "Internet addressing"}     How to use it, what to look for
 @{" Behind the scenes " Link "Behind the scenes"}       What happens when you send an Internet message?
 @{" Internet replies " Link "Internet replies"}        All that header stuff
 @{" Your address " Link "Your address"}            What your Internet email address will be
 @{" Advanced email " Link "Advanced email"}          Other things you can do with Internet email
 @{" User profiles " Link "User profiles"}           Letting the world know who you are
 @{" CC buttons " Link "CC buttons"}              Automatic monitoring of SIGs
 @{" Change password " Link "Change password"}         Changing your password
 @{" Enter coupon " Link "Enter coupon"}            Upgrading your access

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The only way around this at the moment is to send files that
have been encrypted by a password known only to you and the receiver,
see @{"Encryption" Link "Encryption"}.

   (2)  This downloading only has to happen once, the list is kept on
disk for the tool to use in later sessions.  Occasionally you may wish
to grab a new copy of the user list.


@EndNode

@Node "The user list" "iceterm.guide/The user list"
@Next "Sending messages"
@Prev "EMail"
@Toc "EMail"

The user list
-------------

   The user list is stored in the directory that you selected with the
IceTERM icon's @{b}EMAILROOT@{ub} tool type entry (see @{"Basic Tool types" Link "Basic Tool types"}).  If
you look in this directory you will find one subdirectory for each
IceBBS system you call, within these subdirectories are the user name
lists and the messages that you have received.

   From time to time you might want to update your copy of the user
list. This is done with the @{b}Find Users@{ub} button.  Clicking on this button
will open up a string requester where you can type the first part of
the name of the user you are looking for (even just the first character
will do--and it is not case sensitive). IceTERM will then request that
the BBS send the names of all the users which start with the sequence
of letters you entered.  This is usually a short list and will not take
too long to send.  IceTERM will save this list, adding it to any other
name searches that you do, in that way it gradually allows you to build
up as much of that BBS's user list as you need.

   If you have a faster modem (or don't mind the wait) you can get the
whole user list by just hitting return in the search string requester
without typing any text in.

   Also, this name downloading is an @{i}updating@{ui} process, if any users
that already appear in your list get removed from the BBS, then when
you update their section of the user list their names will be removed
from your local copy too.


@EndNode

@Node "Sending messages" "iceterm.guide/Sending messages"
@Next "Emailing a file"
@Prev "The user list"
@Toc "EMail"

Sending email messages
----------------------

   Note: the IceOLR program can also be used to compose and send email
messages to other users on the BBS, to users on other FidoNet BBSs and
to internet email addresses.  The advantage that the IceOLR email
function has is that you can create and read email while off line.

   To send a regular text message to another user on this BBS you click
on the @{b}Send Message@{ub} button in the email control panel.  As soon as this
is done a list of the users on the BBS will be presented (if you cannot
find the name you are looking for click on the @{b}Find Users@{ub} button), you
click on the name of the user you want to send the message to and then
your favourite text editor will be summoned for you to compose the
message in (see @{"Your Editor" Link "Your Editor"}).  Once you have finished entering the
message you save it and exit the editor, as you do that IceTERM will
start sending the message to the addressee's account on the BBS system.


@EndNode

@Node "Emailing a file" "iceterm.guide/Emailing a file"
@Next "FidoNet mail"
@Prev "Sending messages"
@Toc "EMail"

Sending a file
--------------

   The @{b}Send File@{ub} function (found in the email control panel, see @{"EMail" Link "EMail"})
works in much the same way as the @{b}Send Message@{ub} function.  You hit the
@{b}Send File@{ub} button, then select the name of the user you wish to send the
file to, and then you use the file requester to select the file that
you wish to send.  Once this is done the email system will ask for
final confirmation, and if it is safe to proceed, will load the file
into memory (so you don't have to keep that disk in the drive until the
transmission is done) and start sending the file.  Note that there is
no progress indicator on files sent by email, you know its done when
the modem lights are no longer flashing or when you can click on the
email close window button without a warning requester appearing. It is
highly recomended that you archive(1) the files you are sending so that
the recipient can test them to see that they did not get corrupted or
truncated.  Files that you send this way go to that user's private
email directory where they are held for him to download in the normal
way (see @{"Downloading email" Link "Downloading email"}).  The files are identified by name and a
note as to who sent them(2) and when.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  With a tool such as @{b}LHARC@{ub}, @{b}ARC@{ub}, @{b}ZOO@{ub}, @{b}LZ@{ub} or @{b}LHA@{ub}.

   (2)  The @{i}note@{ui} is in the form of a short description (see
@{"Short description" Link "Short description"}.


@EndNode

@Node "FidoNet mail" "iceterm.guide/FidoNet mail"
@Next "FidoNet addressing"
@Prev "Emailing a file"
@Toc "EMail"

FidoNet mail
------------

   The @{b}Send Fido@{ub} button is a version of the @{b}Send Message@{ub} button that
will prompt you for the additional information required to send a
message to a user on another BBS system through FidoNet.  Note that the
BBS you are connected to might not support FidoNet, or if it does it
might place some restrictions on what other BBS systems can be mailed
to.  It is best to consult with the sysop before using this function.
Check the @{b}News@{ub} function (see @{"News" Link "News"}) to see if there is a news file
describing restrictions on email or netmail.


@EndNode

@Node "FidoNet addressing" "iceterm.guide/FidoNet addressing"
@Next "FidoNet newsgroups"
@Prev "FidoNet mail"
@Toc "EMail"

FidoNet addressing
------------------

   The additional information needed to send a FidoNet message is the
name of the person and the FidoNet number of the BBS she is registered
on.  The FidoNet numbers (sometimes called @{i}node numbers@{ui}) are composed
of three or four numbers separated by various punctuation marks.  The
numbers take the format:

     zone:net/node.point

   where:
@{b}zone@{ub}
     is approximately the number of the continent the BBS is located on
     (zone 1 is North America and zone 2 is Europe),

@{b}net@{ub}
     is the network within the zone that the BBS belongs to.  Networks
     are usually located within the dialing area of a local phone call,
     but they may be smaller or larger for organizational purposes,

@{b}node@{ub}
     is the number of the BBS within the network to which it belongs.
     Within any given network the node numbers must be unique.  This is
     normally the finest level of addressing necessary.  Nodes within
     the same network generally do a lot of talking between each other,

@{b}point@{ub}
     is the last level of FidoNet addressing.  This is usually a single
     user system which only communicates to the rest of FidoNet through
     one machine (its boss).  Note that points are not listed in the
     FidoNet phone directory(1), and if a FidoNet address is given
     without a point number it is taken to be zero.  All nodes have a
     point number of zero.

   As there are no phone books of all the users on the various FidoNet
supporting systems in the world it can be difficult to start up a
conversation with a user via the email.  However, what does happen often
is that people meet in one of the public echomail conferences and
pursue other discussions that are not within the regular scope of the
conference area via private email exchanges.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The FidoNet nodelist is published weekly and lists over 20000
systems.


@EndNode

@Node "FidoNet newsgroups" "iceterm.guide/FidoNet newsgroups"
@Next "Internet mail"
@Prev "FidoNet addressing"
@Toc "EMail"

FidoNet newsgroups and email
----------------------------

   The BBS also provides a SIG monitoring facility for FidoNet
conferences.  Since some of the FidoNet echomail conferences carry such
a large volume of messages per day some people prefer not to read them
at all.  Yet what are they supposed to do when they have a particular
question that might readily be answered by posting it to a conference?
They would have to read the conference for perhaps a week in the hope
that a reply comes their way.  The FidoNet processor on IceBBS will
monitor the incoming messages in all the FidoNet SIGs and if it finds
one addressed to a user on the BBS it will send a copy of that message
to the user by email(1).  Then the next time the user accesses the
email function he will see the message @{i}without having to have been
reading that conference in the mean time@{ui}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Some people do not like this feature, it will become optional
later.


@EndNode

@Node "Internet mail" "iceterm.guide/Internet mail"
@Next "Internet addressing"
@Prev "FidoNet newsgroups"
@Toc "EMail"

Sending mail to an Internet user
--------------------------------

   The @{b}Send Internet@{ub} button provides a way to enter email messages that
are in a form suitable for transmission to another machine connected to
the @{i}Internet@{ui}.  The Internet is a big network of computers that spans
the globe.  This network is roughly composed of two sets of machines,
those that are @{i}on the net@{ui} (1) and those that are @{i}nearby@{ui} (2).  There are
estimates that as many as 40 million people may now have access to the
Internet.  The big pay services like BIX, GEnie and CompuServe offer
access to the Internet for email purposes.

   Note that this feature may not be supported on all IceBBS systems,
they need to have a UUCP feed to connect their machines to the net.  If
it is not available an error message will appear when you try to send a
message, consult the news tool for local information.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  To be on the net your machine needs to actually be connected to
the net 24 hours a day through a dedicated high speed line.

   (2)  Amiga users can use the UUCP package from Matt Dillon and a
cast of thousands to connect to other machines that connect to other
machines that connect to the Internet, in this case the machine is said
to be nearby, perhaps a couple of @{i}hops@{ui} off the net.


@EndNode

@Node "Internet addressing" "iceterm.guide/Internet addressing"
@Next "Behind the scenes"
@Prev "Internet mail"
@Toc "EMail"

Internet addressing
-------------------

   Assuming that the BBS is connected to the net then to send and
receive mail all you have to do is to find the name and address of the
person you want to send mail to.  Look for an address like:

     svermeulen@ragnarok.mtroyal.ab.ca

   (which is my address), usually in the signature area of their
messages (some magazines like Wired and Mondo also publish the Internet
address of their authors...).  When you hit the @{b}Send Internet@{ub} button
IceTERM will prompt you to enter the person's address.  You need to
type it in @{i}exactly@{ui}. Normally these things are case insensitive but its
best to preserve the case.  After entering the address IceTERM will ask
for the subject of your message and then will open your editor (see
@{"Your Editor" Link "Your Editor"}) to allow you to compose your message.  When you save the
message and exit from the editor IceTERM will ask if you really want to
send the message, say no to abort the process, otherwise the message
will start its twisty journey through the Internet.


@EndNode

@Node "Behind the scenes" "iceterm.guide/Behind the scenes"
@Next "Internet replies"
@Prev "Internet addressing"
@Toc "EMail"

How Internet mail works
-----------------------

   What happens is this:  IceTERM will insert the necessary From:, To:,
and Subject: lines in to your message along with a blank line, that in
the Internet world, separates the header from the message.  It then
sends the message over to IceBBS which, upon receiving it, invokes the
SENDMAIL program (which is part of the UUCP package that the BBS
machine is running).  If the BBS does not have UUCP available then it
will send back an error message to you explaining this unfortunate
fact.  Every so often a script file on the BBS machine will do a bit of
Internet processing, in particular the programs UUxqt and UUcico will
get run and the message will take another step in its journey. In all
probability the message will leave the BBS machine at this point and
disappear into an evil smelling puff of smoke.  Although there is a
chance that someone (or something) lurking on the Internet will see it
and send a reply to you.


@EndNode

@Node "Internet replies" "iceterm.guide/Internet replies"
@Next "Your address"
@Prev "Behind the scenes"
@Toc "EMail"

Replies from the Internet
-------------------------

   When a reply does come back from the Internet it will appear like any
other email, the full message (including header) will be displayed for
you to edit as you choose, if you want to reply to the message. Note
that you don't need to worry about the contents of the header in most
cases as IceBBS and IceTERM have already extracted all the information
they need to address the reply correctly, so you can even delete all
the header information. The upper limit on the size of these messages
is about 50K bytes so if you need to send larger messages (typically
uuencoded(1) files) you have to split them into chunks, and send each
chunk as a separate message.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  UUencode and UUdecode are programs that take a binary file and
convert it to a plain ASCII text form (suitable for sending in an email
message) and back again.  The PGP package (see @{"Encryption" Link "Encryption"}) also has
this capability which it calls @{i}armoured ASCII@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "Your address" "iceterm.guide/Your address"
@Next "Advanced email"
@Prev "Internet replies"
@Toc "EMail"

Your address on the Internet
----------------------------

   You may want to know what your Internet style email address is so
someone can send you email (typically you add this address to your
signature text that you include on messages you post in the SIGs).  It
will be of the form:

     <UserID>@bbsname.xx.yy.zz

   where the @{b} @bbsname.xx.yy.zz@{ub} is the address of the BBS and the
@{b}<UserID>@{ub} gets replaced with your account number.  Your account number
is a unique multi-digit number which IceBBS assigns to you when your
account is created.  To discover what your account number is you can
use the @{b}Show@{ub} button (see @{"User profiles" Link "User profiles"}).  For example if your account
number is @{b}N123456@{ub} on my BBS machine then your email address would be:

     N123456@ragnarok.myroyal.ab.ca

   The reason for this is that there are certain restrictions on the
characters that a name can contain in an Internet address, whereas
IceBBS does not place similar restrictions on it's user's names.  If
your name only contains letters or digits then you can use that name
directly, for example:

     TermUser12@ragnarok.myroyal.ab.ca

would be the address for someone called @{b}TermUser12@{ub} on my BBS.

   If your name contains spaces then you can try one of the following:

@{b}"Your name"@site@{ub}
     Placing your name in quotation marks will usually work, but the
     software running at some sites along the way might have problems
     with it,

@{b}Your_name@site@{ub}
     Replacing the spaces in your name with underscores will fix the
     problem, the BBS mail importer knows to try replacing any
     underscores with spaces when looking for an account to deliver the
     mail to,

@{b}Your.name@site@{ub}
     Replacing the spaces in your name with periods will fix the
     problem, the BBS mail importer knows to try replacing any periods
     with spaces when looking for an account to deliver the mail to.

   If your name contains any punctuation or other special characters
(especially parentheses) you will have to enclose it in quotation
marks, otherwise the various mail processors along its path will try to
process it further.

   Note: many internet mail processors do not respect the quotation
marks, when this happens it can cause your mail to bounce in strange
ways or perhaps to go to unexpected places.  If you are wanting to use
internet mail I would strongly suggest you create an account with a
name that has no spaces or other punctuation characters in it.


@EndNode

@Node "Advanced email" "iceterm.guide/Advanced email"
@Next "User profiles"
@Prev "Your address"
@Toc "EMail"

Advanced email techniques
-------------------------

   This section contains some additional information on things that you
can do with Internet style email.  The Internet email messages follow
the RFC-822 specification, some of the features that are implemented
are:

   @{b}*@{ub} header line folding,

   @{b}*@{ub} supports the reply-to header, if a reply-to line is present then
     that's where the replies go, if one is not present then replies go
     to the from header line,

   @{b}*@{ub} email to a user list is possible, comma separate the addresses,

   @{b}*@{ub} the header keywords to be any mixture of upper and lower case,

   The email processor on the BBS that converts inbound internet
messages into IceBBS format email supports human readable names, this
means that someone out there can send a message to you by quoting your
username, for example:

     To: "stephen vermeulen"@amuc.mtroyal.ab.ca

   will now stand a good chance of reaching my account on the AMUC
Express BBS.  I say @{i}a good chance@{ui} because I suspect that some mail
processors may not like user names longer than 8 characters and may not
like imbedded spaces, so the email processor will also map the
following names to the @{b}stephen vermeulen@{ub} account

     stephen_vermeulen@amuc.mtroyal.ab.ca
     stephen.vermeulen@amuc.mtroyal.ab.ca

   the cryptic account number based system is still supported and will
be added as the @{b}From:@{ub} line to any email you create. The sysop can add
additional account name aliasing via UUCP's @{b}UULIB:aliases@{ub} file if it is
needed.  For example if the current AMUC Chairman is Ian Sinclair then
the following aliases:

     amuc: ian_sinclair
     UsersGroup: ian_sinclair
     chairman: ian_sinclair
     president: ian_sinclair

   would redirect any mail addressed to @{b}amuc@{ub}, @{b}usersgroup@{ub}, @{b}chairman@{ub} or
@{b}president@{ub} to the account named @{b}ian_sinclair@{ub} and if there is no
@{b}ian_sinclair@{ub} account then the @{b}ian_sinclair@{ub} account would receive the
mail.

   And now for the new feature: Internet expert mode.  This is
intentionally hidden away since in order to use it you need to
understand how to write Internet compatible mail headers.  To enter
expert mode either when sending a new internet message or replying to
one you have received all you need do is put a @{b}~@{ub} as the first and only
character in the subject string.  When you do this IceTERM will not add
any @{b}To:@{ub} or @{b}Subject:@{ub} lines to your message, the only thing it will add
is the @{b}From:@{ub} line so you @{i}must@{ui} supply the message in correct Internet
format.  This means that you supply the entire Internet header(1), a
blank line and then the text of your message.  The only part of the
header that is mandatory is the @{b}To:@{ub} line, you can add @{b}CC:@{ub}, @{b}BCC:@{ub},
@{b}REPLY-TO:@{ub} and other optional headers as suits your purpose.  All
headers can span multiple lines using header folding (break the line at
an appropriate point and then indent the continuation lines by at least
one space). For more information refer to RFC-822 (and don't blame me
if your head explodes).

   One of the interesting use of all this is to do bulk junk mailings,
for example to send mail to 5 people on AMUC Express and one person on
another Internet site, from your account on AMUC Express you send a
message like:

     To:  "stephen vermeulen"@amuc,
         "jeff rose"@amuc, wuth@castrov.cuc.ab.ca,
            "bryan ewert"@amuc,
           "ian sinclair"@amuc, AMUCChairman@amuc
     Subject: Some wild ramblings...
     
     Here is a test message, it goes out to six people.
     
     Regards, the tester.

   notice the @{b}To:@{ub} line has been folded onto four lines in the message
(keeping each line to under about 80 characters) and the continuation
lines each start with at least one character of white space (the ragged
alignment is intentional to demonstrate that alignment is not needed).
The five users who are also on @{b}amuc@{ub} can have the addresses abbreviated
to just @{b} @amuc@{ub}, the one user who is on a separate internet site needs a
full address specification. The following is the same message, but with
one one person as the addressee, two others get the message as a carbon
copy (@{b}CC:@{ub}) and the other three get it as a blind carbon copy (@{b}BCC:@{ub}):

     To:  "stephen vermeulen"@amuc,
     CC:  "jeff rose"@amuc, wuth@castrov.cuc.ab.ca
     BCC:  "bryan ewert"@amuc,
           "ian sinclair"@amuc, AMUCChairman@amuc
     Subject: Some wild ramblings...
     
     Here is a test message, it goes out to six people.
     
     Regards, the tester.

   The blind carbon copy (@{b}BCC:@{ub}) gets its name from the fact that the
primary and secondary recepients (@{b}To:@{ub} and @{b}CC:@{ub} addresses) do not get the
@{b}BCC:@{ub} lines included in their copies of the mail. So in the above
example @{b}stephen vermeulen@{ub}, @{b}jeff rose@{ub} and @{b}wuth@{ub} have no idea that the
message was also sent to @{b}bryan ewert@{ub}, @{b}ian sinclair@{ub}, and @{b}AMUCChairman@{ub}.

   In the next version of the message we add a @{b}reply-to:@{ub} line so that
if any of the recepients replies to the message both @{b}the tester@{ub} and
@{b}AMUCNewsLetterEditor@{ub} get copies of the reply:

     To:  "stephen vermeulen"@amuc,
     CC:  "jeff rose"@amuc, wuth@castrov.cuc.ab.ca
     BCC:  "bryan ewert"@amuc,
           "ian sinclair"@amuc, AMUCChairman@amuc
     Reply-To: "the tester"@amuc, AMUCNewsLetterEditor@amuc
     Subject: Some wild ramblings...
     
     Here is a test message, it goes out to six people.
     
     Regards, the tester.

   Note that by (mis)using the reply-to line you can send a message to
several people (maybe even Ken Pierce) and get the replies to go to
several other people (and if you wish, @{i}not@{ui} include yourself among the
reply recepients).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Note: if you are using expert mode to send internet messages
you must capitalize the first letter of the header lines.  That is you
should use: @{b}To:@{ub}, @{b}Subject:@{ub} etc. not @{b}to:@{ub} and @{b}subject:@{ub}.  This is to avoid
a problem in UUCP's sendmail command.


@EndNode

@Node "User profiles" "iceterm.guide/User profiles"
@Next "CC buttons"
@Prev "Advanced email"
@Toc "EMail"

Using the user profiles
-----------------------

   The @{b}Edit@{ub} button is used to enable you to edit your own profile.  So
what is a profile? The profile is intended to be a little informative
blurb about yourself so that other users can figure out if they want to
send you email. Perhaps there are several people with similar names, or
perhaps the user is just looking for someone who considers himself an
expert in a certain arcane area.  One of the more interesting uses of
the profile is to provide a place for you to post your "public
encryption key" (see @{"Encryption" Link "Encryption"}) so that other people can send you
encrypted email.

   Two buttons on the email control panel (see @{"EMail" Link "EMail"}) @{b}Show@{ub} and @{b}Edit@{ub} are
used to browse and maintain user profiles. The @{b}Show@{ub} button will bring
up the list of users, from which you can pick users whose profile
descriptions you want to read.  When you click on the name of a user in
this list two things will happen. First the title bar of the list
window will change to show the account number of this person (see
@{"Your address" Link "Your address"}); and second, if the user has edited his profile the
contents of his profile will be displayed for you to read.

   The @{b}Edit@{ub} button is used to enable you to edit your own profile using
your editor (see @{"Your Editor" Link "Your Editor"}).


@EndNode

@Node "CC buttons" "iceterm.guide/CC buttons"
@Next "Change password"
@Prev "User profiles"
@Toc "EMail"

The carbon copy buttons
-----------------------

   The two buttons labeled: @{b}CC: Fido@{ub} and @{b}CC: Usenet@{ub} are used to control
the BBS's news feature which automatically places a copy of all FidoNet
and USENET news articals addressed to you into your email box.  The CC:
buttons will allow you to enable (button pushed in) or disable (button
sticking out) this IceBBS feature.  The settings of the buttons are
stored on the BBS in your account file as soon as you change them.


@EndNode

@Node "Change password" "iceterm.guide/Change password"
@Next "Enter coupon"
@Prev "CC buttons"
@Toc "EMail"

The change password button
--------------------------

   To change your password just hit this button, a string requester will
popup and ask you to re-enter your old password.  Then you will be
asked to enter your new password.  If you use the @{b}PASSWORD@{ub} tool type or
you use dialing scripts with your password in them make sure to update
these.


@EndNode

@Node "Enter coupon" "iceterm.guide/Enter coupon"
@Prev "Change password"
@Toc "EMail"

The enter coupon button
-----------------------

   This button allows you to enter the serial number of an IceBBS
upgrade coupon that you have been given. This will then cause an
automatic upgrade of your account, and when the coupon expires your
account will automatically downgraded too.


@EndNode

@Node "News" "iceterm.guide/News"
@Next "Shell"
@Prev "EMail"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

News
====

   The @{b}News@{ub} button is used to access a number of news or help bulletins
that the sysop has created.  Typically this facility is used to place
answers to frequently asked questions on-line.

   Clicking on the @{b}News@{ub} button will bring up a list of the available
news files.  To view the contents of any news files in the list just
click on their names, the BBS will send the requested information and
will display it in a scrollable message box.

   These message boxes can be left on the display while you do other
things so they can form a convenient on-line reference system.


@EndNode

@Node "Shell" "iceterm.guide/Shell"
@Next "Serial port features"
@Prev "News"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Shell
=====

   The @{b}Shell@{ub} button will open a window that is connected to an AmigaDOS
shell on the BBS machine.  Within this window one can issue normal
AmigaDOS commands and see their output displayed.  Since the ability to
issue AmigaDOS commands is potentially very dangerous(1) regular users
will normally not be allowed to use this function, in which case
clicking on the @{b}Shell@{ub} button will just result in a warning message
explaining that you have insufficient privileges to use the shell.  If
you are a co-sysop with sufficient privilege to use the shell you will
find that you can open as many as you need.

   To exit from a shell window you type the command @{b}endcli@{ub} into it.
Note that you should not issue any commands that open window displays
since there is usually no way you can stop them.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  A simple command such as @{b}format dh0:@{ub} could be disastrous.


@EndNode

@Node "Serial port features" "iceterm.guide/Serial port features"
@Next "Doors"
@Prev "Shell"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Special serial port features
============================

   IceTERM can open the serial port in shared mode for those who really
want to.  To get this to happen either include the tool type @{b}SHARED@{ub} or
else include the @{b}-s@{ub} CLI switch.

   IceTERM also supports the @{b}OwnDevUnit.library@{ub}, this is for UUCP users
who run @{b}Getty@{ub} all the time.  If you don't have the OwnDevUnit library
then nothing new will happen.  If you do have it then IceTERM will
request access to the serial port via ODU and if it fails you will get
a requester telling you that ODU has the port locked.


@EndNode

@Node "Doors" "iceterm.guide/Doors"
@Prev "Serial port features"
@Toc "Using the terminal"

Doors
=====

   IceBBS supports a unique and powerful system of expansion called the
@{i}doors system@{ui} (or just doors for short).  This system has been designed
so additional clients and servers may be added to both the BBS and
IceTERM ends of the communications link by just dragging icons and
editing a few tool types.

   The idea behind a IceBBS door is that there are two programs
communicating transparently through the BBS and IceTERM packages.  The
connection that the BBS and IceTERM provide for the door is error free
and transparently multiplexed in with other BBS and IceTERM functions.
The user can start up and treat doors in the same way he treats any
other BBS function.

   The two programs involved in a door are called the client and server.
(So now you can say you've used a @{i}client-server@{ui} architecture).  The
client always runs on the IceTERM end of the connection and the server
always runs on the BBS end.


 @{" Installing doors " Link "Installing doors"}        Really, its just drag it and drop it
 @{" Accessing a door " Link "Accessing a door"}        Starting a door
 @{" Preview door " Link "Preview door"}            Previewing pictures on the BBS
 @{" Remote file door " Link "Remote file door"}        Working on the BBS file system
 @{" Chess door " Link "Chess door"}              Have a game of GPChess
 @{" Voting door " Link "Voting door"}             Express your opinion
 @{" IceFTP " Link "IceFTP"}                  Internet FTP in a door
 @{" IceIRC " Link "IceIRC"}                  Internet Relay Chat in a door
 @{" Door tool types " Link "Door tool types"}         Some more tool type information
 @{" Programming doors " Link "Programming doors"}       So you want to write a door program?


@EndNode

@Node "Installing doors" "iceterm.guide/Installing doors"
@Next "Accessing a door"
@Prev "Doors"
@Toc "Doors"

Installation
------------

   Installation of a door is quite simple, just drag the icon for the
door client and drop it in the drawer where these are stored on your
system. The directory where the door clients are stored is established
with the @{b}DOORDIR@{ub} tool type.


@EndNode

@Node "Accessing a door" "iceterm.guide/Accessing a door"
@Next "Preview door"
@Prev "Installing doors"
@Toc "Doors"

Accessing a door
----------------

   To use a door from IceTERM just click on the @{b}Doors@{ub} button and a door
chooser will appear with a list of the doors to choose from.  Click on
the names of any doors you wish to use.  Like any other IceTERM
function(1) you can start up several copies of a door if you wish(2).
Once the door has been started you can close the door chooser list, or
leave it open to start other doors from.  If you use the doors
frequently you can even use the @{b}AUTOSTART@{ub} tool type (see @{"Autostart" Link "Autostart"}) to
automatically open the door chooser when you log into the BBS.

   Note that sysops have the ability to control user access to the doors
on a door by door basis, so even if you have the neccessary client in
your door directory you may find that you cannot use the door on
certain BBS systems.

   As a user of IceTERM you only need the client part of each door you
want to be able to use.  You @{i}do not need@{ui} the server part, although the
server part is usually distributed along with the client so that the
sysop can install it on the BBS system.

   Related topics: @{"Doors do not appear" Link "Doors do not appear"} and @{"Doors do not work" Link "Doors do not work"}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Except SIGs and email.

   (2)  Some doors may not allow this.


@EndNode

@Node "Preview door" "iceterm.guide/Preview door"
@Next "Remote file door"
@Prev "Accessing a door"
@Toc "Doors"

The preview door
----------------

   This is a door that has been written to allow you to preview
miniaturized versions of IFF, GIF or JPEG pictures to help you decide
what to download.  When this door is started it brings up three windows
which are quite similar to the ones used by the get files tool (see
@{"Get files" Link "Get files"}).

   With these windows you navigate the directory tree in the same way
as with the get files tool.  However, instead of starting a download
when a filename is selected the previewer will attempt to display the
file as a picture.  If it not an IFF ILBM format file it will display a
short message telling you it cannot display the file.  If the file is
an IFF picture it will download it directly onto a small screen on your
Amiga's display.

   In order to reduce the transmission time for the previewed pictures
most sysops will prepare special miniaturized pictures. These will not
have the quality of the original but they should give you an idea of
the content before you spend time downloading.  The file names of
miniaturized pictures are usually given a @{b}.mini@{ub} suffix.  The size and
number of colours in a mini-picture is entirely up to the sysop, I
generally recomend reducing the picture size until it is 10K bytes or
less and using the 64 colour EHB mode.

   If you want to help out your local sysop try uploading miniaturized
versions of any pictures you upload.  You can make the miniatures with
a tool such as Wasp, ADPro, or HamLabPlus.


@EndNode

@Node "Remote file door" "iceterm.guide/Remote file door"
@Next "Chess door"
@Prev "Preview door"
@Toc "Doors"

The RemFile door
----------------

   The @{b}RemFile@{ub} door is a tool intended for use by co-sysops to aid the
main sysop with the chores of file system maintenance.  It gives the
co-sysops the ability to copy, delete, and test files.  As well they
can add descriptions and revise existing descriptions.

   The @{b}Parent@{ub}, @{b}Date@{ub} and @{b}Full@{ub} buttons function the same as those in the
get files tool (see @{"Get files" Link "Get files"}).  The @{b}Home@{ub} button is used in conjunction
with the @{b}Set Home@{ub} button.  By pressing the @{b}Set Home@{ub} button you tell the
door to memorize the current directory and when the @{b}Home@{ub} button is
pressed it returns you to this directory.  This is most useful for
returning to a frequently visited directory like the upload directory.

   The @{b}Show@{ub} and @{b}Edit@{ub} buttons are used to view the long description of a
file and to edit that long description.  When the long description is
to be edited your favourite editor is used (in the same way that the
IceTERM program does it) so the @{b}EDITOR@{ub} tool type is needed in the
doors's icon (see @{"Your Editor" Link "Your Editor"}).

   The RemFile door can also be used to copy, rename and delete files.
These all work in a similar fashion, you first click on the name of the
file that you want to work on and then click on the button named after
the task you wish to perform.  The @{b}Rename@{ub} button will prompt you for
the new name and then will get the BBS to perform an AmigaDOS rename of
the file.  Note that you can only supply the new name of the file, you
cannot include a new directory path in the name.  The @{b}Delete@{ub} button is
used to delete the selected file from disk, a confirmation requester
will appear after you click on it.

   The copy function is a bit more complicated, you select the name of
the file to be copied in the same way as you did for the rename and
delete functions.  However, the file copying process also needs to know
what directory you wish the file to be copied to.  To set this
directory name you need to move to that directory and then click on the
@{b}Set Dest Dir@{ub} button.  This directory name will then be placed into the
status display area on the @{b}Copy to:@{ub} line.  Now to perform the copy you
return to the directory where the file you want to copy is, select the
file and then hit the @{b}Copy to@{ub} button.  It is because of this constant
returning to the source directory when validating new uploads that the
@{b}Home@{ub} button was added.

   The copy function has another feature, it can copy the same file to
two separate directories at the same time.  This is accomplished by
using the @{b}Set Dest Dir@{ub} to set the name of the first directory and the
@{b}Set Dest Two@{ub} button to set the name of the second directory.  Then to
copy to both directories at once you hit the @{b}Both@{ub} button.  This feature
was added so that sysops could easily put a copy of each new upload
into a directory containing new files, while at the same time placing
copies of those files into the general file directories where they
belong.  Then the BBS can run a script file which ages out the new file
directory as the files in there become a week or two old.

   The major part of a co-sysop's file maintainance duties revolve
around testing the files that are uploaded.  To aid in this two methods
are used.  The simplest is the @{b}CRC@{ub} button.  This performs a very quick
check to ensure the whole file matches a CRC that was computed on the
uploader's machine.  This is good enough to test for problems in
transmission of the file (for example an incomplete file that was
caused by the user logging out for some reason before the file send was
fininshed) and only takes a second or two to run.  Unfortunately this
cannot test the inner workings of a file for correctness, for example
one often finds users uploading incomplete or damaged archives.

   To perform this sort of testing one needs to use the @{i}archiver@{ui}
buttons.  There are four of these in the bottom row of buttons.  The
first is a multi-state button that is used to select the archiver that
is to be used to test the file.  The list of archivers that are
available for use is determined by the sysop when he configures the
remote file door's server.

   The three buttons: @{b}Test@{ub}, @{b}List@{ub} and @{b}Unarc@{ub} are used to tell the
archiver what operation you wish to perform on the selected file.  Not
all archivers allow all operations to be performed.  The @{b}Test@{ub} button
runs the archiver's file test mode and displays the results of it in a
window for you perusal.  The @{b}List@{ub} button lists the contents of the
archive.  The @{b}Unarc@{ub} button tells the archiver to unpack the archive
into a directory that the sysop has set aside for this purpose, once
the archive is unpacked the results of the extraction will be displayed
and you can then inspect individual files in the archive (perhaps even
downloading them) with the get files tool.


@EndNode

@Node "Chess door" "iceterm.guide/Chess door"
@Next "Voting door"
@Prev "Remote file door"
@Toc "Doors"

GPChess door
------------

   This is a @{i}play by mail@{ui} chess game simulator.  It was written by Greg
Pringle and the server is distributed as part of the full version of
the IceBBS software.  The chess game features a graphical chess board
where you enter your moves complete with a history display feature, so
you can review the past moves that led up to your grief.  It also has
some score logging.

   If two users are both online at the same time they can make GPChess
into a real-time game by both opening the conference and telling each
other when they have completed their move.


@EndNode

@Node "Voting door" "iceterm.guide/Voting door"
@Next "IceFTP"
@Prev "Chess door"
@Toc "Doors"

Voting door
-----------

   The voting door is the first of the new ARexx based doors for IceBBS.
So in order to use it you must have ARexx installed and active on your
system.  If you are running AmigaDOS 2.0 or higher ARexx will be
installed, but it may not be active yet.  To activate it you can issue
an ARexx command in a CLI such as:

     rx "say 2+2"

   this will cause the ARexx process to be loaded from disk and come to
life.

   The voting door allows the sysop to make up several questionaires or
polls for the users of his BBS to answer. These polls take the form of
multiple choice questions, your responses get logged into a file on the
BBS.  The sysop has a program for tallying the votes that he will run
occasionally.


@EndNode

@Node "IceFTP" "iceterm.guide/IceFTP"
@Next "IceIRC"
@Prev "Voting door"
@Toc "Doors"

IceFTP door
-----------

   What is FTP? FTP is File Transfer Protocol, a system for transferring
files between computers on the Internet.  It is very popular because
there are a lot of big "anonymous FTP sites" on the Internet.  An
anonymous FTP site is like a big BBS that allows you to log onto it and
download files without having to register for an account.  The IceFTP
door allows the user of IceTERM to explore this side of the internet
from his Amiga without having to set up software such as AmiTCP and PPP
or SLIP.

   IceFTP will only be available on IceBBS systems that are connected
to the Internet.  Your sysop will probably have some information about
this in the login message or the news area.

Installation
............

   To install the client door on your system you just drag the FTPClient
icon into your @{b}Doors@{ub} directory (the place the @{b}DOORDIR=@{ub} tool type points
to) and that's it.  You will also need to have installed MUI(1).

   There is a default list of FTP sites called @{b}FTP.Sites@{ub} that may come
with the IceFTP archive to make setup a bit easier, just drag it into
the door directory too.  It contains a short list of FTP sites.

Starting IceFTP
...............

   To start the FTP door just click on the @{b}Internet FTP@{ub} item in the
list of Doors. A window much like the following picture will appear:

Choosing an FTP site
....................

   The first thing you need to do is to select the FTP site you want to
connect to.  This is done by click on one of the ftp site names in the
list at the top of the window.  This list is initially loaded from the
FTP sites file which you specify with the @{b}SITELIST=@{ub} tool type in the
FTPclient's icon.  By default this is set up as:

     SITELIST=FTP.sites

   So to start with you just double click on the name of the site you
want to visit.

   If you want to add the name of other sites you can do so by entering
the site name, user name (usually @{b}anonymous@{ub} or @{b}ftp@{ub}) and password into
the string gadgets below.  Once these are entered you hit @{b}Add@{ub} to add
the site to the list.  If you want to save the list for future use you
can hit the @{b}Save@{ub} button.

   If the site accepts the user name @{b}anonymous@{ub} the password is not
needed and can be left blank.  If you have a private account you want
to access then you can enter the appropriate username and password.

   Note that the user name and password are stored in the @{b}SITELIST@{ub} file
so be careful!

   Now lets connect to a site double click on the name and the following
might happen:

   @{b}*@{ub} the status line goes to @{b}Connecting...@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub} then after a few seconds you get a @{b}Connection refused@{ub}

if this happens the site is probably busy and you should try some other
time of day (many sites have restrictions during their office hours).

   If you get a @{i}Could not find site@{ui} type message that appears very
quickly, it could mean that the BBS's link to the Internet is currently
down.

   Or you could get a successful connection, at which point the window's
contents will change.

Browsing an FTP site
....................

   Now you are in the directory browsing mode.  There is an information
region at the top of the window that shows the name of the site you are
connected to and the current directory on that site.

   Below this is the listing of the files and directories in the current
directory.  You can double click on these, if you select a directory
name the FTP client will try to take you into that directory (it is not
uncommon for this to fail because you don't have permission to go
there, or that the directory is on a disk that is currently not on
line).

   If you double click on the name of a file it is placed in the list
of files to be downloaded.

   The parent directory button takes you back up a level.

   The change site button allows you to leave the site, to go to
another one.

   The clear downloads button will remove all the files you have
selected from the list (as will changing the directory).  You can also
remove individual files by double clicking on them where they appear in
the download list.

Downloading from an FTP site
............................

   When you are ready to download something you just hit the @{b}Download@{ub}
button.  This will cause the contents of the screen to change again to
a download progress monitor.

   This window has a list which shows the names and sizes of the files
that are yet to be downloaded and a progress bar at the bottom that
shows the progress through the current file.

   Note that like other IceTERM functions you can use other IceTERM
tools at the same time as the FTP client, in fact you can even use more
than one FTP client at the same time (if you are browsing one site while
downloading from another).

Tool types for IceFTP
.....................

   The FTPclient takes two optional tool types in its icon:

@{b}SITELIST=filename@{ub}
     specifies the file that you want the site list to be loaded from
     and saved to,

@{b}DOWNDIR=dirname@{ub}
     specifies the directory you want downloads to go to, defaults to
     @{b}RAM:@{ub}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  MUI (Magic User Interface) is a package written by Stefan
Stuntz.  MUI is a system to generate and maintain graphical user
interfaces. With the  aid  of  a  preferences program, the user of an
application has the ability to customize the outfit according to his
personal taste.  MUI is distributed as shareware. To obtain a complete
package containing lots of examples and more information about
registration please look for a  file  called  @{b}muiXXusr.lha@{ub}  (XX means
the latest version number) on your local bulletin boards or on public
domain disks.


@EndNode

@Node "IceIRC" "iceterm.guide/IceIRC"
@Next "Door tool types"
@Prev "IceFTP"
@Toc "Doors"

IceIRC door
-----------

   What is IRC? IRC-Internet Relay Chat-is a real-time, text-based,
conferencing system for the Internet.  It allows a large number of
people to chat at once about a large number of topics.  It is real-time
because within a few seconds (usually) of you typing a new message into
a channel it is visable to all the other people who are viewing that
channel.

   Typically there might be five to ten thousand people connected into
the IRC at any one time.  There might be several thousand different
topics being discussed, some might only have one or two people, some
might have fifty.

   IRC has been extended to provide lots of other services (like file
transfer) over time.  The current version of IceIRC only does the
basics, but it's enough to start.

Installation
............

   To install the client door on your system you just drag the IRCClient
icon into your @{b}Doors@{ub} directory (the place the @{b}DOORDIR=@{ub} tool type points
to) and that's it.  You will also need to have installed MUI.

   There is a default list of IRC server sites called @{b}IRC.Sites@{ub} that
may come with the archive to make setup a bit easier, just drag it into
the door directory too.  There is another file called @{b}IRC.Topics@{ub}, drag
it into the door directory too.  This is only a partial list of the
topics on IRC but its a convenient start.

Starting IceIRC
...............

   To start the IRC door just click on the @{b}Internet IRC@{ub} item in the
list of Doors. A window similar to the one in the following picture
will appear:

   The first thing you need to do is to select the IRC site you want to
connect to.  This is done by clicking on one of the IRC site names in
the list at the top of the window.  This list is initially loaded from
the IRC sites file which you specify with the @{b}SITELIST=@{ub} tool type in
the IRCclient's icon.  By default this is set up as:

     SITELIST=IRC.sites

   So to start with you just double click on the name of the site you
want to visit.

   If you want to add the name of other sites you can do so by entering
the site name, nick name, password and port number into the string
gadgets below.  Once these are entered you hit @{b}Add@{ub} to add the site to
the list.  If you want to save the list for future use you can hit the
@{b}Save@{ub} button.

   Most servers do not require you to enter a password (that's really
for system operator type stuff), and you can make the nickname anything
you want (9 characters maximum).  The port number is also optional,
this is a number like @{b}6667@{ub} which is needed on some sites that run more
than one server, or run the server connected to a non-standard port
number.

   Now lets connect to a site, double click on the name and the
following might happen:

   @{b}*@{ub} the status line goes to @{b}Connecting...@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub} then after a few seconds you get a @{b}Connection refused@{ub}

if this happens the site is probably busy and you should try some other
time of day (many sites have restrictions during their office hours).

   If you get a @{i}Could not connect@{ui} type message that appears very
quickly, it could mean that the BBS's link to the Internet is currently
down.

   Or you could get a successful connection, at which point the window's
contents will change.

Joining a Channel
.................

   Now you are in the system control mode.  This window will soon
display the login message for the site you are trying to reach.  This
window has a scrolling list at the top where messages from the IRC
server are displayed and below that are three string gadgets and three
buttons.

   The string gadgets have the following functions:

@{b}Join Channel@{ub}
     enter the name of the IRC channel you want to join and hit return,
     this will then attempt to get you into that channel.  To join the
     @{b}#amiga@{ub} channel just enter @{b}#amiga@{ub} and hit return,

@{b}Nickname@{ub}
     To change your nickname, just edit it here and hit return,

@{b}Expert Command@{ub}
     This allows one to enter any IRC command directly, however, you
     have to know what the commands are and you have to get the
     formatting correct.  So don't use this.  Its really here for
     testing and future development,

The buttons are:

@{b}Clear@{ub}
     Clears the scrolling list,

@{b}Pick channels@{ub}
     Pick the channels you want to chat in.  This is the preferred way
     of joining a channel,

@{b}List channels@{ub}
     This asks the IRC server for a list of all the IRC channels that
     are currently available, since this list is quite long it might
     take a few minutes to complete.  You can use this list to select
     channels to add to your @{i}pick channels@{ui} list.  Normally you won't
     have to use this button,

   The following picture shows the @{i}pick channels@{ui} list:

Talking in a channel
....................

   If you've joined a channel by double clicking on in the @{i}Pick a
Channel@{ui} window, or by typing the channel name into the @{b}Join Channel@{ub}
string gadget another window will appear.  This window has the name of
the channel in its title bar and the majority of it is taken up by a
scrolling list that contains what various people are saying on the
channel.

   At the bottom of the channel window is a string gadget where you
enter what you want to say on the channel (up to about 500 characters).

   Below this are four buttons:

@{b}List names@{ub}
     This gets the current list of who is on the channel,

@{b}Clear list@{ub}
     This clears the scrolling chat list,

@{b}Keep to file@{ub}
     This stores the contents of the chat list into a file (a file
     requester will appear to get the name of the file to use),

@{b}Scroll on/off@{ub}
     This is a cycle gadget that enables/disables the scrolling of the
     text list as new messages are added.  This is useful if you want
     to scroll back to reveiw something for a bit,

The Pick and List Channel windows
.................................

   The Pick a Channel (opened by Pick Channels) and List of Channels
(opened by List Channels) windows have the following features:

List of channels:

   @{b}*@{ub} double clicking a channel name in the list will cause that channel
     to be inserted into the Pick a Channel window,

   @{b}*@{ub} the @{b}Add to Pick List@{ub} button does the same thing,

   @{b}*@{ub} the @{b}Keep to file@{ub} button allows the contents to be saved to a file
     for later editing.

Pick a channel:

   @{b}*@{ub} double clicking on a channel name in the list will ask the server
     to allow you to join that channel and another channel window will
     open,

   @{b}*@{ub} the string gadget allows you to enter a channel name by hand
     (rather       than picking it from the list of channels)

   @{b}*@{ub} the @{b}Delete@{ub} button deletes the currently highlighted channel from
        your preferred channels list

   @{b}*@{ub} the @{b}Save@{ub} button allows you to save the list to disk so it is
     available       the next time you start IRC.

General IRC Tips
................

   All of the IRC windows support @{b}TAB@{ub} key cycling through the gadgets.
The gadgets you cannot tab cycle to all have keyboard equivalents.

   Note that MUI also supports @{b}ALT-TAB@{ub} cycling through all the windows
of one application, this can be @{i}quite@{ui} useful for something like IceIRC
if you are short on screen real estate.

   Note that like other IceTERM functions you can use other IceTERM
tools at the same time as the IRC client, in fact you can even use more
than one IRC client at the same time.

IceIRC tool types
.................

   The IRCclient takes two optional tool types in its icon:

@{b}SITELIST=filename@{ub}
     specifies the file that you want the site list to be loaded from
     and saved to,

@{b}CHANLIST=filename@{ub}
     specifies the file that you want the pick a channel list to be
     loaded from and saved to.


@EndNode

@Node "Door tool types" "iceterm.guide/Door tool types"
@Next "Programming doors"
@Prev "IceIRC"
@Toc "Doors"

Tool types for the door icons
-----------------------------

   When the door chooser is started it first scans the doors directory
looking for files which have icons attached.  It opens each icon in
turn looking for ones with the appropriate tool types.  These tool
types are: @{b}STACK@{ub}, @{b}PRIORITY@{ub}, @{b}MENUNAME@{ub}, @{b}SERVER@{ub} and @{b}AREXX@{ub}.

   Door icons @{i}must@{ui} have both the @{b}MENUNAME@{ub} and @{b}SERVER@{ub} tool types for the
door client's name to be displayed in the chooser's list for selection
by the user.  The @{b}STACK@{ub} will default to 8000 bytes if not present and
the @{b}PRIORITY@{ub} will default to 2 if not present.

   @{b}STACK@{ub} sets the number of bytes that the door client's stack will be
set to when the door client process is spawned by the IceTERM package.
@{b}PRIORITY@{ub} is the @{i}communications channel@{ui} priority (not the AmigaDOS task
priority) that the door's client and server will use to communicate.
The priority is user selectable in case you decide that doors are more
or less important than another BBS task.  Setting the priority to zero
(the minimum) will place the door at the same level as SIGs and file
downloads, a priority of 5 is the maximum used within IceTERM (by the
chat and confer functions).

   The @{b}MENUNAME@{ub} is used by the user to specify the name of the door
that will be displayed in the selection menu.  You should set an
informative string here (eg. @{i}Multi User Dungeon@{ui}, @{i}Abandon Hope All Ye
Who Enter Here@{ui} etc.).

   The @{b}SERVER@{ub} tool type is used by the sysop and user to define the name
of the server that is to be launched on the BBS when this client is
started. This allows the user and sysop to change the actual file names
(in case there is a name conflict) while still allowing the correct
server to be launched.  Only the name of the door file on the BBS is
needed here.  If you downloaded a door from another BBS system it is a
good idea to check with the sysop first to see what the correct door
server name is.

   The server icon will also include the @{b}ACCESS@{ub} tool type, the BBS
checks for this tool type to determine which users are allowed to use
the door.  This tool type is not needed in a door client.

   The @{b}AREXX@{ub} tool type is required on doors that are written in ARexx.
This is how IceTERM and IceBBS recognise that these are ARexx doors.


@EndNode

@Node "Programming doors" "iceterm.guide/Programming doors"
@Prev "Door tool types"
@Toc "Doors"

Programming doors
-----------------

   There are two different programming environments for creating IceBBS
doors in: a compiled language such as C or else in ARexx.  In either
case additional programming information, including example source code
for a working client and server, is provided on the distribution disk
sent to sysops.  For the serious C programmer the @{b}toolkit@{ub} archive
contains what is needed, while for the ARexx programmer the @{b}RexxDoorKit@{ub}
contains what is needed. A simulator program is included that allows
one to develop door clients and servers without needing a IceBBS and
IceTERM program running on the development machine.

   Generally speaking the ARexx based doors are much easier to write,
but the end result is not as glamourous as those written in C.  This is
because ARexx has little built in support for Amiga graphics, some of
the additional ARexx libraries can help fill this gap.


@EndNode

@Node "From the CLI" "iceterm.guide/From the CLI"
@Next "Unattended use"
@Prev "Using the terminal"
@Toc "Main"

IceTERM␀from the CLI
********************

   The IceTERM program can be started from the CLI environment. CLI
users will need to keep the @{b}IceTERM.info@{ub} (icon) file around because
this is used to specify the various parameters that IceTERM needs to
run.  As CLI users do not like their directories cluttered with @{b}.info@{ub}
files IceTERM will look for the icon in several places. When IceTERM is
started from the CLI it will first look in the current directory for
the @{b}IceTERM.info@{ub} file(1), if it does not find it there it will then
look in the @{b}S:@{ub} directory and if it fails to find it there it will look
in the @{b}C:@{ub} directory.

   The arguments IceTERM accepts from the CLI are the serial port
device name, the unit number, the baud rate, the handshaking type and
the name of a script file to be run.  These arguments are optional. If
you have an alternate serial board, you can use it by supplying the
name of the appropriate serial device and the unit number.  If you just
supply the serial device name and not the unit number IceTERM will open
unit zero.  Finally, if you specify an alternate serial device and unit
but no baud rate the system will use whatever baud rate is specified
with the Amiga's Serial program (in the Prefs drawer).

   @{i}Note@{ui}: all the command line parameters are applied after IceTERM
reads the configuration information from the tool icon, so if you wish
to override the icon settings without changing the icon you may do so
by supplying the appropriate CLI command line parameter.  Also note
that IceTERM first loads any Amiga defaults (such as preference baud
setting) and @{i}then@{ui} applies the icon parameters, and @{i}then@{ui} applies the CLI
parameters.

   The syntax of IceTERM from the CLI is:

     IceTERM [script] [-ddevice] [-uunitno] [-bbaud] +
          [-hhandshake] [-s]

   where the @{b}[]@{ub} indicate optional parameters.  All parameters except
the script file are identified by a @{b}-@{ub} and a single letter, they are
immediately followed by the parameter value (without any spaces in
between).  Parameters can appear in any order.

   For example to use the ASDG serial card, unit number 1, at 4800 baud
with no handshaking you would use

     IceTERM -b4800 -u1 -dsiosbx.device -hn

   To run IceTERM with a MNP modem connected on the Amiga's serial port
at 9600 baud and use the script file called "demo_script":

     IceTERM demo_script -b9600 -h7

   or equivalently:

     IceTERM demo_script -b9600 -h7 -dserial.device -u0

   will do the trick.

   The @{b}-s@{ub} switch tells IceTERM to open the serial port in shared access
mode.  This may be of use to people running programs like @{b}Getty@{ub}.

   The script file (see @{"Script Files" Link "Script Files"}) is the name of a IceTERM script
file to run to get yourself dialed in to the BBS, any command line
parameter which does not start with a hyphen (@{b}-@{ub}) character will be
taken as the name of the script file to be used.  Only one script file
may be specified.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  if you rename @{b}IceTERM@{ub} to @{b}FarOutTerminal@{ub} you will need to rename
the icon to @{b}FarOutTerminal.info@{ub} as well.


@EndNode

@Node "Unattended use" "iceterm.guide/Unattended use"
@Next "Script Files"
@Prev "From the CLI"
@Toc "Main"

Unattended Use
**************

   IceTERM is highly interactive by nature, however the batch SIGs tool
is suitable for unattended use.  It is possible to call IceTERM from a
cron program or looping AmigaDOS script file.  This way you can have
IceTERM call a BBS several time a day to collect new SIG messages for
you to read with IceOLR.  To do this you will probably want to include
the @{b}deadbeat@{ub} command in your script (see @{"Script Files" Link "Script Files"}) to escape from
troubled connections and you must also include the following tool type:

     AUTOSTART=batch

   Once the batch SIG download is done the BBS will wait until the line
has been idle for about 5 minutes and then log you off.  When this
happens IceTERM will shut down and exit (it may wait for a requester to
disappear first).  Because of this 5 minute delay the automatic system
is not yet suitable for long distance transfers.

   If for some reason an IceTERM requester appears during your session
(appart from AmigaDOS requesters like "disk full") the requester will
be canceled after 20 seconds.  There are a few special requesters that
take upto 30 minutes to disappear, but these only appear when the editor
would appear to edit some text, something that an unattended session
would not be doing.


@EndNode

@Node "Script Files" "iceterm.guide/Script Files"
@Next "Tool types"
@Prev "Unattended use"
@Toc "Main"

The Script File
***************

   IceTERM supports a script file which can be used to make the modem
automatically redial until you are logged in, for dialing a number of
different lines on a single BBS or for dialing a number of BBS systems.


 @{" Parameter types " Link "Parameter types"}      Strings, numbers and labels
 @{" Script commands " Link "Script commands"}      The script command language
 @{" Running scripts " Link "Running scripts"}      How to get IceTERM to use a script
 @{" Auto dial scripts " Link "Auto dial scripts"}    Examples of IceTERM dialing scripts
 @{" Stopping scripts " Link "Stopping scripts"}     how to interrupt a script file


@EndNode

@Node "Parameter types" "iceterm.guide/Parameter types"
@Next "Script commands"
@Prev "Script Files"
@Toc "Script Files"

Script parameters
=================

   The commands for the script file must appear in lower case, they are
generally separated by spaces or are placed on new lines.  In the
following command description the items in uppercase are parameters for
the commands, there are three types of parameters:

@{b}STRING@{ub}
     this is some ASCII text that is to be processed by the command.
     It may include letters, numbers and symbols, but if it includes
     any space characters the string must be enclosed in quotation
     marks.  For example, this may be used to specify the modem dialing
     command,

@{b}N@{ub}
     this is a numeric parameter, a number from 0 to 32767, this is
     used for specifing delays and ASCII character codes,

@{b}LABEL@{ub}
     this is a label that indicates a point in the script file to which
     the script can jump in certain conditions, labels can be any
     alpha-numeric string (as long as they are unique and not the same
     as one of the command names, see @{"Script commands" Link "Script commands"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Script commands" "iceterm.guide/Script commands"
@Next "Running scripts"
@Prev "Parameter types"
@Toc "Script Files"

Script commands
===============

   The following are the commands that the script language understands:

@{b}send STRING@{ub}
     The @{b}send@{ub} command sends the string of text that follows it to the
     serial port. @{b}STRING@{ub} may be a single word such as: @{b}Xyzzy@{ub} or it may
     be a word or words enclosed in double quotes (@{b}"@{ub}), such as: @{b}"this
     is a sample STRING"@{ub}.

@{b}delay N@{ub}
     The @{b}delay@{ub} command delays for @{b}N@{ub} tenths of a second (@{b}N@{ub} is a number).
     For example a @{b}delay 30@{ub} would delay the script file for about 3
     seconds. A common script file error is to use a @{b}wait@{ub} command
     rather than a @{b}delay@{ub},

@{b}goto LABEL@{ub}
     The @{b}goto@{ub} command causes the script to jump to the indicated label
     in the script (either fowards or backwards) and then execution
     will continue following the label.  You may have as many labels as
     you like, labels may be any combinations of ASCII characters which
     do not make up one of the above reserved command words. Labels may
     appear anywhere between two commands,

@{b}wait STRING@{ub}
     The @{b}wait@{ub} command causes execution of the script to pause until the
     desired @{b}STRING@{ub} is received from the serial port or another string
     that triggers an exception is received.  Typically this is used to
     detect a specific modem response before sending more commands,
     often a @{b}wait OK@{ub} command is used.  A common script file error is to
     use a @{b}delay@{ub} command rather than a @{b}wait@{ub} command.

@{b}on STRING LABEL@{ub}
     The @{b}on@{ub} command is used to add a new exception string to the list
     of strings which, when received from the serial port, will cause
     an immediate jump to the specified label.  You may have as many
     exception strings active as you wish.  Specifying the same string
     a second time will erase the first specification allowing you to
     change the branch label (note that the actual labels can only
     appear at one place in the file),

@{b}name STRING@{ub}
     The @{b}name@{ub} command allows you to specify a different user name in
     different parts of the script file, this allows you to log onto
     different BBS systems with different user names from the same
     script file.  For this to work correctly you need to place the
     correct user name command just prior to dialing the number of the
     BBS,

@{b}password STRING@{ub}
     The @{b}password@{ub} command allows you to specify a different password in
     different parts of the script file, this allows you to log onto
     different BBS systems with different passwords from the same
     script file. For this to work correctly you need to place the
     correct password command just prior to dialing the number of the
     BBS,

@{b}exit@{ub}
     The @{b}exit@{ub} command is used to terminate the script file and put the
     IceTERM program into its listen for auto-connect sequence mode,

@{b}beep@{ub}
     The @{b}beep@{ub} command is used to cause the Amiga to issue a beeping
     sound, this is useful to alert yourself to a successful connection
     or some other problem,

@{b}cr@{ub}
     The @{b}cr@{ub} command is used to send a carriage return to the serial
     port, this is usually used immediately after each @{b}send@{ub} command
     that is used to send commands to the modem.  The reason(1) this is
     separate from the @{b}send@{ub} command is so that you can insert a @{b}delay@{ub}
     or @{b}wait@{ub} before the @{b}cr@{ub} command is sent since some modems do not
     like to be sent commands too quickly,

@{b}crlf@{ub}
     The @{b}crlf@{ub} command is used to send a carriage return and then a line
     feed to the serial port, this may be used immediately after each
     @{b}send@{ub} command you use to send commands to the modem(2),

@{b}lf@{ub}
     The @{b}lf@{ub} command is used to send a line feed to the serial port,
     really just here for symmetry considerations,

@{b}char N@{ub}
     The @{b}char@{ub} command will send a single ASCII character (identified by
     its ASCII code number @{b}N@{ub}) to the serial port.  The command: @{b}char 10@{ub}
     is the same as @{b}LF@{ub} and @{b}char 13@{ub} is the same as @{b}CR@{ub},

@{b}print STRING@{ub}
     The @{b}print@{ub} command will cause the string to be printed to the
     display window, without sending anything to the serial port.  This
     is useful for printing status messages telling you what the script
     is currently doing.  It is also possible to get the screen to
     flash by typing a CTRL-G into the string to be printed (in some
     editors),

@{b};comment@{ub}
     Comments in the script file are initiated with the @{b};@{ub} character.
     All the characters that follow until the end of the line is
     reached are considered to be part of the comment.  Blank lines are
     allowed in the script if you wish,

@{b}deadbeat@{ub}
     This command specifies how long a script file should loop or wait
     before stopping and shutting down IceTERM.  For example, if you
     execute the following line in a script file:

          deadbeat 300

     then if the script is still executing (or the terminal is waiting
     for the BBS to wake up still) 30 seconds later then the terminal
     will shut down. The parameter is the number of 1/10ths of a second
     (like the @{b}delay@{ub} command) to wait before closing down IceTERM.  If
     you issue a second dead beat time out at a later point in the
     script then it will reinitialize the count down to the new time
     out value.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This also makes it possible to build very long command strings,
although why you would need to is beyond me.

   (2)  Some older modems do not like the @{b}crlf@{ub} command you should use
the @{b}cr@{ub} command instead.


@EndNode

@Node "Running scripts" "iceterm.guide/Running scripts"
@Next "Auto dial scripts"
@Prev "Script commands"
@Toc "Script Files"

Running scripts
===============

   A script may be automatically run when IceTERM is started either
from the CLI or from an icon.  In the tool icon use the @{b}SCRIPT@{ub} tool
type to specify the name of the script file you want IceTERM to run.
From the CLI you specify the name of the script file somewhere on the
the command line. If IceTERM is started from a project icon no @{b}SCRIPT@{ub}
tool type is necessary as IceTERM will use the name of the project
icon's file as the script file to be run.


@EndNode

@Node "Auto dial scripts" "iceterm.guide/Auto dial scripts"
@Next "Stopping scripts"
@Prev "Running scripts"
@Toc "Script Files"

Script examples
===============

   Here is a brief autodial sequence that will redial one phone number
until it gets through:

     ;add any special modem initialization in this
     ;section.
     ;
     send ATX6    ;extended result codes on a USR modem
     cr
     wait OK
     
     ;now define what the script file is to do when the
     ;modem sends us one of CONNECT, BUSY or NOCARRIER
     ;
     on CONNECT startproto
     on BUSY redial
     on NOCARRIER redial
     
     ;dial the number and then wait for 10 seconds before
     ;trying again
     ;
     redial
     
       send ATZ
       cr
       wait OK
       send ATDP2842048
       cr
       delay 100   ;10 seconds delay
       goto redial
     
     ;the only way we get here is if the modem has connected
     ;and sent us a CONNECT message, IceTERM picks this up
     ;and jumps here.
     ;
     startproto
       beep     ;let the user know we've connected
       exit

   The following script file segment dials two BBS machines, it
illustrates the @{b}name@{ub} and @{b}password@{ub} commands:

     redial
     
       send ATZ
       cr
       wait OK
       ;
       ; set the user name and password for the first BBS
       ;
       name "An Amiga User"
       password "this is a password"
       send ATDP2842048
       cr
       delay 100
       ;
       ; set the user name and password for the second BBS
       ;
       name "Zorro, the Amiga Bus"
       password "this is a different password"
       send ATDP2845625
       cr
       delay 100   ;10 seconds delay
       goto redial


@EndNode

@Node "Stopping scripts" "iceterm.guide/Stopping scripts"
@Prev "Auto dial scripts"
@Toc "Script Files"

Stopping scripts
================

   Script files may be interrupted while they are running by holding
down an @{b}ALT@{ub} key and then hitting the @{b}ESC@{ub} key.  Note that in older
versions of IceTERM the abort key was the @{b}ESC@{ub} alone, this caused
problems when trying to access a BBS that was using TrapDoor as its
front end, so the key press was changed to include the @{b}ALT@{ub} qualifier.


@EndNode

@Node "Tool types" "iceterm.guide/Tool types"
@Next "Encryption"
@Prev "Script Files"
@Toc "Main"

Tool Types
**********

Icons and configurations
========================

   IceTERM normally(1) reads all of its configuration information from
the tool(2) and or project(3) icons associated with it.

   IceTERM has a number of tool types that can be placed in the IceTERM
tool or project icons either by you or by IceTERM when you use the
snapshot (see @{"The main buttons" Link "The main buttons"}) menu item.  These are documented in
several places within this manual.  This chapter is to act as a
reference for these settings.  Note that some of these are not really
intended to be user defined, but appear for completeness.


 @{" From WorkBench " Link "From WorkBench"}       Project and tool icons
 @{" From CLI " Link "From CLI"}             Icons in the S: and C: directories
 @{" Tooltype rules " Link "Tooltype rules"}       The syntax requirements of tool types
 @{" Tool type comments " Link "Tool type comments"}   Commenting out unwanted tool types
 @{" The snapshot menu " Link "The snapshot menu"}    And IceTERM's updating of tool types
 @{" Window positioning " Link "Window positioning"}   Customizing window layouts
 @{" Screen control " Link "Screen control"}       Selecting screen size and number of colours
 @{" Scrolling screens " Link "Scrolling screens"}    Support for virtual screens
 @{" Colour palettes " Link "Colour palettes"}      The many colours of IceTERM
 @{" Alternate fonts " Link "Alternate fonts"}      Specifing a different font or size
 @{" Text colour " Link "Text colour"}          Changing the colour of the text
 @{" Starting scripts " Link "Starting scripts"}     Specifing the dialing script
 @{" Syncronizing clocks " Link "Syncronizing clocks"}  Downloading BBS time
 @{" Timer control " Link "Timer control"}        Adjusting the update rate
 @{" Task priority " Link "Task priority"}        Raytracing and IceTERM
 @{" Special directories " Link "Special directories"}  Places IceTERM stores files for you
 @{" The editor " Link "The editor"}           Selecting a different editor
 @{" The keepfile " Link "The keepfile"}         A handy place to save things
 @{" The tools " Link "The tools"}            More details on all the tools
 @{" WBHACK " Link "WBHACK"}               Forcing editors to use IceTERM's screen
 @{" Autostart " Link "Autostart"}            Automatically starting tools at login
 @{" The control window " Link "The control window"}   The main control panel of IceTERM
 @{" Name and password " Link "Name and password"}    The login data
 @{" Serial port " Link "Serial port"}          Controlling the serial port
 @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}                 Serial port diagnostic display
 @{" Tooltype bugs " Link "Tooltype bugs"}        AmigaDOS 1.3 or older

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  With the exception of the occasional user who starts it from
the CLI.

   (2)  A tool icon is the icon that WorkBench has attached to a
program so that the user can run or manipulate it in some way.

   (3)  Project icons are icons that are attached to data files (such
as text files, pictures, sound samples, songs and IceTERM scripts).


@EndNode

@Node "From WorkBench" "iceterm.guide/From WorkBench"
@Next "From CLI"
@Prev "Tool types"
@Toc "Tool types"

Starting from the WorkBench
===========================

   If IceTERM is started by double clicking on the tool icon alone,
then it will read just the tool types array of that one icon to
determine how it is to be configured.  If IceTERM is started by either
double clicking on a project icon(1) or by extended selection(2)
IceTERM will first read any tool types in the tool icon (if this icon
in fact exists) and then will read the tool types in the project icon,
note that if any tool types appear in both icons the values read last
will override those read earlier.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  For which the default tool is set to IceTERM.

   (2)  The user single clicks on one icon first and then while holding
down the shift key double clicks on the other icon.  The two icons are
the IceTERM program's icon and the project icon of a script file.


@EndNode

@Node "From CLI" "iceterm.guide/From CLI"
@Next "Tooltype rules"
@Prev "From WorkBench"
@Toc "Tool types"

Starting from the CLI
=====================

   If IceTERM is started from the CLI it will look for a @{b}IceTERM.info@{ub}
file(1), and will load any tool types it finds there.  It will load the
icon files' tool types @{i}before@{ui} scanning the CLI parameters (see
@{"From the CLI" Link "From the CLI"}), so the CLI may be used to temporarily override the icon
settings.  IceTERM is persistent in its searching for an icon, it will
look first in the current directory, then it will look in the @{b}S:@{ub}
directory and then it will look in the @{b}C:@{ub} directory(2).

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This is how the IceTERM icon appears to a CLI user.

   (2)  The reason for all this searching is that CLI users generally
do not like icon files cluttering their directories, so this allows
them to hide the icons away somewhere they don't often look at.


@EndNode

@Node "Tooltype rules" "iceterm.guide/Tooltype rules"
@Next "Tool type comments"
@Prev "From CLI"
@Toc "Tool types"

Tool type rules
===============

   The keyword part(1) of a tool type should appear in uppercase.  This
is not a strict requirement since @{i}all@{ui} of IceTERM's tool types
processing is case-insensitive(2); however, the @{i}Amiga User Interface
Style Guide@{ui} insists that case sensitivity is the proper way.

   Also note that there should generally be @{i}no spaces@{ui} between the tool
type name, the equals sign and the parameter.  If spaces are included
either the tool type will not be recognized or the parameter will
include the space at the start of it.  You can include spaces within
the parameter itself if it is appropriate to do so (for example between
your first and last name in the @{b}user@{ub} tool type); however, spaces in
file and directory names are just a very good way of making your life
unpleasant.  Tool types should be kept short, generally about 60
characters is a good upper limit.

   Also note that tool types can appear in any order; however, if a tool
type appears twice the last of the two will override the first(3).

   Tool types can be used to specify a number of different things.
These include directory names, file names, window sizes and positions,
and even the state of some of the buttons.

   Tool types which take file names expect to be given a full AmigaDOS
file name, you should include the drive in this too, like:

     KEEPFILE=dh1:t/keepfile.txt

   It is possible to use relative paths in the directory part of the
name if you know what you are doing.

   Tool types which take directory names expect to be given a full
AmigaDOS directory name, you should include the drive in this too, like:

     TEMPDIR=dh1:t

   Craig Lever discovered it is also possible to use @{i}environmental
variables@{ui} (4) in the tool types.  For example, if the variable @{b}editor@{ub} is
set as follows:

     SETENV editor "C:ed"

   The following tool type will define @{b}ed@{ub} as the IceTERM editor:

     EDITOR=$editor

   Tool types that specify window snapshot information take a series of
numbers separated by vertical bar characters(5).  For example

     CHATWINDOW=0|63|561|109

   specifies that the chat window should open zero pixels from the left
edge of the screen, 63 pixels down from the top of the screen, and it
should be 561 pixels wide and 109 pixels high.

   Some tool types take a string of characters.  In this case @{i}all@{ui} the
characters after the equals sign (which is effectively the last
character in the tool type name) will be included in the string.  This
is important as the following tool types do @{i}not@{ui} reference the same user
account:

     USER=Joe Doe
     USER= Joe Doe
     USER=Joe  Doe

   In fact IceBBS will see these as three different accounts, a fact
that can sometimes be confusing...

   A number of configuration tool types take a single numeric quantity.
This should be composed only of the digits 0, 1...9 and possibly a
minus sign.  Examples of these are:

     TEXTPEN=1
     UNIT=8
     BAUD=19200

   Most of these numeric tool types will perform some additional range
checking on the number you specify, so sometimes you may not get
exactly what you are asking for.  For example @{b}BAUD=14400@{ub} is not legal
as not all serial devices can run at this rate (even though most high
speed modems can transmit at it), for this reason the IceTERM might
choose to use @{b}BAUD=9600@{ub} instead.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This is the word to the left of the equals sign.

   (2)  IceTERM used to be case sensitive but far too many users got
confused, so it was made to ignore the case of letters and there have
been no complaints since.

   (3)  Except in the case of the @{b}PALETTE@{ub} tool type.

   (4)  Environmental variables are variables that are maintained by
AmigaDOS.  Refer to your AmigaDOS manual for more information.

   (5)  The vertical bar @{b}|@{ub} is sometimes known as the pipe character.


@EndNode

@Node "Tool type comments" "iceterm.guide/Tool type comments"
@Next "The snapshot menu"
@Prev "Tooltype rules"
@Toc "Tool types"

Commenting out tool types
=========================

   If you wish to comment out a tool type so that it does not take
effect you can do so quite simply by just placing a character like a
semi-colon (@{b};@{ub}) or an @{b}x@{ub} in front of the tool type.  This changes the
tool type to something that IceTERM does not recognize so you don't
have to delete and re-enter tool types while testing things out.
Commodore recommends placing the whole tool type and value within
brackets, for example:

     (SWIDTH=656)


@EndNode

@Node "The snapshot menu" "iceterm.guide/The snapshot menu"
@Next "Window positioning"
@Prev "Tool type comments"
@Toc "Tool types"

The snapshot menu
=================

   When you use the snapshot menu (see @{"The main buttons" Link "The main buttons"}) that is
attached to most of the tools in IceTERM you may observe considerable
disk activity taking place. What is happening is that IceTERM is
updating the tool types pertaining to the window whose menu you just
used.  These tool types are written into the icon that IceTERM was
started from. Older versions of IceTERM did not update the tool types
that already existed in the icon, they always added fresh tool types to
the end of the icon's tool type array.  This could lead to a lot of
tool types indeed.  The new versions of IceTERM update the tool types,
but they stop scanning with the first match they find. This can lead to
a situation where if there are duplicate tool types in the icon
(perhaps from running older versions of IceTERM) it appears that
IceTERM is not updating the icon, or if it is, it appears that the
updates are being ignored.  The solution is to delete the second and
later copies of all tool types in the icon.

   Note that if the icon is currently visible on the WorkBench there
may be a conflict between IceTERM and the WorkBench, see
@{"Problems snapshotting" Link "Problems snapshotting"}. Another problem that may arise is that under
older versions of AmigaDOS multiple tool types can get joined together,
see @{"Tooltype bugs" Link "Tooltype bugs"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Window positioning" "iceterm.guide/Window positioning"
@Next "Screen control"
@Prev "The snapshot menu"
@Toc "Tool types"

Window positioning
==================

   A number of the following tool types are configuration entries which
the terminal program will save to the icon file whenever the user
selects the @{b}Snapshot@{ub} menu item (see @{"The snapshot menu" Link "The snapshot menu"}).  There are two
kinds of these entries, ones which allow the initial position and size
of the window to be saved and restored and a number of customization
items which record the user's preferred button settings.  The window
position and size tool types all use the same format, they consist of
the tool type name followed by an equals sign @{b}=@{ub}, followed by four
numbers separated by vertical bar @{b}|@{ub} characters.  The first number is
the @{i}x@{ui} coordinate (in pixels) of the left edge of the window, measured
from the left edge of the screen where the window should open.  The
second is the @{i}y@{ui} coordinate of the top edge of the window, measured from
the top edge of the screen, where the window is to open.  The third and
fourth numbers are the width and height of the window when it opens.


@EndNode

@Node "Screen control" "iceterm.guide/Screen control"
@Next "Scrolling screens"
@Prev "Window positioning"
@Toc "Tool types"

Screen control
==============

   IceTERM has the ability to run on its own custom screen.  If you
specify any of @{b}SWIDTH@{ub}, @{b}SHEIGHT@{ub} or @{b}SDEPTH@{ub} in the IceTERM icon's tool
types array, IceTERM will open its own custom screen and all its
windows will appear on it.  This really helps to unload the WorkBench,
so give it a try!  The @{b}SWIDTH@{ub} specifies the width of the screen in
pixels, it must be at least 640 wide.  The @{b}SHEIGHT@{ub} specifies the number
of lines on the display, if you select 400 you will get an interlaced
display.  @{b}SDEPTH@{ub} is the number of bit planes to use for the screen, 1
gives you 2 colours, 2 gives you 4, 3 gives you 8 and 4 gives you 16.
I strongly advise against using the 16 colour option, especially if you
are running on an unexpanded or unaccelerated system.


@EndNode

@Node "Scrolling screens" "iceterm.guide/Scrolling screens"
@Next "Colour palettes"
@Prev "Screen control"
@Toc "Tool types"

Scrolling screens
-----------------

   If you are running AmigaDOS 2.0 you will find that IceTERM will
support the scrollable screen mode.  All that you need to do to make
use of these screens that may be taller and or wider than the monitor is
to set the @{b}SWIDTH@{ub} and @{b}SHEIGHT@{ub} tool types to be larger than the visible
screen size(1). In this fashion you can even run IceTERM on a screen as
large (or larger) than 1024 by 800.  The only thing to watch out for
here is chip memory!

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  However, you cannot scroll a screen higher than 400 pixels in a
non-interlaced display.  Setting the SHEIGHT tool type equal to or
greater than 400 currently yields an interlaced display.


@EndNode

@Node "Colour palettes" "iceterm.guide/Colour palettes"
@Next "Alternate fonts"
@Prev "Scrolling screens"
@Toc "Tool types"

Colour palettes
---------------

   So that you can set up custom colours for your custom screen the
IceTERM program recognizes the @{b}PALETTE@{ub} tool type to specify a custom
screen colour.  If you are running a 2 bitplane (4 colour) screen you
will need 4 lines of @{b}PALETTE@{ub} commands.  The @{b}PALETTE@{ub} tool type is
followed by three characters from the set: @{b}0@{ub}, @{b}1@{ub}, @{b}2@{ub}, ... @{b}9@{ub}, @{b}A@{ub}, @{b}B@{ub}, @{b}C@{ub}, @{b}D@{ub},
@{b}E@{ub}, @{b}F@{ub}. These represent the numbers zero through to 15, and these are
taken as being the brightness of the three colours (red, green and
blue) that make up the video display.  If the colour: @{b}000@{ub} is specified
then black will be used, if @{b}FFF@{ub} is selected then the result is white,
and @{b}060@{ub} will be a dark green.  For example:

     PALETTE=AAA
     PALETTE=000
     PALETTE=FFF
     PALETTE=679

   will give you a custom screen with the same colours as 2.0 uses(1).
Note each subsequent palette entry @{i}appends@{ui} to the palette definition
table, this is @{i}unlike@{ui} other tool types where subsequent ones completely
overrode the previous ones.  Because of this, if you have a 4 colour
screen and you have 4 palette entries in the TOOL icon for IceTERM then
any additional palette entries that you define in a PROJECT icon will appear
to be ignored.  They are not really ignored, but they are just defining
colours 5-8 which you cannot see on a 4 colour screen.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Craig Lever suggested a palette of 000, AA9, F70, 008.


@EndNode

@Node "Alternate fonts" "iceterm.guide/Alternate fonts"
@Next "Text colour"
@Prev "Colour palettes"
@Toc "Tool types"

Alternate fonts
---------------

   IceTERM can use different fonts for its displays, it can use both
fixed width and proportionally spaced fonts (although fixed width are
usually to be preferred(1)).  With the @{b}FONT@{ub} tool type set you can
specify a different font to be used by name.  For example to use the
pearl font specify:

     FONT=pearl.font

   To specify the size of the font you use the @{b}FONTSIZE@{ub} tool type.  If
you have installed AmigaDOS 2.0 you are not limited to specifing only
the font sizes that exist on your system.  The new font routines are
able to scale @{i}any@{ui} font to the size you desire.  As this scaling takes
some time the @{b}Fountain@{ub} tool is provided as part of the new WorkBench so
that you can make new sizes once and save them to disk.  To load the
CGTimes font at a 15 point size you would specify:

     FONT=CGTimes.font
     FONTSIZE=15

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Using proportional fonts can mess up the displays in the chat,
talk, feedback and conference tools.


@EndNode

@Node "Text colour" "iceterm.guide/Text colour"
@Next "Starting scripts"
@Prev "Alternate fonts"
@Toc "Tool types"

Text colour
-----------

   A tool type has been added to allow you to change the colour of the
pen that is used to render all the text in IceTERM's gadgets and other
displays.  This is the @{b}TEXTPEN@{ub} tool type.  It takes a single number
which is the number of the pen to be used, typically 1, 2 or 3 would be
used.  For example, if you have kept the default AmigaDOS 2.0 colour
scheme, then you can make all the text in IceTERM black by using:

     TEXTPEN=1


@EndNode

@Node "Starting scripts" "iceterm.guide/Starting scripts"
@Next "Syncronizing clocks"
@Prev "Text colour"
@Toc "Tool types"

Running a script file
=====================

   A script (see @{"Script Files" Link "Script Files"}) may be automatically run when IceTERM is
started either from the CLI or from an icon.  In the tool icon use the
@{b}SCRIPT@{ub} tool type to specify the name of the script file you want
IceTERM to run.

   If you are starting IceTERM from a project icon, then the file
associated with that icon (ie. the file that has the same name as the
icon) will be taken as being the script file that is to be run, any
@{b}SCRIPT@{ub} tool types will be ignored.


@EndNode

@Node "Syncronizing clocks" "iceterm.guide/Syncronizing clocks"
@Next "Timer control"
@Prev "Starting scripts"
@Toc "Tool types"

Setting your clock to match BBS time
====================================

   The SIGs function on old versions of IceTERM (pre v98) may have
problems retrieving new messages for you if you do not keep your clock
properly adjusted. If you don't have battery a backed up clock, the
tool type @{b}SETCLOCK@{ub} when set to @{b}yes@{ub} will allow IceTERM to change your
machine's system time to match that of the IceBBS system you are
calling.  The default setting is @{b}no@{ub}.

   If you are calling from another time zone you probably will not want
to enable this feature.


@EndNode

@Node "Timer control" "iceterm.guide/Timer control"
@Next "Task priority"
@Prev "Syncronizing clocks"
@Toc "Tool types"

Countdown and session timers
============================

   The @{b}UPDATERATE@{ub} tool type is used to set the number of seconds
between updates of the session timer and count down timer.  To get the
timers to change every second set this to @{b}1@{ub}.  The default is to update
every 10 seconds.  For users of unaccelerated machines that are trying
to use high speed modems it is recomended to set this to a large value.

     UPDATERATE=60

   This will update the timer once per minute.


@EndNode

@Node "Task priority" "iceterm.guide/Task priority"
@Next "Special directories"
@Prev "Timer control"
@Toc "Tool types"

Task priority
=============

   For those who like to run IceTERM from the WorkBench along with
something that consumes a lot of CPU (like a ray tracer) the @{b}PRIORITY@{ub}
tool type can be used to run IceTERM at a priority higher than the
WorkBench normally will do (see @{"Multitasking" Link "Multitasking"}).  Generally setting this
to @{b}3@{ub} will be sufficient. For example:

     PRIORITY=3


@EndNode

@Node "Special directories" "iceterm.guide/Special directories"
@Next "The editor"
@Prev "Task priority"
@Toc "Tool types"

Directories
===========

   The following tool types are used to specify the names of directories
that IceTERM should use for certain purposes.  It is recomended that
each of these be set to a @{i}different@{ui} directory and that these
directories not be used for any other purpose (as IceTERM may wish to
delete files in these directories from time to time).

   @{b}MESSROOT@{ub} This is used to specify a directory where you want the
batch SIGs tool to download the messages bases to.  If this tool type
does not exist when the SIGs tool is started IceTERM will prompt you
for a directory.  This directory is used both by the on-line SIGs tool
and by OLR (see @{"Batch SIGs" Link "Batch SIGs"}), the off-line reading, replying and posting
system, so you will need to create this directory on a disk with some
free space.  The directory should exist before you start IceTERM (and
hit either the @{b}Sigs@{ub} see @{"SIGs" Link "SIGs"} or @{b}BatchSIG@{ub} buttons see @{"Batch SIGs" Link "Batch SIGs"}) and
you should @{i}not@{ui} store anything else in this directory.

   @{b}EMAILROOT@{ub} This is used specify a directory where you want any email
(see @{"EMail" Link "EMail"}) that is sent to you to be saved and where the user list
(see @{"The user list" Link "The user list"}) is also to be saved between IceTERM sessions (so
you don't have to keep downloading it).  Again this directory should
exist before you start using email.

   @{b}DOWNDIR@{ub} This is used to specify a directory where you want any files
you download to be put.

   @{b}TEMPDIR@{ub}  This is where IceTERM will store a number of different
temporary files it creates from time to time, typically files for use
with your editor.  To speed things you might assign this to @{b}T:@{ub} or
perhaps @{b}RAM:@{ub}.

   @{b}DOORDIR@{ub} This is the directory where the client side of IceBBS doors
(see @{"Doors" Link "Doors"}) are to be searched for.  When the user clicks on the @{b}Doors@{ub}
button IceTERM will scan this directory and display a list of the
available doors for the user to pick from.  Note that both the door
client program and its icon must be placed in this directory.

Files
=====


@EndNode

@Node "The editor" "iceterm.guide/The editor"
@Next "The keepfile"
@Prev "Special directories"
@Toc "Tool types"

The editor
----------

   @{b}EDITOR@{ub}  IceTERM allows you to select the editor you wish to compose
email, file descriptions, and messages with.  The default is @{b}ED@{ub} and you
will probably want to change that. The limitation is that the editor
@{i}must@{ui} be in your @{b}C:@{ub} directory (at least under AmigaDOS 1.3), or you
should specify the full path to the editor (see @{"Tooltype rules" Link "Tooltype rules"}).  If
you are running IceTERM on its own screen you should note that some
editors will only open on the WorkBench, or even their own screens.

   If you are running AmigaDOS 2.0 you may need to add the @{b}WBHACK@{ub} tool
type to get your editor to open on IceTERM's screen (see
@{"Message problems" Link "Message problems"}).

   IceTERM also supports the new public screen feature of AmigaDOS 2.0
and higher. If your editor supports opening its windows on a named
public screen you might be able to use this technique to get the editor
to open on IceTERM's screen (see @{"WBHACK" Link "WBHACK"}).


@EndNode

@Node "The keepfile" "iceterm.guide/The keepfile"
@Next "WBHACK"
@Prev "The editor"
@Toc "Tool types"

The keepfile
------------

   @{b}KEEPFILE@{ub} When you are reading messages in the feedback tool, you can
save interesting ones by just hitting a button. These messages are
saved in the file specified by this tool type.  Please note that you
should include the full path to the file, as in:
     KEEPFILE=dh1:vterm/stuff/goodies.txt
   where @{b}goodies.txt@{ub} is the file which will contain the saved messages.


@EndNode

@Node "WBHACK" "iceterm.guide/WBHACK"
@Next "Autostart"
@Prev "The keepfile"
@Toc "Tool types"

WBHACK
------

   This tool type can be used with editors that do not support public
screens(1) to force the editor to open on IceTERM's custom screen.  As
this tool type uses a bit of a sneaky trick (it temporarily changes the
IceTERM screen into a @{i}WorkBench@{ui} type screen) there are some potential
side effects you should watch out for.  The most common is that while
the editor is active on IceTERM's screen you change screens to the
WorkBench screen and start clicking on drawer icons.  If the IceTERM
screen is still the front most screen you will find the WorkBench
drawers opening on it instead of on the WorkBench.  This may also
happen with programs you start while the editor is running.  Neither of
these is dangerous @{i}unless@{ui} you close IceTERM before you close all the
stray windows on it's screen. See also @{"Message problems" Link "Message problems"}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Or on pre-AmigaDOS 2.0 machines that do not have the public
screen facility available to be used.


@EndNode

@Node "Autostart" "iceterm.guide/Autostart"
@Next "The tools"
@Prev "WBHACK"
@Toc "Tool types"

Autostart
---------

   The @{b}AUTOSTART@{ub} tool type is used to automatically start up some of
IceTERM's functions as soon as you log in.  For example you might add:

     AUTOSTART=batch
     AUTOSTART=feedback

   and then IceTERM will automatically start scanning the SIGs and
downloading feedback as soon as you connect.

   If you are a CLI user then you need to locate your IceTERM icon
(where ever you have hidden it) and then by adding the @{b}AUTOSTART=batch@{ub}
you can do an autologin, SIG scan and logout by waiting for the idle
timeout.

   All twelve main control panel buttons can be specified.  They are:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}chat@{ub} to open a chat window,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}talk@{ub} to open a talk window,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}news@{ub} to open the news window,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}sigs@{ub} to start the on-line SIG reader,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}batch@{ub} to start the batch SIG downloader,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}email@{ub} to open the email tool,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}feedback@{ub} to start reading feedback,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}get@{ub} to start the get files directory browser,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}send@{ub} to prepare to send a file,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}doors@{ub} to open the doors selector,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}shell@{ub} to open an AmigaDOS shell on the BBS,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}confer@{ub} to start the conference tool,

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}monitor@{ub} to start the activity monitor.

   Note that all of these can be abbreviated to the first two letters
and none are case sensitive.


@EndNode

@Node "The tools" "iceterm.guide/The tools"
@Next "The control window"
@Prev "Autostart"
@Toc "Tool types"


Detailed information on the various tool types that are generated
during the snapshotting of the various tools appears here.  There
normally will be no need to edit any of these tool types.

 @{" Confer " Link "Conference tool"}                 
 @{" Get files " Link "Get files tool"}                
 @{" Monitor " Link "Monitor tool"}              
 @{" Sigs " Link "Sigs tool"}           
 @{" BatchSigs " Link "BatchSigs tool"}                
 @{" Feedback " Link "Feedback tool"}               
 @{" Chat " Link "Chat tool"}           
 @{" Talk " Link "Talk tool"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Conference tool" "iceterm.guide/Conference tool"
@Next "Get files tool"
@Prev "The tools"
@Toc "The tools"

The conference tool
===================

   The @{b}CONFHISTORY@{ub} tool type enters a number which specifies the number
of lines that are to be kept in the conference window's scrollable
history buffer.  A value such as 30-50 is appropriate.

   The @{b}HAILSTRING@{ub} and @{b}TAILSTRING@{ub} tool types contain text or control
characters you want sent with each paragraph you type in the conference
window to identify your messages (see @{"Conference" Link "Conference"}).  The first is the
text you want put at the start of your message and the second is the
text you want put at the end of your message.  Remember to reset the
pen type and colour to their default settings by the end of the message
if you are using ANSI codes.

   The @{b}CONFLOG@{ub} tool type is used to specify the name of the file to
which the multi-user conference should be logged when the @{b}Log@{ub} button is
pressed.  If this is not present the file name will default to
@{b}RAM:CONF.LOG@{ub}.

   The @{b}CONFWINDOW@{ub} tool type is for setting position and size of the
conference window of the conference tool, this is the window with
scroll back where everything everyone in the conference says is written.

   The @{b}USERWINDOW@{ub} tool type is for setting position and size of the
user's editing window in the conference tool.  This is the window where
the user is typing the message he wants to enter into the conference.


@EndNode

@Node "Get files tool" "iceterm.guide/Get files tool"
@Next "Monitor tool"
@Prev "Conference tool"
@Toc "The tools"

Get files tool
==============

   The following tool types are used by the get files tool:

@{b}GETFILE_BTNS@{ub}
     The window that holds the buttons for the get files tool,

@{b}GETFILE_FILES@{ub}
     The window that holds the list of files to choose from within the
     get files tool,

@{b}GETFILE_DIRS@{ub}
     The window that holds the list of directories to choose from
     within the get files tool,

@{b}GETFILE_CFRM@{ub}
     The status of the @{b}Confirm@{ub} button in the get files tool,

@{b}GETFILE_DESC@{ub}
     The status of the @{b}Describe@{ub} button in the get files tool,

@{b}GETFILE_NAME@{ub}
     The status of the sorting type button (by @{b}Name@{ub} or by @{b}Date@{ub}) in the
     get files tool,

@{b}GETFILE_YMD@{ub}
     The status of the date style button (brief @{b}YMD@{ub} or @{b}Full@{ub} format) in
     the get files tool,

@{b}GETFILE_VERBOSE@{ub}
     The status of the short description control button (the @{b}?@{ub} button)
     in the get files tool.

@{b}BUFFERS@{ub}
     Older versions of IceTERM used to write the received data to disk
     in 200 byte chunks, by default the new IceTERM will write it in
     1024 byte (1K) chunks. This speeds up downloads (especially to
     floppies) on unaccelerated machines.  The tool type @{b}BUFFERS@{ub} can be
     used to customize the buffer size.  To get the buffer size of
     older IceTERMs you include the tooltype:

          BUFFERS=0

     To get a 4096 byte buffer (4K) you use:

          BUFFERS=3840

     as 3840+256 = 4096.

     On my machine (A2000 equipped with a 33MHz 68040) I can download
     to @{i}floppy@{ui} disk at up to 4142 bytes per second with a 4K buffer
     size using a ComSpec serial port set to 57600 baud.  Downloading
     to @{b}RAM:@{ub} runs at about 4418 bytes per second.  On a non-accelerated
     Amiga the improvement in floppy speeds (or even downloading to
     hard drive) at high serial port rates (especially on the internal
     serial port) should be more dramatic.


@EndNode

@Node "Monitor tool" "iceterm.guide/Monitor tool"
@Next "Sigs tool"
@Prev "Get files tool"
@Toc "The tools"

Monitor tool
============

   The following tool types are used by the monitor tool:

@{b}MON_BTNS@{ub}
     The window that holds the buttons for the monitor tool,

@{b}MON_LIST@{ub}
     The window that holds the list of events that the monitor tool is
     displaying,

@{b}MON_STATS@{ub}
     The BBS statistics windonw, this displays the BBS up time and the
     list of lines and who is on them,

@{b}MON_BELL@{ub}
     The status of the @{b}Bell@{ub} button that enables or disables the paging
     bell in the monitor tool,

@{b}MON_FLASH@{ub}
     The status of the @{b}Flash@{ub} button that enables or disables the paging
     screen flash in the monitor tool.


@EndNode

@Node "Sigs tool" "iceterm.guide/Sigs tool"
@Next "BatchSigs tool"
@Prev "Monitor tool"
@Toc "The tools"

SIGs tool
=========

@{b}NSWINDOW@{ub}
     The window that displays the SIGs control panel,

@{b}NSDATE@{ub}
     The window that displays the goto message by date or search string
     control panel,

@{b}NSTHREAD@{ub}
     The state of the high mark control button (either @{b}New@{ub} or @{b}Manual@{ub}),

@{b}NSALLSUB@{ub}
     The state of the button that selects between the list of all the
     SIGs or just the subscription (either @{b}All@{ub} or @{b}Sub@{ub}),

@{b}NSQUOTE@{ub}
     The quoting mode control button's setting, a single digit:

    @{b}0@{ub}
          no quoting will be done,

    @{b}1@{ub}
          the message will be quoted by inserting the quoting string at
          the start of each line,

    @{b}2@{ub}
          a header line containing the author and date of the original
          message will be written at the begining of the reply,

    @{b}3@{ub}
          both the header line and the message quoting will be done.

@{b}NSQUOTETEXT@{ub}
     The text that will be inserted at the beginning of message lines
     to quote a reply,

@{b}NSQUOTEHEAD@{ub}
     The text that will be used to generate the introductory header on
     replies,

@{b}NSAUTH@{ub}
     The state of the button that enables the author filter,

@{b}NSSUBJ@{ub}
     The state of the button that enables the subject filter,

@{b}NSMESSAGE@{ub}
     The window that displays the message text,

@{b}NSSUB_LIST@{ub}
     The window that displays which SIGs the user is currently
     subscribed to,

@{b}NSALL_LIST@{ub}
     The window that displays the list of all the SIGs that are
     available,

@{b}NSPICK_LIST@{ub}
     The window that displays the list of SIGs to choose from for the
     goto SIG function,

@{b}NSMOVE_LIST@{ub}
     The window that displays the list of SIGs for a moderator to pick
     where to move a message to.


@EndNode

@Node "BatchSigs tool" "iceterm.guide/BatchSigs tool"
@Next "Feedback tool"
@Prev "Sigs tool"
@Toc "The tools"

Batch SIGs tool
===============

   The @{b}BATCHWINDOW@{ub} is used to set the size and position of the window
which displays the batch SIGs tool's control panel.


@EndNode

@Node "Feedback tool" "iceterm.guide/Feedback tool"
@Next "Chat tool"
@Prev "BatchSigs tool"
@Toc "The tools"

Feedback tool
=============

   The @{b}SIGWINDOW@{ub} tool type is used to set the size and position of the
window that displays the feedback messages for the user to read.


@EndNode

@Node "Chat tool" "iceterm.guide/Chat tool"
@Next "Talk tool"
@Prev "Feedback tool"
@Toc "The tools"

Chat tool
=========

   The @{b}CHATWINDOW@{ub} tool type is used to set the size and position of the
chat window.


@EndNode

@Node "Talk tool" "iceterm.guide/Talk tool"
@Prev "Chat tool"
@Toc "The tools"

Talk tool
=========

   The @{b}TALKWINDOW@{ub} tool type is used to set the size and position of the
speech window.


@EndNode

@Node "The control window" "iceterm.guide/The control window"
@Next "Name and password"
@Prev "The tools"
@Toc "Tool types"

The control window
==================

   The @{b}CONTROLWINDOW@{ub} tool type is used to set the size and position of
the main control panel for IceTERM.


@EndNode

@Node "Name and password" "iceterm.guide/Name and password"
@Next "Serial port"
@Prev "The control window"
@Toc "Tool types"

User and password
=================

   The @{b}USER@{ub} and @{b}PASSWORD@{ub} entries are used to specify your user name and
password.  The IceTERM program will automatically send these to the BBS
when you connect to it and log you in.  If you do not already have an
account, the BBS will create one for you.  Both of these entries are
limited to 63 characters(1) and capitilization is not important--that
is, @{b}Fred@{ub} is the same as @{b}fred@{ub}.  Spaces are important and the length of
names can be a concern on FidoNet (see @{"Basic Tool types" Link "Basic Tool types"}), along with
the presence of special characters(2).

   One other feature was added for the use of IceTERM in a @{i}family
setting@{ui}, this is a password prompt.  If you do not put a password tool
type in the IceTERM icon then IceTERM will prompt you to enter a
password for the BBS before it starts dialing.  This actually was
already there, except it would save the pasword into your icon tool
types for future use, it now no longer saves the password.  A feature
like this deserves credit to the person who suggested it, but since
that name might live in infamy I will be gallant about it and keep
silent.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  If you plan to use FidoNet email you should limit your name to
30 characters or less.

   (2)  If you want a reliable Internet address simplify your name so
that it only contains letters and digits, and it uses periods or
underscores instead of spaces (see @{"Your address" Link "Your address"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Serial port" "iceterm.guide/Serial port"
@Next "LINK"
@Prev "Name and password"
@Toc "Tool types"

The serial port
===============

   The @{b}BAUD@{ub} tool type is used to set the baud rate between IceTERM and
your modem (see @{"Basic Serial Port" Link "Basic Serial Port"}).  If this item is not specified
IceTERM will use the baud rate that you have set in the Amiga serial
preferences tool.  Most current modems are 1200 or 2400 baud, the newer
MNP and V.42 modems use 9600 baud, and the more advanced (and
expensive) modems can use 19200 and 38400 baud.

   The @{b}HANDSHAKE@{ub} tool type is used to select the type of handshaking
that is to be used between IceTERM and your modem (see
@{"Basic Serial Port" Link "Basic Serial Port"}).  If no handshaking tool type is set in the IceTERM
icon then IceTERM will use the default you have set up in the serial
preferences tool.

   There are two methods of handshaking (see @{"MNP error" Link "MNP error"}) that can be
used with IceTERM, either @{b}none@{ub} or @{b}7wire@{ub}.  The first (@{b}none@{ub}) is quite
simple, it specifies that no handshaking is to be used so there is no
way for the computer to tell the modem to slow down when its buffers
get full (or visa versa).  This is generally quite safe for 1200 and
2400 baud modems; however, it is @{i}not@{ui} safe for MNP, V42 or higher speed
modems.  To disable handshaking use: @{b}HANDSHAKE=none@{ub}.

   There are some very old modems that do not support the @{b}7wire@{ub} mode of
handshaking (see @{"Scripts will not run" Link "Scripts will not run"}), for these you must use the @{b}none@{ub}
mode.

   The @{b}7wire@{ub} mode is usually to be preferred over @{b}none@{ub}; however, there
are some complications, you must have a serial cable that supports the
additional wires(1) and your modem may need to be told to turn on the
handshaking (see @{"Modem settings" Link "Modem settings"}) (look for commands relating to CTS/RTS
or seven wire handshaking).  To enable handshaking set: @{b}HANDSHAKE=7wire@{ub}.

   The serial device that IceTERM is to use may be set by the @{b}DEVICE@{ub}
tool type.  This is useful if you have some extra serial ports on an
expansion card.  For the ASDG dual serial board the setting to use
would be @{b}DEVICE=siosbx.device@{ub}.  Each serial port device can potentially
have more than one unit.  By default the first unit is normally unit
number zero.  If your serial card supports more than one port then the
@{b}UNIT@{ub} tool type can be used to tell IceTERM to use a different port.
For the Commodore A2232 card (which has 7 ports) the physically lowest
port on the expansion connector is selected with @{b}UNIT=2@{ub} and the
top-most port is selected with @{b}UNIT=8@{ub}.

   IceTERM can also open the serial port in shared mode for those who
really want to.  To get this to happen include the tool type @{b}SHARED@{ub}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This is usually the case with prefabricated serial cables these
days.


@EndNode

@Node "LINK" "iceterm.guide/LINK"
@Next "Tooltype bugs"
@Prev "Serial port"
@Toc "Tool types"

The link diagnostics
====================

   IceTERM has a link diagnostics display mode.  If you are installing a
new modem or serial port and want to see what's happening on the serial
link you can add the tool type @{b}LINK@{ub} to the IceTERM icon.  This will add
an extra two lines of information to the main control pannel. The top
line tells you about the data you are sending to the BBS and the bottom
line tells you about the data being received from the BBS.  For example
you might see:

     SENT P      67 N   3 C   2
     RCVD P     332 N   5 C   6 O   1

which means that you have sent the BBS 67 packets of data and IceTERM
has received 332 packets from the BBS.  Also, the BBS encountered
problems with some of the packets you sent it, in fact 3 did not make
it through intact (and were NAKed), the BBS sent 6 check packets to
find out what the status on some packets it sent you was, while IceTERM
sent the BBS 2 check packets because the BBS did not acknowledge
receipt of two data packets fast enough.  In the packets the terminal
received from the BBS there were 5 that it had to ask for a
retransmission on (because they were damaged), one of these IceTERM
suspects was damaged by a serial port overrun(1).  If you have
everything set up properly you should get a display like:

     SENT P      67 N   0 C   0
     RCVD P     332 N   0 C   0 O   0

note that things like the data cache being enabled on some '040s and
the serial port being used at too high a speed or too many ports being
used at once or the handshaking in IceTERM or your modem not being set
correctly can all lead to problems...

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  This occurs when the handshaking between the serial port and
computer (at either end) does not work fast enough and a byte or two
gets lost.  This seems to be the most common sort of serial port error.


@EndNode

@Node "Tooltype bugs" "iceterm.guide/Tooltype bugs"
@Prev "LINK"
@Toc "Tool types"

Bugs
====

   Users of older versions of WorkBench quite often come across a bug
in WorkBench in which two tool types keep getting merged into one when
they attempt to edit them.  The only known cure for this is to get a
copy of a more recent version of the @{b}icon.library@{ub} and @{b}info.library@{ub}. If
a you find that this does not fix the problem, reboot the system using
a WorkBench with those newer libraries on it.  This is fixed under
AmigaDOS 2.0.  Under AmigaDOS 2.0 you may experience a problem with
snapshot not writing all its tool types to the icon, see
@{"Problems snapshotting" Link "Problems snapshotting"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Encryption" "iceterm.guide/Encryption"
@Next "Technical Information"
@Prev "Tool types"
@Toc "Main"

Message Encryption
******************

   This chapter addresses the problem of privacy in BBS based
communications.  If you wish to use a BBS to send some confidential
information to another person you should be aware that the the data you
send may be readily visible to other people.  Essentially from the time
you enter your data into your computer to the time it is received by
the intended person your data is at risk.  The greatest area of risk is
while your data is stored on the BBS awaiting delivery to the recipient.

   While your data is on the BBS (and this is true for most BBS
software) there is little or nothing stopping someone who has access to
the BBS machine from copying it, deleting it, altering it or directing
it to another person.  The only way to protect your data from alteration
or render it useless in the event it is copied or directed to some
other party is to encrypt it in some way.  Note that this does not
protect you in the event someone decides to delete your data so that
the recipient never gets it (which might cause you some grief).

   There are a number of freely distributable utilities that you can
use to encrypt a message or file that is to be sent via a BBS's email
system.  There are a few things you might want to consider when
selecting an encryption package.  The first is the degree of security
the package provides, this can be very difficult to evaluate if you
don't have any cryptanalytic experience.  The second is the package's
portability: is it available on different types of machines?  And the
third is what key management facilities does it provide (after all if
you have to make a telephone call to deliver the decryption key why not
just send the message directly to the recipient's modem).

   Fortunately there is one freely distributable encryption package that
addresses the above problems and more.  This package is called PGP
(which stands for Pretty Good Privacy), it is well known and believed
to be of high quality and versions of it are available to run on a
large number of different machines.  PGP also provides facilities to
sign a message or file (to prove it came from you) and to verify these
signatures.

   The centerpiece of PGP is its use of the RSA public key algorithm.
This system allows you to create an encryption key in two parts, one
secret and one public.  You give the public key to anyone, and with it
they can encrypt messages and files for you such that the only way to
decrypt them is to use the secret key.  This technique solves the
previously discussed problem of how to safely send the decryption key
to the recipient.

   The user profile feature (see @{"User profiles" Link "User profiles"}) of the IceBBS email
system can be used as a place to publish your public key so that others
can download it to send you encrypted mail or files.

   When publishing your public key it is a good idea to provide it in
the armoured ASCII form.  You can then include it directly in your user
profile or insert it into the text of any message you might send.  To
generate a key in this form use a command like:

     pgp -kxa "your name" file.dat

then you just insert the contents of @{b}file.dat@{ub} into your user profile.

   Some networks (in particular FidoNet) have rules restricting the use
of encrypted messages.  If you experience problems sending encrypted
mail you should contact your sysop for help.

   IceOLR includes some built in support for PGP to help you collect
keys, test the signatures of signed messages and sign the messages you
post.


@EndNode

@Node "Technical Information" "iceterm.guide/Technical Information"
@Next "Multitasking"
@Prev "Encryption"
@Toc "Main"

Technical Information
*********************

   This chapter contains some miscellaneous technical information that
might be of interest to various users of IceTERM.  The items included
here are all based on answers to questions that users have asked from
time to time on my BBS.


@EndNode

@Node "Multitasking" "iceterm.guide/Multitasking"
@Next "040 support"
@Prev "Technical Information"
@Toc "Main"

Multitasking
============

   IceTERM is actually a family of programs contained in a single
executable that multitask together as needed.  The most important
program (from the point of view of reliable data transfer) is the
@{i}protocol@{ui}, it runs at the highest priority.  The next is the MUX(1) (it
decides who gets what from the protocol), it runs one priority level
below the protocol process.  Below the MUX are the the various user
interface modules (which also do the disk or user I/O), these all run
one priority level below the MUX (hence, two levels below the
protocol). Connecting these are linked lists (often in the form of Exec
messages queued at Exec message ports) containing the queued data.

   For example, when you start something from the WorkBench it starts at
priority 1, so the protocol runs at 1, the MUX at 0 and the other tasks
at -1.

   When you started @{b}LHARC@{ub}ing (or @{b}LZ@{ub}eding) from a CLI at the default
priority of zero, you are starting a @{i}very@{ui} compute intensive operation,
in fact @{b}LZ@{ub} consumes all the CPU that the protocol does not use and
completely starves the MUX and other tasks since it is running at a
higher priority than they are.  While you have free RAM this is not a
problem for IceTERM, as it just adds the data to the queue between the
MUX and protocol.  With something like @{b}LZ@{ub} or @{b}LHARC@{ub} it is best to run
them at a lower priority (-5 is good and safe), they will still finish
in about the same time, but other tasks can get to run if they need to.
The @{b}PRIORITY@{ub} tool type can be used to adjust IceTERM's priority, see
@{"Task priority" Link "Task priority"}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  MUX is short for multiplexer.


@EndNode

@Node "040 support" "iceterm.guide/040 support"
@Next "Direct Updates"
@Prev "Multitasking"
@Toc "Main"

68040 Machines
==============

   IceTERM flushs the 68040 data cache properly when it spawns
sub-processes.  What this means is that it is safe for you to leave the
@{i}COPYBACK@{ui} mode on when running IceTERM on an '040 equipped Amiga.


@EndNode

